{"title_page": "Celypha woodiana", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of moth}}\n<!--{{Speciesbox\n| name = Mistletoe marble\n| image = File:49.165 BF1066 Celypha woodiana, larva (14148253061).jpg\n| taxon = Celypha woodiana\n| authority = (Barrett, 1882)\n}} -->\n\n{{Taxobox\n| image = File:49.165 BF1066 Celypha woodiana, larva (14148253061).jpg\n| image_width = 250px\n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=''Celypha woodiana'' (Barrett, 1882) |url=https://fauna-eu.org/cdm_dataportal/taxon/b418329c-0e01-4680-9c11-964e508c7d94 |website=Fauna Europaea |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>ordo = [[Lepidoptera]]\n| zoodivisio = [[Ditrysia]]\n| zoosectio = [[Cossina]]\n| familia = [[Tortricidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Celypha]]\n''| species = '''''C. Woodiana'''''\n| binomial = ''Celypha woodiana''\n| binomial_authority = (Barrett, 1882)\n| synonyms =\n* ''Brachytaenia woodiana'' <small>(Barrett, 1882</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Celypha woodiana''''' is a [[moth]] of the family [[Tortricidae]] found in Europe.\n\n==Description==\nWingspan c. 17mm. The moths fly in July and August and can be found resting on tree trunks during the day. They later come to [[Moth trap|light]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kimber |first1=Ian |title=49.165 BF1066 ''Celypha woodiana'' (Barrett, 1882) |url=https://ukmoths.org.uk/species/celypha-woodiana/ |website=UKmoths |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Ova\nEggs can be found on mistletoe in September and October.<ref name=ukmoths>{{cite book |last1=Emmet |first1=A M |authorlink1=A. Maitland Emmet |title=A Field Guide to the Smaller British Lepidoptera |date=1988 |publisher=[[British Entomological and Natural History Society]]] |location=London |page=170 |edition=Second}}</ref>\n\n;Larva\nLarvae can be found from September to May in a [[Leaf mine|mine]]. The initial mine is inconspicuous as a brown, narrow, lower-surface corridor and the larva can leave the mine and start a new one elsewhere. In April and May the larva make a full depth transpaent blotch with most of the [[frass]] ejected. The mines can be difficult to find as the leaf falls from the plant.<ref name=\"ppe\">{{cite web |last1=Ellis |first1=W N |title=''Celypha woodiana'' (Barrett, 1882) mistletoe marble |url=https://bladmineerders.nl/parasites/animalia/arthropoda/insecta/lepidoptera/ditrysia/apoditrysia/tortricoidea/tortricidae/olethreutinae/olethreutini/celypha/celypha-woodiana/ |website=Plant Parasites of Europe |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThe moth is found from [[Great Britian]] to the [[Ukraine]] but is absent (or yet to be found) in some countries.<ref name=\"ppe\"/>\n\nIn Great Britain the moth is subject to a [[United Kingdom Biodiversity Action Plan|Biodiversity action plan]] (UK BAP species).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sterling |first1=Phil |last2=Parsons |first2=Mark |title=Field Guide to the Micro Moths of Great Britain and Ireland |date=2012 |publisher=British Wildlife Publishing |location=Gillingham, Dorset |isbn=978 0 9564902 1 6 |page=26}}</ref> It is rare and confined to mature apple [[orchard]]s in southern England and the south [[Midlands]].<ref name=ukmoths/> In 2019 the moth was found in [[Wales]] for the first tilme, with leaf mines and a larva at [[Magor Marsh]] ({{lang-cy|Cors Magwyr}}), a [[Gwent Wildlife Trust]] nature reserve.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Rare moths found in Wales |work=Butterfly |issue=132 |publisher=[[Butterfly Conservation]] |date=2019 |page=8}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q13458703}}\n\n[[Category:Olethreutini]]\n[[Category:Tortricidae of Europe]]\n[[Category:Moths described in 1882]]\n\n\n{{Olethreutinae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of moth}}\n<!--{{Speciesbox\n| name = Mistletoe marble\n| image = File:49.165 BF1066 Celypha woodiana, larva (14148253061).jpg\n| taxon = Celypha woodiana\n| authority = (Barrett, 1882)\n}} -->\n\n{{Taxobox\n| image = File:49.165 BF1066 Celypha woodiana, larva (14148253061).jpg\n| image_width = 250px\n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=''Celypha woodiana'' (Barrett, 1882) |url=https://fauna-eu.org/cdm_dataportal/taxon/b418329c-0e01-4680-9c11-964e508c7d94 |website=Fauna Europaea |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>ordo = [[Lepidoptera]]\n| zoodivisio = [[Ditrysia]]\n| zoosectio = [[Cossina]]\n| familia = [[Tortricidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Celypha]]\n''| species = '''''C. Woodiana'''''\n| binomial = ''Celypha woodiana''\n| binomial_authority = (Barrett, 1882)\n| synonyms =\n* ''Brachytaenia woodiana'' <small>(Barrett, 1882</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Celypha woodiana''''' is a [[moth]] of the family [[Tortricidae]] found in Europe.\n\n==Description==\nWingspan c. 17mm. The moths fly in July and August and can be found resting on tree trunks during the day. They later come to [[Moth trap|light]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kimber |first1=Ian |title=49.165 BF1066 ''Celypha woodiana'' (Barrett, 1882) |url=https://ukmoths.org.uk/species/celypha-woodiana/ |website=UKmoths |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Ova\nEggs can be found on mistletoe in September and October.<ref name=ukmoths>{{cite book |last1=Emmet |first1=A M |authorlink1=A. Maitland Emmet |title=A Field Guide to the Smaller British Lepidoptera |date=1988 |publisher=[[British Entomological and Natural History Society]]] |location=London |page=170 |edition=Second}}</ref>\n\n;Larvae\nLarvae can be found from September to May in a [[Leaf mine|mine]]. The initial mine is inconspicuous as a brown, narrow, lower-surface corridor and the larva can leave the mine and start a new one elsewhere. In April and May the larva make a full depth transpaent blotch with most of the [[frass]] ejected. The mines can be difficult to find as the leaf falls from the plant.<ref name=\"ppe\">{{cite web |last1=Ellis |first1=W N |title=''Celypha woodiana'' (Barrett, 1882) mistletoe marble |url=https://bladmineerders.nl/parasites/animalia/arthropoda/insecta/lepidoptera/ditrysia/apoditrysia/tortricoidea/tortricidae/olethreutinae/olethreutini/celypha/celypha-woodiana/ |website=Plant Parasites of Europe |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThe moth is found from [[Great Britian]] to the [[Ukraine]] but is absent (or yet to be found) in some countries.<ref name=\"ppe\"/>\n\nIn Great Britain the moth is subject to a [[United Kingdom Biodiversity Action Plan|Biodiversity action plan]] (UK BAP species).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sterling |first1=Phil |last2=Parsons |first2=Mark |title=Field Guide to the Micro Moths of Great Britain and Ireland |date=2012 |publisher=British Wildlife Publishing |location=Gillingham, Dorset |isbn=978 0 9564902 1 6 |page=26}}</ref> It is rare and confined to mature apple [[orchard]]s in southern England and the south [[Midlands]].<ref name=ukmoths/> In 2019 the moth was found in [[Wales]] for the first tilme, with leaf mines and a larva at [[Magor Marsh]] ({{lang-cy|Cors Magwyr}}), a [[Gwent Wildlife Trust]] nature reserve.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Rare moths found in Waes |work=Butterfly |issue=132 |publisher=[[Butterfly Conservation]] |date=2019 |page=8}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q13458703}}\n\n[[Category:Olethreutini]]\n[[Category:Tortricidae of Europe]]\n[[Category:Moths described in 1882]]\n\n\n{{Olethreutinae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jowaninpensans", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celypha_woodiana"}
{"title_page": "Doom (franchise)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| image          = File:Doom \u2013 Game\u2019s logo.svg\n\nAIzaSyBY8UG9e2CekI51BemVOfkAPnmPEe5rkXo\n\n| creator        = {{plainlist|\n*[[John Carmack]]\n*[[John Romero]]\n*[[Adrian Carmack]] \n*[[Kevin Cloud]]\n*[[Tom Hall]]}}\n| origin         = [[Doom (1993 video game)|''Doom'']] (1993)\n| owner          = [[ZeniMax Media]]\n| books          = \n| novels         = [[#Novels|List of novels]]\n| short_stories  = \n| comics         = ''Doom'' (1996)\n| magazines      =\n| films          = [[#Films|List of films]]\n| shorts         =\n| tv             = \n| atv            = \n| tv_specials    = \n| tv_films       = \n| dtv            =\n| plays          =\n| musicals       = \n| games          = ''[[Doom: The Boardgame]]'' (2004)\n| rpgs           =\n| vgs            = [[#Games|List of video games]]\n| radio          =\n| soundtracks    = \n| music          =\n| toys           =\n| otherlabel1    = \n| otherdata1     = \n| otherlabel2    =\n| otherdata2     =\n| otherlabel3    =\n| otherdata3     =\n| website        = \n}}\n\n'''''Doom''''' (stylized as '''''DooM''''', and later '''''DOOM''''') is a [[video game]] series and [[media franchise]] created by [[John Carmack]], [[John Romero]], [[Adrian Carmack]], [[Kevin Cloud]], and [[Tom Hall]].<ref name=\"IGNvideo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/videos/2013/12/10/we-play-doom-with-john-romero |title=We Play Doom with John Romero |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=2013-12-10 |accessdate=2018-02-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111052825/http://www.ign.com/videos/2013/12/10/we-play-doom-with-john-romero |archivedate=2018-01-11 |url-status=live}}</ref> The series focuses on the exploits of [[Doomguy|an unnamed space marine]] operating under the auspices of the Union Aerospace Corporation (UAC), who fights hordes of demons and the undead.\n\n''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' is considered one of the pioneering first-person shooter games, introducing to [[IBM]]-compatible computers features such as [[3D computer graphics|3D graphics]], third-dimension spatiality, networked [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] gameplay, and support for player-created modifications with the [[Doom modding|''Doom'' WAD]] format. Since its debut in 1993, over 10 million copies of games in the ''Doom'' series have been sold; the series has spawned numerous sequels, novels, comic books, board games, and films adaptations.\n\n==Games==\n===Main series===\n{{Video game titles|\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom (1993 video game)\n| title      = Doom\n| date       = {{vgrelease|NA|December 10, 1993|EU|1993}}\n| multiplereleasedates = no\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 1993 \u2013 [[MS-DOS]]<br/>1994 \u2013 [[32X|Sega 32X]], [[Atari Jaguar]]<br/>1995 \u2013 [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]<br/>1996 \u2013 [[3DO Interactive Multiplayer|3DO]]<br/>1997 \u2013 [[Sega Saturn]]<br/>1998 \u2013 [[Acorn Archimedes]]<br/>2001 \u2013 [[Game Boy Advance]]<br/>2006 \u2013 [[Xbox 360]] (original Activision release)<br/>2009 \u2013 [[iOS]]<br/>2012 \u2013 Xbox 360 (Bethesda re-release)<br/>2019 \u2013 [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| platform   = \n| notes      = * Originally developed by [[id Software]] and published by [[GT Interactive Software]].\n* On April 30, 1995, an updated version of the game, ''The Ultimate Doom'', was released; it included a new fourth episode, \"Thy Flesh Consumed\", in addition to the original three episodes.\n* On May 22, 2019, John Romero released an unofficial 5th episode to commemorate the game's 25th anniversary titled \"Sigil.\"\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom II\n| title      = Doom II: Hell on Earth\n| date    