\n| platform   = \n| notes      = *Originally developed and published by [[Midway Games]].\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom 3\n| title      = Doom 3\n| date       = {{vgrelease|NA|August 3, 2004|EU|August 13, 2004}}\n| multiplereleasedates = yes\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2004 \u2013 [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Linux]]<br/>2005 \u2013 [[OS X]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]]\n| platform   = \n| notes      = *Originally developed by id Software and published by [[Activision]].\n* The Xbox version contains the full versions of ''The Ultimate Doom'' and ''Doom II'', but they are only available in the limited collector's edition.\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom 3: Resurrection of Evil\n| title      = Doom 3: Resurrection of Evil\n| date       = {{vgrelease|NA|April 3, 2005|EU|April 8, 2005}}\n| multiplereleasedates = yes\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2005 \u2013 Microsoft Windows, Linux, Xbox\n| notes      = * Developed by Nerve Software and published by Activision.\n* Expansion pack for ''Doom 3'', which requires ''Doom 3'' to play on Microsoft Windows.\n* The Xbox version does not require ''Doom 3'' to play and also contains the full versions of ''The Ultimate Doom'', ''Doom II'', and ''Master Levels for Doom II''.\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom 3: BFG Edition\n| title      = Doom 3: BFG Edition\n| date       = {{vgrelease|NA|October 16, 2012|AUS|October 18, 2012|EU|October 19, 2012}}\n| multiplereleasedates = yes\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2012 \u2013 Microsoft Windows, [[PlayStation 3]], Xbox 360<br/>2015 \u2013 [[Nvidia Shield]]<br/>2019 \u2013 Nintendo Switch, PlayStation 4, Xbox One\n| notes      = * Originally developed by id Software and published by [[Bethesda Softworks]].\n* HD remasters of ''Doom 3'' and its expansion ''Resurrection of Evil''. A new expansion pack is also included in the game titled ''The Lost Mission''.\n* The game also includes the full versions of ''The Ultimate Doom'' and ''Doom II'', as well as the ''No Rest for the Living'' expansion pack by Nerve Software.\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom (2016 video game)\n| title      = Doom\n| date       = {{vgrelease|WW|May 13, 2016}}\n| multiplereleasedates = no\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2016 \u2013 Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, Xbox One<br/>2017 \u2013 Nintendo Switch\n| notes      = * Developed by id Software and published by Bethesda Softworks.\n* Multiplayer co-developed with [[Certain Affinity]].\n* SnapMap co-developed with Escalation Studios.\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom Eternal\n| title      = Doom Eternal\n| date       = {{Vgrelease|WW|March 20, 2020}}\n| multiplereleasedates = no\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2020 \u2013 Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, Xbox One, Nintendo Switch, [[Google Stadia|Stadia]]\n| notes      = * Developed by id Software and published by Bethesda Softworks.\n* Sequel to the 2016 reboot.\n}}\n}}\n\n===Spin-offs===\n{{Video game titles|\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom RPG\n| title      = Doom RPG\n| date       = {{vgrelease|WW|September 13, 2005}}\n| multiplereleasedates = no\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2005 \u2013 [[Mobile game|Mobile]]\n| platform   = \n| notes      = * Developed by Fountainhead Entertainment and published by [[JAMDAT Mobile]].\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom Resurrection\n| title      = Doom Resurrection\n| date       = {{vgrelease|WW|June 26, 2009}}\n| multiplereleasedates = no\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2009 \u2013 iOS\n| platform   = \n| notes      = * Developed by Escalation Studios and published by id Software.\n* Set in parallel to ''Doom 3''.\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom II RPG\n| title      = Doom II RPG\n| date       = {{vgrelease|WW|November 23, 2009}}\n| multiplereleasedates = no\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2009 \u2013 [[Java Platform, Micro Edition|Java ME]], [[BlackBerry OS]]<br/>2010 \u2013 [[Windows Mobile]], iOS\n| platform   = \n| notes      = * Developed and published by id Software.\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom VFR\n| title      = Doom VFR\n| date       = {{vgrelease|WW|December 1, 2017}}\n| multiplereleasedates = no\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2017 \u2013 [[Windows Mixed Reality]], [[HTC Vive]], [[PS VR]]\n| platform   = \n| notes      = {{#invoke:list|bulleted|Developed by id Software and published by Bethesda Softworks.|Virtual reality game set during the events of the 2016 reboot of ''Doom''.}}\n}}\n}}\n\n==Common elements==\n{{expand section|date=November 2014}} \nThe ''Doom'' video games consist of first-person shooters in which the player controls an unnamed space marine also referred to as ''[[Doomguy]]''. The player has to battle the forces of [[Hell]], consisting of [[demon]]s and the [[undead]]. In the games, the player's character will often go back and forth through hell. ''Doom II: Hell on Earth'' follows after the events in ''Doom'', the player once again assumes the role of the unnamed space marine. After returning from Hell, the player finds that [[Earth]] has also been invaded by the demons, who have killed billions of people.<ref name=\"classicdoomtext\">{{cite web|url=http://www.classicdoom.com/doomtext.htm#doom2|accessdate=June 25, 2011|title=DOOMTEXT.HTM: Storylines for Doom, Doom II, Final Doom, Doom 64|author=Transcripts from printed manuals by Ledmeister}}</ref>\n\n==Development and history==\n{{Video game timeline\n|subtitle = Main series in bold\n|range1 = 1993\u2013\n|range1_color = #ff0000 #aa0000\n|1993 = '''''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'''''\n|1994 = '''''[[Doom II: Hell on Earth]]''''' \n|1995 = ''[[Master Levels for Doom II]]'', ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|The Ultimate Doom]]''\n|1996 = ''[[Final Doom]]''\n|1997 = ''[[Doom 64]]''\n|2004 = '''''[[Doom 3]]'''''\n|2005 = ''[[Doom 3: Resurrection of Evil]]'', ''[[Doom RPG]]''\n|2009 = ''[[Doom Resurrection]]'', ''[[Doom II RPG]]''\n|2010 = ''[[Doom II: No Rest for the Living]]''\n|2012 = ''[[Doom 3: BFG Edition]]''\n|2016 = '''''[[Doom (2016 video game)|Doom]]'''''\n|2017 = ''[[Doom (2016 video game)|Doom VFR]]''\n|2020 = '''''[[Doom Eternal]]'''''\n}}\nThe development of the original ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' started in 1992, when [[John Carmack]] developed a new game engine, the [[Doom engine]], while the rest of the id Software team finished the ''[[Wolfenstein 3D]]'' prequel, ''[[Spear of Destiny (video game)|Spear of Destiny]]''.\n\n''[[Doom II: Hell on Earth]]'' was released in 1994, followed by two other official releases based on its version of the Doom engine: ''[[Master Levels for Doom II]]'' in 1995, and ''[[Final Doom]]'' in 1996.\n\n''[[Doom 64]]'' was released in 1997, developed by [[Midway Games]] and supervised by id Software.<ref>{{cite web | author=IGN staff | date=November 11, 1996 | title=''Doom 64'' News | url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1996/11/12/doom-64-news | publisher=[[IGN]] | accessdate=July 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''[[Doom 3]]'' was announced in 2000. A reboot to the original ''Doom'', it uses new graphics technology. ''Doom 3'' was hyped to provide as large a leap in realism and interactivity as the original game and helped renew interest in the franchise when it was released in 2004. ''Doom 3'' had its own expansion pack released in 2005, titled ''[[Doom 3: Resurrection of Evil]]''.\n\nAfter the ''Doom 4'' project development was scrapped in 2013, id Software's [[Tim Willits]] said that the next game in the ''Doom'' series was still the team's focus, but it has not been confirmed to be titled ''Doom 4''.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://multiplayerblog.mtv.com/2013/08/05/id-software-and-bethesdas-cancelled-doom-4-just-wasnt-doom-enough |title=id Software and Bethesda's Cancelled 'Doom 4' Just Wasn't 'Doom' Enough |publisher=Multiplayerblog.mtv.com |date=August 5, 2013 |accessdate=November 29, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104102655/http://multiplayerblog.mtv.com/2013/08/05/id-software-and-bethesdas-cancelled-doom-4-just-wasnt-doom-enough |archivedate=November 4, 2013 }}</ref> It was later renamed to simply ''[[Doom (2016 video game)|Doom]]'' in 2014. The game became a second reboot of the series, rather than a continuation or origin story of earlier games and was released in 2016.<ref name=\"Doom 4 Polygon\">{{cite web| title=The new Doom game is just titled 'Doom,' runs on id Tech 6, and more details| url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/7/17/5913883/doom-4-quakecon-reveal| author= Griffin McElroy| date=July 17, 2014| publisher=Polygon| accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA sequel to the 2016 reboot, ''[[Doom Eternal]]'' was released in 2020.\n\n==Other media==\n===Novels===\n{{Main|Doom (novel series)}}\nA [[Doom (novel series)|set of four novels]] based on ''Doom'' were written by [[Dafydd ab Hugh]] and [[Brad Linaweaver]]. The books, listed in order, are titled ''Knee Deep in the Dead'', ''Hell on Earth'', ''Infernal Sky'' and ''Endgame''. All were published between June 1995 and January 1996 by [[Pocket Books]]. The unnamed Marine is called \"Flynn Taggart\" or \"Fly\" in the novels. The first two books feature recognizable locations and situations from the first two games.\n\nIn 2008, a new series of ''Doom'' novels by [[Matthew J. Costello]], an author who had worked on the story and scripts for ''Doom 3'' and ''Resurrection of Evil'', were published. The series of books aim to novelize the story of ''Doom 3'', with the first installment, ''[[Doom 3: Worlds on Fire|Worlds on Fire]]'', published on February 26, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simonsays.com/content/book.cfm?tab=23&pid=586443 |title=Doom 3: Worlds on Fire |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |accessdate=July 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206170046/http://www.simonsays.com/content/book.cfm?tab=23&pid=586443 |archivedate=December 6, 2008  }}</ref> The second book in the series, ''[[Doom 3: Maelstrom|Maelstrom]]'', was released in March 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simonsays.com/content/book.cfm?tab=1&pid=635379&er=9781416553854 |title=Doom 3: Maestrom |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |accessdate=September 11, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206170041/http://www.simonsays.com/content/book.cfm?tab=1&pid=635379&er=9781416553854 |archivedate=December 6, 2008  }}</ref>\n\n===Comic book===\nAn one-shot comic book written by Steve Behling and Michael Stewart with art by [[Tom Grindberg]] was released in May 1996 by [[Marvel Comics]] as a giveaway for a video game convention.\n\n===Board game===\nIn 2004, a board game designed by [[Kevin Wilson (game designer)|Kevin Wilson]] and published by [[Fantasy Flight Games]] titled ''[[Doom: The Boardgame]]'' was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fantasyflightgames.com/doomproducts.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828122930/http://fantasyflightgames.com/va08.html |archivedate=August 28, 2008 |title=Doom |publisher=Fantasy Flight Games |accessdate=April 3, 2011}}</ref> For the 20th anniversary of the series, the [[Game-Art-HQ]] community created an art tribute with 20 illustrations of the characters from the game.\n\n===Films===\n====''Doom'' (2005)====\n{{Main|Doom (film)}}\nIn 2005, [[Universal Pictures]] released the first live-action film adaptation, titled ''[[Doom (film)|Doom]]'', which starred [[Dwayne Johnson]].\n\n====''Doom: Annihilation'' (2019)====\n{{Main|Doom: Annihilation}}\nIn 2019, Universal released a second live-action film adaptation [[direct-to-video]], titled ''[[Doom: Annihilation]]''.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game series reviews\n| updated = March 25, 2020\n| game1 = [[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom (1993)]]\n| gr1 = (PC) 86.67%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/524287-doom-1993/index.html |title=''Doom (1993)'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(PS1) 84.00%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/ps/919060-doom/index.html |title=''Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(iOS) 82.86%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/iphone/978641-doom-classic/index.html |title=''Doom Classic'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(X360) 80.16%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/xbox360/935829-doom/index.html |title=''Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(32X) 80.00%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/sega32x/563223-doom/index.html |title=''Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(GBA) 79.87%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/gba/531288-doom/index.html |title=''Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(JAG) 78.75%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/jaguar/563365-doom/index.html |title=''Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(SNES) 54.05%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/snes/588285-doom/index.html |title=''Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(SAT) 47.00%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/saturn/197140-doom/index.html |title=''Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n| mc1 = (iOS) 84<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/doom-classic |title=''Doom Classic'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(X360) 82<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/doom |title=''Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(GBA) 81<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/doom |title=''Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n| game2 = [[Doom II: Hell on Earth]]\n| gr2 = (PC) 95.00%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/197142-doom-ii/index.html |title=''Doom II'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(X360) 77.36%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/xbox360/971665-doom-ii/index.html |title=''Doom II'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(GBA) 76.64%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/gba/562057-doom-ii/index.html |title=''Doom II'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n| mc2 = (PC) 83<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/doom-ii |title=''Doom II'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(X360) 77<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/doom-ii |title=''Doom II'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(GBA) 77<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/doom-ii |title=''Doom II'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n| game3 = [[Final Doom]]\n| gr3 = (PS1) 80.71%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/ps/562797-final-doom/index.html |title=''Final Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(MAC) 60.00%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/mac/581781-final-doom/index.html |title=''Final Doom'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(PC) 56