 |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n| mc10 = (PS3) 67<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/doom-3-bfg-edition |title=''Doom 3: BFG Edition'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(X360) 67<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/doom-3-bfg-edition |title=''Doom 3: BFG Edition'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(PC) 59<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/doom-3-bfg-edition |title=''Doom 3: BFG Edition'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n| game11 = [[Doom (2016 video game)|Doom (2016)]]\n| gr11 = (XONE) 89.04%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/xboxone/819504-doom/index.html |title=''DOOM'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(PS4) 85.82%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/ps4/819505-doom/index.html |title=''DOOM'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(PC) 85.38%<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/805860-doom/index.html |title=''DOOM'' Reviews |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n| mc11 = (XONE) 87<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/doom |title=''DOOM'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(PS4) 85<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/doom |title=''DOOM'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref><br/>(PC) 85<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/doom |title=''DOOM'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n| game12 = [[Doom Eternal]]\n| gr12 = \u2014\n| mc12 = (XONE) 89<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/doom-eternal |title=''Doom Eternal'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref><br/>(PS4) 87<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/doom-eternal |title=''Doom Eternal'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref><br/>(PC) 90<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/doom-eternal |title=''Doom Eternal'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nIn 1996, ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' ranked the series as the 19th top game of all time, for how \"despite the hundreds of copycat titles, no one has ever been able to equal id's original, pulsing classic.\"<ref>''Next Generation'' 21 (September 1996), p.64.</ref>\n\nThe series' unnamed protagonist, a marine, has had a mostly positive reception. In 2009, [[GameDaily]] included \"the Marine\" on its list of \"ten game heroes who fail at the simple stuff\" for his inability to look up and down in the original series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/character-flaws-ten-game-heroes-that-cant-do-easy-things/?page=7 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425051056/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/character-flaws-ten-game-heroes-that-cant-do-easy-things/?page=7 |archivedate=April 25, 2009 |title=Character Flaws: Ten Game Heroes Who Fail at the Simple Stuff Gallery by GameDail |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=April 25, 2009 |accessdate=October 15, 2012}}</ref> [[UGO Networks]] ranked him fourth on its 2012's list of best [[silent protagonist]]s in video games, noting his courage to continue in silence even when he faces Hell's army.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ugo.com/games/best-silent-protagonists-in-video-games?page=2 | title=Best Silent Protagonists In Video Games | date=March 15, 2012 | author=Basile, Sal | publisher=[[UGO Networks]] | accessdate=July 7, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514020143/http://www.ugo.com/games/best-silent-protagonists-in-video-games?page=2 | archivedate=May 14, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' ranked Doomguy at number 16 on its list of the greatest soldiers in video games for being \"the original video game space marine\" and \"one of the classic silent protagonists\".<ref>Chad Hunter, Michael Rougeau, [http://www.complex.com/video-games/2013/05/the-50-greatest-soldiers-in-video-games/doomguy The 50 Greatest Soldiers In Video Games], Complex.com, May 25, 2013.</ref> Both [[CraveOnline]] and VGRC ranked him the fifth most \"badass\" male character in the video game's history.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.craveonline.com/gaming/articles/155562-top-10-biggest-gaming-bad-asses | title=Top 10 Biggest Gaming Bad Asses | date=October 17, 2007 | publisher=[[CraveOnline]] | accessdate=July 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.vgrc.net/2010/06/the-top-10-male-badasses-in-gaming.html | title=The Top 10 Male Badasses in Gaming | author=McCabe, Sean | date=June 17, 2010 | publisher=VGRC | accessdate=July 28, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005021811/http://www.vgrc.net/2010/06/the-top-10-male-badasses-in-gaming.html | archive-date=October 5, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\n=== Sales ===\nThe original ''Doom'' sold 2-3 million physical copies<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=znUoeG5ulvQC&lpg=PA14&dq=doom%20copies%20sold&pg=PA14#v=onepage&q=doom%20copies%20sold&f=false |title=Networking and Online Games: Understanding and Engineering Multiplayer Internet Games |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |author1=Armitage, Grenville |author2=Claypool, Mark |author3=Branch, Philip |year=2006 |location=Chichester, England |pages=14 |isbn=0470030461 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221020129/https://books.google.com/books?id=znUoeG5ulvQC&lpg=PA14&dq=doom%20copies%20sold&pg=PA14 |archivedate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> and 1.15 million shareware copies<Ref>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000302112243/http://pc.ign.com/news/11728.html | url=http://pc.ign.com:80/news/11728.html | title=PC Data Top Games of All Time | date=November 1, 1999 | author=IGN Staff | work=[[IGN]] | archivedate=March 2, 2000 | url-status=dead | access-date=May 31, 2018 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> from its 1993 release up through 1999. ''Doom II'' sold 1.55 million copies of all types in the United States during the same period,<Ref>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000302112243/http://pc.ign.com/news/11728.html | url=http://pc.ign.com:80/news/11728.html | title=PC Data Top Games of All Time | date=November 1, 1999 | author=IGN Staff | work=[[IGN]] | archivedate=March 2, 2000 | url-status=dead | access-date=May 31, 2018 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> with about a quarter of that number also sold in Europe,<ref>{{cite book|last=Kushner |first=David |title=[[Masters of Doom|Masters of Doom: How Two Guys Created An Empire And Transformed Pop Culture]] |publisher=[[Random House]] |at=182, 210 |year=2003 |isbn=0-375-50524-5}}</ref> a total of some 5-6 million sales for the original duology. ''Doom 3'' sold 3.5 million copies along with many copies of the expansion pack ''Resurrection of Evil'' from its 2004 release up through 2007, making it the most successful game in the series at that point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/docs/press/010710_id_carmack_emmys.x |title=John Carmack and id Software's pioneering development work in 3D game engines recognized with two technology Emmy awards |website=[[Shacknews]] |date=January 9, 2007 |accessdate=July 15, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705061409/http://www.shacknews.com/docs/press/010710_id_carmack_emmys.x |archivedate=July 5, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The sales of ''Doom 64'' were not disclosed. \n\nThe 2016 reboot sold over 2 million copies on the PC alone from its May 2016 release up to July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wholesgame.com/news/doom-sells-2-million-copies-on-pc/|title=Doom sells 2 million copies on PC|date=July 19, 2017|accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DOOMgames}}\n{{id Software}}\n{{ZeniMax Media}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doom (Series)}}\n[[Category:Doom (series)| ]]\n[[Category:ZeniMax Media franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 1993]]\n[[Category:Horror media franchises]]\n[[Category:Science fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Religion in science fiction]]\n[[Category:Space warfare in fiction]]\n[[Category:Hell in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Video games about demons]]\n[[Category:Undead in popular culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| image          = File:Doom \u2013 Game\u2019s logo.svg\n| creator        = {{plainlist|\n*[[John Carmack]]\n*[[John Romero]]\n*[[Adrian Carmack]] \n*[[Kevin Cloud]]\n*[[Tom Hall]]}}\n| origin         = [[Doom (1993 video game)|''Doom'']] (1993)\n| owner          = [[ZeniMax Media]]\n| books          = \n| novels         = [[#Novels|List of novels]]\n| short_stories  = \n| comics         = ''Doom'' (1996)\n| magazines      =\n| films          = [[#Films|List of films]]\n| shorts         =\n| tv             = \n| atv            = \n| tv_specials    = \n| tv_films       = \n| dtv            =\n| plays          =\n| musicals       = \n| games          = ''[[Doom: The Boardgame]]'' (2004)\n| rpgs           =\n| vgs            = [[#Games|List of video games]]\n| radio          =\n| soundtracks    = \n| music          =\n| toys           =\n| otherlabel1    = \n| otherdata1     = \n| otherlabel2    =\n| otherdata2     =\n| otherlabel3    =\n| otherdata3     =\n| website        = \n}}\n\n'''''Doom''''' (stylized as '''''DooM''''', and later '''''DOOM''''') is a [[video game]] series and [[media franchise]] created by [[John Carmack]], [[John Romero]], [[Adrian Carmack]], [[Kevin Cloud]], and [[Tom Hall]].<ref name=\"IGNvideo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/videos/2013/12/10/we-play-doom-with-john-romero |title=We Play Doom with John Romero |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=2013-12-10 |accessdate=2018-02-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111052825/http://www.ign.com/videos/2013/12/10/we-play-doom-with-john-romero |archivedate=2018-01-11 |url-status=live}}</ref> The series focuses on the exploits of [[Doomguy|an unnamed space marine]] operating under the auspices of the Union Aerospace Corporation (UAC), who fights hordes of demons and the undead.\n\n''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' is considered one of the pioneering first-person shooter games, introducing to [[IBM]]-compatible computers features such as [[3D computer graphics|3D graphics]], third-dimension spatiality, networked [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] gameplay, and support for player-created modifications with the [[Doom modding|''Doom'' WAD]] format. Since its debut in 1993, over 10 million copies of games in the ''Doom'' series have been sold; the series has spawned numerous sequels, novels, comic books, board games, and films adaptations.\n\n==Games==\n===Main series===\n{{Video game titles|\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom (1993 video game)\n| title      = Doom\n| date       = {{vgrelease|NA|December 10, 1993|EU|1993}}\n| multiplereleasedates = no\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 1993 \u2013 [[MS-DOS]]<br/>1994 \u2013 [[32X|Sega 32X]], [[Atari Jaguar]]<br/>1995 \u2013 [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]<br/>1996 \u2013 [[3DO Interactive Multiplayer|3DO]]<br/>1997 \u2013 [[Sega Saturn]]<br/>1998 \u2013 [[Acorn Archimedes]]<br/>2001 \u2013 [[Game Boy Advance]]<br/>2006 \u2013 [[Xbox 360]] (original Activision release)<br/>2009 \u2013 [[iOS]]<br/>2012 \u2013 Xbox 360 (Bethesda re-release)<br/>2019 \u2013 [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| platform   = \n| notes      = * Originally developed by [[id Software]] and published by [[GT Interactive Software]].\n* On April 30, 1995, an updated version of the game, ''The Ultimate Doom'', was released; it included a new fourth episode, \"Thy Flesh Consumed\", in addition to the original three episodes.\n* On May 22, 2019, John Romero released an unofficial 5th episode to commemorate the game's 25th anniversary titled \"Sigil.\"\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom II\n| title      = Doom II: Hell on Earth\n| date       = {{vgrelease|WW|October 10, 1994}}\n| multiplereleasedates = yes\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 1994 \u2013 MS-DOS<br/>1995 \u2013 [[Mac OS]]<br/>2002 \u2013 Game Boy Advance<br/>2010 \u2013 Xbox 360 (original Activision release)<br/>2012 \u2013 Xbox 360 (Bethesda re-release)<br/>2019 \u2013 Nintendo Switch, PlayStation 4, Xbox One, iOS, Android\n| platform   = \n| notes      = *Originally developed by id Software and published by GT Interactive Software.\n* On December 26, 1995, an expansion pack, ''Master Levels for Doom II'', was released; it included 21 additional levels.\n* On May 26, 2010, an expansion pack, ''Doom II: No Rest for the Living'', was released for the Xbox 360 release of the game, developed by [[Nerve Software]].\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Final Doom\n| title      = Final Doom\n| date       = {{vgrelease|NA|June 17, 1996|EU|1996}}\n| multiplereleasedates = no\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 1996 \u2013 MS-DOS, PlayStation, Mac OS\n| platform   = \n| notes      = * Developed by [[TeamTNT]] and published originally by id Software.\n* ''Final Doom'' is a compilation of two standalone ''Doom II'' modifications, ''TNT: Evilution'' and ''The Plutonia Experiment'', which include full sets of new levels (both of them use the same level structure as ''Doom II'' with 30 regular levels and two secret levels), new graphics and textures, new music (for ''TNT: Evilution''), and new text interlude screens in addition to most of the resources from ''Doom II'' and some from ''Doom''.\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom 64\n| title      = Doom 64\n| date       = {{vgrelease|NA|March 31, 1997|PAL|December 2, 1997}}\n| multiplereleasedates = yes\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 1997 \u2013 [[Nintendo 64]]<br/>2020 \u2013 Microsoft Windows, Nintendo Switch, PlayStation 4, Xbox One (Bethesda re-release)\n| platform   = \n| notes      = *Originally developed and published by [[Midway Games]].\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom 3\n| title      = Doom 3\n| date       = {{vgrelease|NA|August 3, 2004|EU|August 13, 2004}}\n| multiplereleasedates = yes\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2004 \u2013 [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Linux]]<br/>2005 \u2013 [[OS X]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]]\n| platform   = \n| notes      = *Originally developed by id Software and published by [[Activision]].\n* The Xbox version contains the full versions of ''The Ultimate Doom'' and ''Doom II'', but they are only available in the limited collector's edition.\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom 3: Resurrection of Evil\n| title      = Doom 3: Resurrection of Evil\n| date       = {{vgrelease|NA|April 3, 2005|EU|April 8, 2005}}\n| multiplereleasedates = yes\n| canceled   = \n| refs       = \n| release    = 2005 \u2013 Microsoft Windows, Linux, Xbox\n| notes      = * Developed by Nerve Software and published by Activision.\n* Expansion pack for ''Doom 3'', which requires ''Doom 3'' to play on Microsoft Windows.\n* The Xbox version does not require ''Doom 3'' to play and also contains the full versions of ''The Ultimate Doom'', ''Doom II'', and ''Master Levels for Doom II''.\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n| series     = no\n| futuregame = no\n| article    = Doom 3: BFG Edition\n| title      = Doom 