 (of African descent or mixed-race) make up a quarter of the population.<ref name=\"cia.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/mp.html#People|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=Cia.gov|accessdate=2017-08-29}}</ref> . Nowadays, a significant proportion of [[Mauritian Creole people|Creoles]] also have some degree of Indian, White or Chinese lineage. [[Rodrigues|Rodriguais]] & [[Chagossians]] are usually incorporated within the creole ethnic group. Mauritian Creoles form about 30% of the local population.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Franco-Mauritian]]s (Mauritian of [[French people|French]] ancestry) are numbered about 42,000.{{cn|date=April 2020}} [[Franco-Mauritian]]s are the descendants of former French colonists/settlers,  comprising the largest group of people of European origin of the island.<ref>{{harvnb|Eriksen|2004|p=80}}</ref> There is a smaller population of people of British descent living in Mauritius, most of whom have been absorbed within the [[Franco-Mauritian]] community.{{cn|date=April 2020}} There is also a considerable number of white foreign expatriates living in Mauritius, about 8000 are from France and 2000 from South Africa.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nAlong with the French European community, there is a small amount of British expatriates or people of British descent in Mauritius.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/in_depth/brits_abroad/html/africa.stm|title=BBC NEWS {{!}} Special Reports {{!}} Brits Abroad|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/indian-ocean/mp-forrel-uk.htm|title=Mauritius - UK Relations|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThere are approximately 28,000 [[Sino-Mauritian]]s from the [[Hakka people|Hakka]] and other Chinese sub-ethnic/linguistic groups.<ref name=\"Eriksen 1998 82\">{{harvnb|Eriksen|1998|p=82}}</ref>\n\nWhile the government officially groups Mauritians in four ethnic groups: Hindus, Muslims, Chinese and general population, the general population gathers all that don't practice the Hindu or Muslim religion, or are not Chinese by race. Hence general population is the Christian community, which includes whites, coloureds, blacks, and those who have converted to Christianity. The exception to the rule is that the general population does not include the Christian-Chinese, although most practice a mix of Christianity and traditional Chinese religions.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nSmall groups of foreign students from Europe or the Indian Ocean region are also present. Recent years have seen a steady flow of foreign workers into the textile industry (primarily Chinese women), the construction industry (primarily Indian workers), and harbour-related activities (primarily Taiwanese men). Immigration policy does not provoke much debate in Mauritius, and the relative economic stability of the island serves to attract foreign workers.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\n\n==Population==\n[[Image:Mauritius demography.png|thumb|450px|Mauritius's population, 1961-2003.]]\n\nAccording to {{UN_Population|source}} the total population was {{UN_Population|Mauritius}} in {{UN_Population|Year}}, compared to 479,000 in 1950.<ref name=\"WPP 2010\"/>\n\nThe proportion of the population aged under 15 was 21.9% in 2010.<ref name=\"WPP 2010\"/> 71.2% were between 15 and 65 years of age, with 6.9% being 65 years or older.<ref name=\"WPP 2010\">{{cite web|url=http://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/index.htm|title=World Population Prospects, the 2010 Revision|date=6 May 2011|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=29 August 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110506000000/http://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/index.htm|archivedate=6 May 2011}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|-\n!\n! width=\"80pt\"|Total population\n! width=\"80pt\"|Popula