 also permitted. However, the [[lingua franca]] is Mauritian Creole and the newspapers and television programs are usually in French.<ref name=\"brandeis.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brandeis.edu/coexistence/linked%20documents/Nigel%20-%20Mauritius%20FINAL.pdf |title=Coexistence International at Brandeis University |format=PDF|website=Brandeis.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref>\n\nMauritian Creole, which is spoken by 90 percent of the population, is considered to be the native language of the country and is used most often in informal settings.<ref name=\"chass.utoronto.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/~cpercy/courses/6362-chiba.htm|title=English Usage in Mauritius|website=Chass.utoronto.ca|accessdate=2017-08-29}}</ref> It was developed in the 18th century by slaves who used a [[pidgin language]] to communicate with each other as well as with their French masters, who did not understand the various African languages. The pidgin evolved with later generations to become a casual language.<ref name=\"m2002.thecgf.com\">{{cite web|url=http://m2002.thecgf.com/Nations/Africa/Mauritius/default.asp|title=Mauritius|website=M2002.thecgf.com|accessdate=2017-08-29}}</ref>\n\nMauritian Creole is a [[French-based creole]] due to its close ties with French pronunciation and vocabulary. \n\nAround 10.2% people can speak the Tamil language and many of their children have started to learn the language.\n\n==Religion==\n{{Further|Religion in Mauritius}}\n\nIn 2011, the population was estimated to be 48.5% [[Hinduism|Hindu]], 26.3% [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]], 17.3% Muslim, 6.4% other Christian, 0.6% other religions, 0.7% no religion, and 0.1% unspecified.<ref name=\"CIATONGA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/mp.html|title=Africa : MAURITIUS|publisher=CIA The World Factbook|accessdate=2017-08-29}}</ref>\n\nMore than 90% of the [[Sino-Mauritian]] community are Christian; the remainder are largely Buddhist.<ref name=\"Eriksen 1998 82\"/>\n\n==Migrants==\n\nAccording to the United Nations, there were 28,713 international migrants in Mauritius in 2017.\n\nTheir most common countries of origin were as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"width:24em;\"\n! colspan=2|International migrants in Mauritius in 2017\n|-\n| {{Flagu|India}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8,689\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Bangladesh}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8,364\n|-\n| {{Flagu|China}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2,964\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Madagascar}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2,287\n|-\n| {{Flagu|France}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1,511\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Sri Lanka}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1,131\n|-\n| {{Flagu|South Africa}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 624\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Great Britain}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 456\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Pakistan}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 187\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Italy}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 146\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Germany}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 136\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Seychelles}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 124\n|-\n|colspan=2|<center><small>Source: [[United Nations ]]</small>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/development/desa/population/migration/data/estimates2/docs/MigrationStockDocumentation_2017.pdf||title= Migrant Stock by Origin and Destination||date=2019||accessdate=4 October 2019}}</center>\n|}\n\n== Other demographic statistics ==\nDemographic statistics according to the World Population Review in 2019.<ref name=\"WPR 2019\">{{cite|url=http://worldpopulationreview.com/countries/mauritius-population/|title=Mauritius Population 2019|website=World Population Review}}</ref>\n\n*One birth every 39 minutes\t\n*One death every 50 minutes\t\n*One net migrant every Infinity minutes\t\n*Net gain of one person every 180 minutes\n\nThe following demographic are from the [[CIA World Factbook]]<ref name=\".cia.gov\">{{cite|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/mp.html|title= The World FactBook - Mauritius|date=July 12, 2018|work=[[The World Factbook]]}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> unless otherwise indicated.\n\n;Population:\n:1,364,283 (July 2018 est.)\n\n;Age structure:\n[[File:Mauritiuspop.svg|thumb|350px|Population pyramid of Mauritius in 2017]]\n:''0-14 years:'' 19.9% (male 138,707 /female 132,774)\n:''15-24 years:'' 14.52% (male 100,281 /female 97,836)\n:''25-54 years:'' 43.6% (male 297,558 /female 297,243)\n:''55-64 years:'' 11.81% (male 76,620 /female 84,554)\n:''65 years and over:'' 10.17% (male 57,094 /female 81,616) (2018 est.)\n\n;Median age:\n:total: 35.7 years. Country comparison to the world: 77th\n:male: 34.5 years \n:female: 36.7 years (2018 est.)\n\n;Birth rate:\n:12.8 births/1,000 population (2018 est.) Country comparison to the world: 152nd\n\n;Death rate:\n:7.1 deaths/1,000 population (2018 est.) Country comparison to the world: 127th\n\n;[[Total fertility rate]]:\n:1.74 children born/woman (2018 est.) Country comparison to the world: 163rd\n:1.80 children born/woman (2010 est.)\n:2.02 children born/woman (2000 est.)\n\n;Population growth rate:\n:0.57% (2018 est.) Country comparison to the world: 150th\n:0.776% (2010 est.)\n\n;Contraceptive prevalence rate:\n:63.8% (2014)\n\n;Net migration rate:\n:0 migrant(s)/1,000 population (2017 est.) Country comparison to the world: 92nd\n\n;Life expectancy at birth:\n:total population: 76 years (2018 est.)\n:male: 72.6 years (2018 est.)\n:female: 79.7 years (2018 est.)\n\n;Infant mortality rate:\n:9.5 deaths/1,000 live births (2018 est.)\n:12.2 deaths/1,000 live births (2010 est.)\n:17.73 deaths/1,000 live births (2000 est.)\n\n;[[Dependency ratio]]s:\n:total dependency ratio: 41.6 (2015 est.)\n:youth dependency ratio: 27.5 (2015 est.)\n:elderly dependency ratio: 14.1 (2015 est.)\n:[[potential support ratio]]: 7.1 (2015 est.)\n\n;Urbanization: \n:urban population: 40.8% of total population (2018)\n:rate of urbanization: 0.11% annual rate of change (2015-20 est.)\n\n;Nationality:\n<br>''noun:'