ge": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demographics_of_Mauritius"}
{"title_page": "Rina Sawayama", "text_new": "{{about|the singer-songwriter|the model and figure skater|Rina Sawayama (model)}}\n<!-- See WP:WikiProject Musicians --> \n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Rina Sawayama\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Rina Sawayama 04 30 2018 -1 (41396335440) (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Sawayama in 2018\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1990|8|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Niigata, Niigata|Niigata]], Japan\n| origin           = [[London]], England\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"VoS\"/>\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"VoS\"/>}}\n* [[electropop]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Daw |first1=Stephen |title=Rina Sawayama Recruits Pabllo Vittar For Infectious Brabo Remix of 'Comme Des Gar\u00e7ons': Listen |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8551606/rina-sawayama-pabllo-vittar-comme-de-garcons |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=21 February 2020 |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[alternative pop]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Piccirillo |first1=Angie |title=Artist of the Month Rina Sawayama on Aughts Pop, Fan Projects, and Having the Hottest Record on BBC 1 |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/04/artist-of-the-month-rina-sawayama/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = [[Dirty Hit]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Clarence Clarity]]\n| website          = \n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|model}}\n}}\n\n'''Rina Sawayama''' ({{lang-ja|\u30ea\u30ca \u30b5\u30ef\u30e4\u30de}}; born 16 August 1990) is a Japanese-born British singer, songwriter and model. \nBorn in [[Niigata (city)|Niigata]], Japan, she was raised from a young age in London, where she currently resides. Her debut [[Mini-LP|mini-album]], ''Rina'' was released in 2017, while her debut studio album ''[[Sawayama]]'' was released on 17 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/nz/album/sawayama/1495129774|title=Sawayama by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music|date=16 January 2020|website=[[Apple Music]]|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRina Sawayama was born 16 August 1990<!-- Note: cited source says only \"August 1990\" with no specific date; do not add a specific date unless you have a reliable source for it; and if you do, cite it --> in [[Niigata, Niigata|Niigata]], Japan.<ref name=\"VoS\">{{cite web |url=https://vibesofsilence.com/introducing-rina-sawayama |title=Introducing: Rina Sawayama |work=Vibes of Silence |date=4 November 2017|accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/rinasawayama/status/1029886151199531008?lang=en|title=RINA on Twitter|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> She lived there until the age of five when her family decided to move to [[London]], England, where she was raised and currently lives.<ref name=\"Vogue\">{{cite news|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/rina-sawayama-model-singer-japanese-beauty-standards-orange-hair|title=Meet the Tangerine-Haired Model and Singer Who's Taking On Asian Beauty Standards|last=Kim|first=Monica|date=17 October 2016|magazine=Vogue|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref> While studying politics, psychology and sociology at [[Magdalene College, Cambridge|Magdalene College, University of Cambridge]],<ref name=\"Pixelated People\">{{cite web |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/pixelated-people-rina-sawayama-interviewed |title=Pixelated People: Rina Sawayama Interviewed|date=8 February 2018|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> she decided to pursue music and modelling. During her time at university, she was in a [[hip hop music|hip hop]] group called Lazy Lion with Theo Ellis from the [[indie rock]] band [[Wolf Alice]].<ref name=\"VoS\"/> She graduated from the university with a degree in politics.\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Musical career ===\nSawayama began her solo career in 2013, with the single \"Sleeping in Waking\". In June 2015, she released a music video, directed by Arvida Bystr\u00f6m, to her track \"Tunnel Vision\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Rina Sawayama|title=Rina Sawayama - Tunnel Vision (Official Video)|date=2015-06-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3MZaDDD2JeI|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she released the single \"Where U Are\", with an accompanying music video co-directed by Alessandra Kurr.<ref name=\":1\" /> The single explored human interaction with digital media, with Sawayama explaining: \"Online you can present your best edited self [and] your overheating phone substitutes human warmth. Weirdest of all\u2014you\u2019re together, but also very alone\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.c-heads.com/2016/02/01/rina-sawayama-streams-smooth-new-track-where-u-are/|title=Rina Sawayama streams smooth new track \"Where U Are\" - C-Heads Magazine|date=2016-02-01|work=C-Heads Magazine|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, her single \"Cyber Stockholm Syndrome\" premiered on ''[[The Fader]]''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/03/22/rina-sawayama-cyber-stockholm-syndrome|title=Rina Sawayama\u2019s Glitchy R&amp;B Captures The Realities Of Living &amp; Loving Online|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en}}</ref> Sawayama described the genesis of the themes of the track as: \"the digital world can offer vital support networks, voices of solidarity, refuge, escape. That\u2019s what \u2018Cyber Stockholm Syndrome\u2019  is about: pessimism, optimism, anxiety, and freedom\".<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2017, the singles \"Alterlife\" and \"Tunnel Vision\", a duet with Shamir, were released, followed by her debut mini-album ''Rina''.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Sawayama was then an unsigned artist, and ''Rina'' was released independently.\n\nIn 2018, she released the single \"Valentine\" on Valentine\u2019s Day.<ref name=\":5\" /> The music video for album track \"Ordinary Superstar\" was released in June 2018.<ref>{{Citation|last=i-D|title=Rina Sawayama - Ordinary Superstar (Official Video)|date=2018-06-05|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JXnxWFKnPJY|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref> In August 2018, Sawayama released the track \"Cherry\", in which she explores her sexual identity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/zmkgyx/rina-sawayama-comes-out-pansexual-interview|title=Singer Rina Sawayama Is Ready to Rep Her Pansexuality|date=2018-08-14|work=Broadly|access-date=2018-08-14|language=en-us}}</ref> Sawayama embarked on her Ordinary Superstar tour across the UK and America in late 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/06/05/rina-sawayama-ordinary-superstar-video|title=Watch Rina Sawayama's new video for \"Ordinary Superstar\"|work=The Fader|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she was the support act for [[Charli XCX]]'s tour across the UK.\n\nIn 2020, after signing to [[Dirty Hit]] records, she announced her debut album, ''[[Sawayama]]''. The album was preceded by the singles \"STFU!\", a heavy metal-style song, and \"[[Comme des Gar\u00e7ons (Like the Boys)]]\", a \"homage to early 2000s dance tracks\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/rina-sawayama-announces-tour-and-debut-album-shares-new-song-listen/|title=Rina Sawayama Announces Tour and Debut Album, Shares New Song: Listen|date=2020-01-17|work=Pitchfork|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-us}}</ref> The third single, the 2000s R&B inspired \"XS\" was released on March 2, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rina Sawayama \"mocks capitalism\" on new track 'XS' |url=https://diymag.com/2020/03/03/listen-rina-sawayama-new-track-xs |website=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> The following month, Sawayama released another single from the album titled \"Chosen Family\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bloom |first1=Madison |last2=Monroe |first2=Jazz |title=Rina Sawayama Shares New Song \"Chosen Family\": Listen |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/rina-sawayama-shares-new-song-chosen-family-listen/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Her debut album ''Sawayama'' was released on April 17, 2020 to widespread critical acclaim.\n\n===Modelling career===\nSawayama has been signed to Anti Agency and [[Elite Model Management]].\n\nAs of 2018, she has starred in campaigns for [[Versus (Versace)|Versus x Versace]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/fashion/article/37225/1/meet-versus-versaces-new-muses-tommy-genesis-hunter-schafer-rejjie-snow|title=Meet Versus Versace\u2019s new gang of multi-talented muses|last=Dazed|date=2017-09-01|work=Dazed|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en}}</ref> [[Jourdan Dunn]]'s ''Missguided'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/people/jourdan-dunn-empowering-new-collection-supermodel-really-wears/|title=Jourdan Dunn on her empowering new collection - and what a supermodel really wears on the school run|last=Holt|first=Bethan|date=2017-03-10|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and wrote and performed an original track for [[Nicola Formichetti]]\u2019s MAC x Nicopanda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/formichetti/status/968561469884370946?lang=en|title=nicola formichetti on Twitter|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Collaborations ===\nIn 2016, Sawayama collaborated with artist [[John Yuyi]] on a visual series critiquing Asian, and Japanese, beauty standards. Subsequently, she was profiled in [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue Magazine]]. In the interview, Sawayama described the genesis of the idea and collaboration: \"For a lot of women in Japan, these are the expectations people put on them, from anime culture, kawaii culture... that can really put women at a disadvantage, objectifying and infantilizing them.\"<ref name=\"Vogue\" />\n\nSawayama has worked with Nicola Formichetti for MAC x Nicopanda. Formichetti also directed the music video for Sawayama\u2019s track \u2018Ordinary Superstar\u2019. The genesis of the partnership was outlined in i-D.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/a3aj9j/read-rina-sawayama-and-nicola-formichettis-texts-to-each-other|title=read rina sawayama and nicola formichetti's texts to each other|date=2018-06-05|work=I-d|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en-uk}}</ref>\n\nMany of Sawayama\u2019s tracks are co-written and produced by [[Clarence Clarity]].\n\n== Critical reception ==\nSawayama's output has been met with critical acclaim, and has been featured in ''The Fader''{{'}}s Gen F series,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/tag/gen-f|title=The FADER - GEN F|website=The FADER|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref> and the ''i-D Meets'' series, as well in ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper Magazine]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/02/style/rina-sawayama-pop-star.html|title=Rina Sawayama Is Not the Asian Britney Spears|access-date=2018-08-14}}</ref> and on the cover of ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash Magazine]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/pixelated-people-rina-sawayama-interviewed|title=Pixelated People: Rina Sawayama Interviewed|work=Clash Magazine|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\nSawayama's singles have been described as \"nostalgic greatness... ultra-sweet and shimmering pop\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefourohfive.com/music/article/rina-sawayama-s-where-u-are-is-ultra-sweet-145|title=Rina Sawayama's 'Where U Are' is ultra-sweet|last=http://thefourohfive.com|work=The 405|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref> and \"90s R&B pop perfection. Very lounge. A little Solange. A smidge of peak-era Mariah\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_au/article/6azqgj/rina-sawayama-where-u-are-premiere-57a206f40007d1df16fc2f2b|title=Fall for the Smooth Curves of Rina Sawayama's \"Where U Are\"|date=2016-01-28|work=Noisey|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\n''The Guardian'' deemed her album \"bracing and modern... Sawayama might be keen to pay tribute, but she's proven she can shepherd pop into the future, too.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/21/rina-sawayama-rina-review-rb-fuelled-peek-into-the-pop-future|title=Rina Sawayama: Rina review \u2013 R&B-fuelled peek into the pop future|last=Aroesti|first=Rachel|date=2017-12-21|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\nSawayama has been featured in numerous best of lists, including ''The Guardian''{{'}}s 18 for '18,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2017/dec/31/18-for-18-the-talent-and-trends-tipped-for-the-top-in-2018|title=18 for '18: the talent and trends tipped for the top in 2018|last=Williams|first=Holly|last2=Brinkhurst-Cuff|first2=Charlie|date=2017-12-31|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-07-13|last3=Fox|first3=Killian|last4=Snapes|first4=Laura|last5=Joshi|first5=Tara|last6=Cumming|first6=Laura|last7=Hans|first7=Simran|last8=Empire|first8=Kitty|last9=Devlin|first9=Hannah}}</ref> the 2017 ''Dazed'' 100,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/dazed100/2017|title=100 people shaping culture in 2017 {{!}} Dazed|last=Dazed|website=Dazed|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref> and ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s Best Pop and R&B Albums of 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-20-best-pop-and-randb-albums-of-2017/|title=The 20 Best Pop and R&B Albums of 2017 {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn August 2018, Sawayama [[coming out|came out]] during an interview with [[Vice (magazine)|Broadly]], declaring: \u201cI\u2019ve always written songs about girls. I don\u2019t think I\u2019ve ever mentioned a guy in my songs, and that\u2019s why I wanted to talk about it.\u201d She identified as both [[bisexuality|bisexual]] and pansexual.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/zmkgyx/rina-sawayama-comes-out-pansexual-interview|title=Singer Rina Sawayama Is Ready to Rep Her Pansexuality|last=Tsjeng|first=Zing|website=Broadly|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Welcome to the El-Palacio]]''\n| Mariko tanahashi\n| Recurring role; 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Turn Up Charlie]]''\n| Layla Valentine\n| Recurring role; 2 episodes\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ List of albums, with selected details, chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Sawayama]]''\n|\n* Released: 17 April 2020\n* Label: [[Dirty Hit]]\n* Formats: {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]|[[Phonograph record|12\" vinyl]]|[[Compact disc|CD]]}}\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ List of extended plays, with selected details, chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\" | Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" | Peak chart positions\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;\" | [[Billboard Japan|JPN<br />Dig.]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Rina''\n|\n* Released: 27 October 2017\n* Label: self-released\n* Formats: {{hlist|Digital download|streaming|12\" vinyl}}\n| 93\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Sleeping in Waking\"\n|2013\n| rowspan=\"3\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Where U Are\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/where-u-are-single/1068605888 |title=Where U Are - Single by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music |work=iTunes |accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"This Time Last Year\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/this-time-last-year-single/1181101883 |title=This Time Last Year - Single by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music |work=iTunes |accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Cyber Stockholm Syndrome\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/cyber-stockholm-syndrome-single/1209034973 |title=Cyber Stockholm Syndrome - Single by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music |work=iTunes |accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2017\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''Rina''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Alterlife\"<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/alterlife-single/1280968251 |title=Afterlife - Single by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music |work=iTunes |accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Tunnel Vision\"<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/tunnel-vision-feat-shamir-single/1298483983 |title=Tunnel Vision (feat. Shamir) - Single by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music |work=iTunes |accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref><br />{{small|(featuring [[Shamir (musician)|Shamir]])}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Valentine (What's It Gonna Be)\"<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/valentine-whats-it-gonna-be-single/1346333878 |title=Valentine (What's It Gonna Be) - Single by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music |work=iTunes |accessdate=2 March 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2018\n| rowspan=\"3\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Cherry\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Flicker\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"STFU!\"<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url= https://music.apple.com/ca/album/stfu-single/1485816072|title=STFU! - Single by Rina Sawayama|work=Apple Music|accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n| 2019\n| rowspan=\"5\"| ''Sawayama''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Comme des Gar\u00e7ons (Like the Boys)]]\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"XS\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Chosen Family\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Bad Friend\"\n|}\n\n==Tours==\n'''Headlining'''\n* Ordinary Superstar Tour (2018)\n* The Dynasty Tour (2020)\n\n'''Supporting'''\n* [[Charli XCX]] \u2013 [[Charli Live Tour]] (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sawayama, Rina}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual musicians]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n[[Category:English people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Japanese emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Japanese female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Japanese rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from Japan]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Niigata Prefecture]]\n[[Category:LGBT models]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Japan]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pansexual people]]\n[[Category:People from Niigata (city)]]\n[[Category:21st-century English women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese singers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Dirty Hit artists]]\n[[Category:Japanese women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:English women in electronic music]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the singer-songwriter|the model and figure skater|Rina Sawayama (model)}}\n<!-- See WP:WikiProject Musicians --> \n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Rina Sawayama\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Rina Sawayama 04 30 2018 -1 (41396335440) (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Sawayama in 2018\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1990|8|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Niigata, Niigata|Niigata]], Japan\n| origin           = [[London]], England\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"VoS\"/>\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"VoS\"/>}}\n* [[electropop]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Daw |first1=Stephen |title=Rina Sawayama Recruits Pabllo Vittar For Infectious Brabo Remix of 'Comme Des Gar\u00e7ons': Listen |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8551606/rina-sawayama-pabllo-vittar-comme-de-garcons |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=21 February 2020 |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = [[Dirty Hit]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Clarence Clarity]]\n| website          = \n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|model}}\n}}\n\n'''Rina Sawayama''' ({{lang-ja|\u30ea\u30ca \u30b5\u30ef\u30e4\u30de}}; born 16 August 1990) is a Japanese-born British singer, songwriter and model. \nBorn in [[Niigata (city)|Niigata]], Japan, she was raised from a young age in London, where she currently resides. Her debut [[Mini-LP|mini-album]], ''Rina'' was released in 2017, while her debut studio album ''[[Sawayama]]'' was released on 17 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/nz/album/sawayama/1495129774|title=Sawayama by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music|date=16 January 2020|website=[[Apple Music]]|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRina Sawayama was born 16 August 1990<!-- Note: cited source says only \"August 1990\" with no specific date; do not add a specific date unless you have a reliable source for it; and if you do, cite it --> in [[Niigata, Niigata|Niigata]], Japan.<ref name=\"VoS\">{{cite web |url=https://vibesofsilence.com/introducing-rina-sawayama |title=Introducing: Rina Sawayama |work=Vibes of Silence |date=4 November 2017|accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/rinasawayama/status/1029886151199531008?lang=en|title=RINA on Twitter|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> She lived there until the age of five when her family decided to move to [[London]], England, where she was raised and currently lives.<ref name=\"Vogue\">{{cite news|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/rina-sawayama-model-singer-japanese-beauty-standards-orange-hair|title=Meet the Tangerine-Haired Model and Singer Who's Taking On Asian Beauty Standards|last=Kim|first=Monica|date=17 October 2016|magazine=Vogue|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref> While studying politics, psychology and sociology at [[Magdalene College, Cambridge|Magdalene College, University of Cambridge]],<ref name=\"Pixelated People\">{{cite web |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/pixelated-people-rina-sawayama-interviewed |title=Pixelated People: Rina Sawayama Interviewed|date=8 February 2018|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> she decided to pursue music and modelling. During her time at university, she was in a [[hip hop music|hip hop]] group called Lazy Lion with Theo Ellis from the [[indie rock]] band [[Wolf Alice]].<ref name=\"VoS\"/> She graduated from the university with a degree in politics.\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Musical career ===\nSawayama began her solo career in 2013, with the single \"Sleeping in Waking\". In June 2015, she released a music video, directed by Arvida Bystr\u00f6m, to her track \"Tunnel Vision\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Rina Sawayama|title=Rina Sawayama - Tunnel Vision (Official Video)|date=2015-06-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3MZaDDD2JeI|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she released the single \"Where U Are\", with an accompanying music video co-directed by Alessandra Kurr.<ref name=\":1\" /> The single explored human interaction with digital media, with Sawayama explaining: \"Online you can present your best edited self [and] your overheating phone substitutes human warmth. Weirdest of all\u2014you\u2019re together, but also very alone\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.c-heads.com/2016/02/01/rina-sawayama-streams-smooth-new-track-where-u-are/|title=Rina Sawayama streams smooth new track \"Where U Are\" - C-Heads Magazine|date=2016-02-01|work=C-Heads Magazine|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, her single \"Cyber Stockholm Syndrome\" premiered on ''[[The Fader]]''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/03/22/rina-sawayama-cyber-stockholm-syndrome|title=Rina Sawayama\u2019s Glitchy R&amp;B Captures The Realities Of Living &amp; Loving Online|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en}}</ref> Sawayama described the genesis of the themes of the track as: \"the digital world can offer vital support networks, voices of solidarity, refuge, escape. That\u2019s what \u2018Cyber Stockholm Syndrome\u2019  is about: pessimism, optimism, anxiety, and freedom\".<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2017, the singles \"Alterlife\" and \"Tunnel Vision\", a duet with Shamir, were released, followed by her debut mini-album ''Rina''.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Sawayama was then an unsigned artist, and ''Rina'' was released independently.\n\nIn 2018, she released the single \"Valentine\" on Valentine\u2019s Day.<ref name=\":5\" /> The music video for album track \"Ordinary Superstar\" was released in June 2018.<ref>{{Citation|last=i-D|title=Rina Sawayama - Ordinary Superstar (Official Video)|date=2018-06-05|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JXnxWFKnPJY|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref> In August 2018, Sawayama released the track \"Cherry\", in which she explores her sexual identity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/zmkgyx/rina-sawayama-comes-out-pansexual-interview|title=Singer Rina Sawayama Is Ready to Rep Her Pansexuality|date=2018-08-14|work=Broadly|access-date=2018-08-14|language=en-us}}</ref> Sawayama embarked on her Ordinary Superstar tour across the UK and America in late 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/06/05/rina-sawayama-ordinary-superstar-video|title=Watch Rina Sawayama's new video for \"Ordinary Superstar\"|work=The Fader|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she was the support act for [[Charli XCX]]'s tour across the UK.\n\nIn 2020, after signing to [[Dirty Hit]] records, she announced her debut album, ''[[Sawayama]]''. The album was preceded by the singles \"STFU!\", a heavy metal-style song, and \"[[Comme des Gar\u00e7ons (Like the Boys)]]\", a \"homage to early 2000s dance tracks\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/rina-sawayama-announces-tour-and-debut-album-shares-new-song-listen/|title=Rina Sawayama Announces Tour and Debut Album, Shares New Song: Listen|date=2020-01-17|work=Pitchfork|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-us}}</ref> The third single, the 2000s R&B inspired \"XS\" was released on March 2, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rina Sawayama \"mocks capitalism\" on new track 'XS' |url=https://diymag.com/2020/03/03/listen-rina-sawayama-new-track-xs |website=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> The following month, Sawayama released another single from the album titled \"Chosen Family\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bloom |first1=Madison |last2=Monroe |first2=Jazz |title=Rina Sawayama Shares New Song \"Chosen Family\": Listen |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/rina-sawayama-shares-new-song-chosen-family-listen/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Her debut album ''Sawayama'' was released on April 17, 2020 to widespread critical acclaim.\n\n===Modelling career===\nSawayama has been signed to Anti Agency and [[Elite Model Management]].\n\nAs of 2018, she has starred in campaigns for [[Versus (Versace)|Versus x Versace]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/fashion/article/37225/1/meet-versus-versaces-new-muses-tommy-genesis-hunter-schafer-rejjie-snow|title=Meet Versus Versace\u2019s new gang of multi-talented muses|last=Dazed|date=2017-09-01|work=Dazed|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en}}</ref> [[Jourdan Dunn]]'s ''Missguided'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/people/jourdan-dunn-empowering-new-collection-supermodel-really-wears/|title=Jourdan Dunn on her empowering new collection - and what a supermodel really wears on the school run|last=Holt|first=Bethan|date=2017-03-10|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and wrote and performed an original track for [[Nicola Formichetti]]\u2019s MAC x Nicopanda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/formichetti/status/968561469884370946?lang=en|title=nicola formichetti on Twitter|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Collaborations ===\nIn 2016, Sawayama collaborated with artist [[John Yuyi]] on a visual series critiquing Asian, and Japanese, beauty standards. Subsequently, she was profiled in [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue Magazine]]. In the interview, Sawayama described the genesis of the idea and collaboration: \"For a lot of women in Japan, these are the expectations people put on them, from anime culture, kawaii culture... that can really put women at a disadvantage, objectifying and infantilizing them.\"<ref name=\"Vogue\" />\n\nSawayama has worked with Nicola Formichetti for MAC x Nicopanda. Formichetti also directed the music video for Sawayama\u2019s track \u2018Ordinary Superstar\u2019. The genesis of the partnership was outlined in i-D.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/a3aj9j/read-rina-sawayama-and-nicola-formichettis-texts-to-each-other|title=read rina sawayama and nicola formichetti's texts to each other|date=2018-06-05|work=I-d|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en-uk}}</ref>\n\nMany of Sawayama\u2019s tracks are co-written and produced by [[Clarence Clarity]].\n\n== Critical reception ==\nSawayama's output has been met with critical acclaim, and has been featured in ''The Fader''{{'}}s Gen F series,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/tag/gen-f|title=The FADER - GEN F|website=The FADER|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref> and the ''i-D Meets'' series, as well in ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper Magazine]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/02/style/rina-sawayama-pop-star.html|title=Rina Sawayama Is Not the Asian Britney Spears|access-date=2018-08-14}}</ref> and on the cover of ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash Magazine]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/pixelated-people-rina-sawayama-interviewed|title=Pixelated People: Rina Sawayama Interviewed|work=Clash Magazine|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\nSawayama's singles have been described as \"nostalgic greatness... ultra-sweet and shimmering pop\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefourohfive.com/music/article/rina-sawayama-s-where-u-are-is-ultra-sweet-145|title=Rina Sawayama's 'Where U Are' is ultra-sweet|last=http://thefourohfive.com|work=The 405|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref> and \"90s R&B pop perfection. Very lounge. A little Solange. A smidge of peak-era Mariah\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_au/article/6azqgj/rina-sawayama-where-u-are-premiere-57a206f40007d1df16fc2f2b|title=Fall for the Smooth Curves of Rina Sawayama's \"Where U Are\"|date=2016-01-28|work=Noisey|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\n''The Guardian'' deemed her album \"bracing and modern... Sawayama might be keen to pay tribute, but she's proven she can shepherd pop into the future, too.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/21/rina-sawayama-rina-review-rb-fuelled-peek-into-the-pop-future|title=Rina Sawayama: Rina review \u2013 R&B-fuelled peek into the pop future|last=Aroesti|first=Rachel|date=2017-12-21|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\nSawayama has been featured in numerous best of lists, including ''The Guardian''{{'}}s 18 for '18,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2017/dec/31/18-for-18-the-talent-and-trends-tipped-for-the-top-in-2018|title=18 for '18: the talent and trends tipped for the top in 2018|last=Williams|first=Holly|last2=Brinkhurst-Cuff|first2=Charlie|date=2017-12-31|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-07-13|last3=Fox|first3=Killian|last4=Snapes|first4=Laura|last5=Joshi|first5=Tara|last6=Cumming|first6=Laura|last7=Hans|first7=Simran|last8=Empire|first8=Kitty|last9=Devlin|first9=Hannah}}</ref> the 2017 ''Dazed'' 100,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/dazed100/2017|title=100 people shaping culture in 2017 {{!}} Dazed|last=Dazed|website=Dazed|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref> and ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s Best Pop and R&B Albums of 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-20-best-pop-and-randb-albums-of-2017/|title=The 20 Best Pop and R&B Albums of 2017 {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn August 2018, Sawayama [[coming out|came out]] during an interview with [[Vice (magazine)|Broadly]], declaring: \u201cI\u2019ve always written songs about girls. I don\u2019t think I\u2019ve ever mentioned a guy in my songs, and that\u2019s why I wanted to talk about it.\u201d She identified as both [[bisexuality|bisexual]] and pansexual.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/zmkgyx/rina-sawayama-comes-out-pansexual-interview|title=Singer Rina Sawayama Is Ready to Rep Her Pansexuality|last=Tsjeng|first=Zing|website=Broadly|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Welcome to the El-Palacio]]''\n| Mariko tanahashi\n| Recurring role; 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Turn Up Charlie]]''\n| Layla Valentine\n| Recurring role; 2 episodes\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ List of albums, with selected details, chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Sawayama]]''\n|\n* Released: 17 April 2020\n* Label: [[Dirty Hit]]\n* Formats: {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]|[[Phonograph record|12\" vinyl]]|[[Compact disc|CD]]}}\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ List of extended plays, with selected details, chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\" | Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" | Peak chart positions\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;\" | [[Billboard Japan|JPN<br />Dig.]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Rina''\n|\n* Released: 27 October 2017\n* Label: self-released\n* Formats: {{hlist|Digital download|streaming|12\" vinyl}}\n| 93\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Sleeping in Waking\"\n|2013\n| rowspan=\"3\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Where U Are\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/where-u-are-single/1068605888 |title=Where U Are - Single by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music |work=iTunes |accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"This Time Last Year\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/this-time-last-year-single/1181101883 |title=This Time Last Year - Single by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music |work=iTunes |accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Cyber Stockholm Syndrome\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/cyber-stockholm-syndrome-single/1209034973 |title=Cyber Stockholm Syndrome - Single by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music |work=iTunes |accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2017\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''Rina''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Alterlife\"<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/alterlife-single/1280968251 |title=Afterlife - Single by Rina Sawayama on Apple Music |work=iTunes |accessdate=18 November 2017}}</