 (2005\u20132016)\n* [[Liberal Front Party (Brazil)|PFL]] (2005)\n* [[Brazilian Labour Party (current)|PTB]] (2003\u20132005)\n* [[Progressistas|PPB]] (1995\u20132003)\n* [[Reform Progressive Party|PPR]] (1993\u20131995)\n* [[Progressive Party (Brazil, 1993)|PP]] (1993)\n* [[Christian Democratic Party (Brazil)|PDC]] (1988\u20131993)\n }}\n| spouse              = {{plain list|\n* {{Marriage|Rog\u00e9ria Nantes Braga|1978|1997|end=div}}\n* {{Marriage|Ana Cristina Valle|1997|2007|end=div}}\n* {{Marriage|[[Michelle Bolsonaro|Michelle de Paula]]|2007}}\n }}\n| children            = {{hlist|[[Fl\u00e1vio Bolsonaro|Fl\u00e1vio]]|[[Carlos Bolsonaro|Carlos]]|[[Eduardo Bolsonaro|Eduardo]]|Jair Renan|Laura}}\n| residence           = [[Pal\u00e1cio da Alvorada]]\n| birth_name          = Jair Messias Bolsonaro\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1955|3|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Glic\u00e9rio]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| education           = [[Academia Militar das Agulhas Negras|Agulhas Negras Military Academy]]\n| signature           = Signature of Jair Bolsonaro.svg\n| website             = {{url|bolsonaro.com.br|Official website}}\n| allegiance          = {{flag|Brazil}}\n| branch              = {{flagicon|Brazil|army}} [[Brazilian Army]]\n| serviceyears        = 1973\u20131988\n| rank                = [[File:Barzil-Army-OF-2 (horizontal).svg|35px]] [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]]\n| commands            = 21st Field Artillery Group<br />9th Field Artillery Group<br />8th Parachutist Field Artillery Group\n}}\n{{Jair Bolsonaro sidebar}}\n\n'''Jair Messias Bolsonaro''' ({{IPA-pt|\u0292a\u02c8i\u0281 me\u02c8si.\u0250z bowso\u02c8na\u027eu, \u0292a\u02c8i\u027e -|br}}; born 21 March 1955) is a Brazilian politician and retired military officer who has been the 38th [[president of Brazil]] since 1{{nbsp}}January 2019. He served in the country's [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Chamber of Deputies]], representing the [[Rio de Janeiro (state)|state of Rio de Janeiro]], between 1991 and 2018. He was [[2018 Brazilian general election|elected president]] as a member of the conservative [[Social Liberal Party (Brazil)|Social Liberal Party]], before leaving them to found the party [[Alliance for Brazil]].\n\nBolsonaro was born in the small town of [[Glic\u00e9rio]], in the northwest area of the [[state of S\u00e3o Paulo]]. He graduated from the [[Academia Militar das Agulhas Negras|Agulhas Negras Military Academy]] in 1977 and served in the [[Brazilian Army|Brazilian Army's]] field artillery and parachutist units. He became known to the public in 1986, when he wrote an article for ''[[Veja (magazine)|Veja]]'' magazine criticizing low wages for military officers, after which he was arrested and detained for fifteen days. One year later, he was accused by the same magazine of planning to plant bombs in military units, which he denied. After a first degree conviction, he was acquitted by the Brazilian Supreme Military Court in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,o-julgamento-que-tirou-bolsonaro-do-anonimato,70002249929|title=O julgamento que tirou Bolsonaro do anonimato|first=Luiz Maklouf|last=Carvalho|work=O Estado de S\u00e3o Paulo|accessdate=8 October 2018|date=1 April 2018|language=portuguese}}</ref>\n\nHe joined the reserve army in 1988 with the rank of [[Military ranks of Brazil|captain]] and ran for the [[Municipal Chamber of Rio de Janeiro|Rio de Janeiro City Council]] that same year, being elected while a member of the [[Christian Democratic Party (Brazil)|Christian Democratic Party]]. Bolsonaro was elected in 1990 to the lower chamber of Congress and was subsequently re-elected six times. During his 27-year tenure as a congressman, he became known for his strong support of [[national conservatism]]. He is a vocal opponent of [[same-sex marriage]] and [[homosexuality]],<ref name=\"noticias.terra.com.br\">{{cite web|url=http://noticias.terra.com.br/brasil/noticias/0,,OI5114016-EI306,00-Bolsonaro+apos+uniao+gay+proximo+passo+e+legalizar+pedofilia.html|title=Bolsonaro: ap\u00f3s uni\u00e3o gay, pr\u00f3ximo passo \u00e9 legalizar pedofilia|website=Noticias.terra.com.br|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/lgbtq-brazilians-edge-after-self-described-homophobic-lawmaker-elected-president-n925726 LGBTQ Brazilians on edge after self-described 'homophobic' lawmaker elected president], ''NBC News''</ref> [[abortion]],<ref name=\"osul.com.br\">{{cite web|url=http://www.osul.com.br/bolsonaro-em-porto-alegre-confirma-ser-contra-o-aborto-e-a-favor-da-reducao-da-maioridade-penal/|title=Bolsonaro, em Porto Alegre, confirma ser contra o aborto e a favor da redu\u00e7\u00e3o da maioridade penal \u2013 Jornal O Sul|date=21 August 2015|website=Osul.com.br|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> [[affirmative action]],<ref name=\"Pol\u00edtica\">{{cite web|url=http://noticias.uol.com.br/politica/ultimas-noticias/2011/04/01/para-ministra-da-igualdade-racial-declaracoes-de-bolsonaro-sao-caso-explicito-de-racismo.htm|title=Para ministra da Igualdade Racial, declara\u00e7\u00f5es de Bolsonaro s\u00e3o caso expl\u00edcito de racismo|publisher=Pol\u00edtica|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> [[drug liberalization]]<ref name=\"epoca2\">{{cite web|url=http://revistaepoca.globo.com/Revista/Epoca/0,,EMI245890-15223,00.html|title=Jair Bolsonaro: \"Sou preconceituoso, com muito orgulho\"|website=revistaepoca.globo.com|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> and [[secularism]].<ref name=\"epoca2\"/> In foreign policy, he has advocated closer relations to the [[United States]]<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://observer.com/2018/10/brazil-elections-jair-bolsonaro-donald-trump/amp/|title=Will Brazil's Jair Bolsonaro Become Trump's New Best Friend?|last=Wierson|first=Arick|date=7 October 2018|website=[[The Observer]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref> and [[Israel]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/brazils-workers-party-likens-pro-israel-presidential-front-runner-to-hitler|title=Brazil's Workers' Party likens pro-Israel presidential front-runner to Hitler|last=Staff|date=6 October 2018|website=[[The Times of Israel]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref> During the [[Jair Bolsonaro presidential campaign|2018 presidential campaign]], he started to advocate for [[economic liberal]] and pro-market policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2017/10/1925458-bolsonaro-diz-que-e-liberal-e-adota-discurso-que-agrada-investidores.shtml|title=Bolsonaro diz que \u00e9 liberal e adota discurso que agrada investidores - 09/10/2017 - Poder|website=Folha de S.Paulo|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> A polarizing and controversial politician, his views and comments, which have been described as [[far-right]] and [[Right-wing populism|populist]] in nature, have drawn both praise and criticism in Brazil.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/07/25/weekinreview/conversations-jair-bolsonaro-soldier-turned-politician-wants-give-brazil-back.html|title=Conversations/Jair Bolsonaro; A Soldier Turned Politician Wants To Give Brazil Back to Army Rule|first=James|last=Brooke|accessdate=7 September 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1993-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/amp/articles/brazilian-swamp-drainer-1539039700|title=Brazilian Swamp Drainer|last=Editorial Board|date=8 October 2018|newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=O inquietante 'fen\u00f4meno Bolsonaro'|url=http://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2014/10/07/politica/1412684374_628594.html|website=brasil.elpais.com|access-date=18 June 2017|language=portuguese|date=2014-10-07}}</ref><ref name=\"veconomist\">{{cite news|title=Brazil's congress starts to reform itself|url=https://www.economist.com/news/americas/21730206-clean-up-sleazy-political-system-will-require-lot-more-work-brazils-congress-starts|work=[[The Economist]]|date=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nBolsonaro announced his pre-candidacy for president in March 2016 as a member of the [[Social Christian Party (Brazil)|Social Christian Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://extra.globo.com/noticias/brasil/jair-bolsonaro-apresentado-como-pre-candidato-presidencia-da-republica-18791859.html|title=Jair Bolsonaro \u00e9 apresentado como pr\u00e9-candidato \u00e0 Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica|work=Extra, Globo|accessdate=8 October 2018|language=portuguese}}</ref> However, he left the party in 2018 and joined the Social Liberal Party, and then launched his [[Jair Bolsonaro presidential campaign, 2018|presidential campaign]] in August of that same year, with retired general [[Hamilton Mour\u00e3o]] as his running mate. He portrayed himself as an [[anti-establishment|outsider]] and a supporter of [[family values]]. Bolsonaro was non-fatally stabbed while campaigning in September 2018. He came in first place in the first round of the [[2018 Brazilian general election|general election on 7{{nbsp}}October 2018]], with [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Workers' Party]] candidate [[Fernando Haddad]] coming in second place. The two candidates faced a [[Two-round system|run-off]] on 28 October 2018, and Bolsonaro was elected with 55.1% of the vote.\n\n== Early life ==\nBolsonaro was born on 21 March 1955 in the town of [[Glic\u00e9rio]], in [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Godoy, Marcelo|title=Um fantasma ronda o Planalto|url=http://infograficos.estadao.com.br/politica/bolsonaro-um-fantasma-ronda-o-planalto|work=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]]|date=2 April 2017}}</ref> in the [[Southeast Region, Brazil|southeast region]] of Brazil, to Percy Geraldo Bolsonaro and Olinda Bonturi.<ref>[http://revistacrescer.globo.com/Voce-precisa-saber/noticia/2015/03/ele-era-digno-nao-era-de-falar-besteira-diz-mae-de-jair-bolsonaro.html \"Ele n\u00e3o era de falar besteira', diz m\u00e3e de Jair Bolsonaro\"], revistacrescer.globo.com; accessed 28 April 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/brasil-45973980 | title=Elei\u00e7\u00f5es 2018: ber\u00e7o do cl\u00e3 Bolsonaro, regi\u00e3o do norte da It\u00e1lia se agita com disputa no Brasil | author=Ferraz, Lucas | date=25 October 2018 | newspaper=BBC News Brasil | accessdate=27 October 2018 | language=Portuguese}}</ref> His family is mostly of [[Italian Brazilians|Italian]] descent, with some [[German Brazilians|German]] ancestry. On his father's side, he is the great-grandson of Italians from [[Veneto]] and [[Calabria]].<ref name=\"genealogia\">{{cite journal|last=TADDONE|first=Daniel|date=2018-10-23|title=Taddone revela genealogia de Bolsonaro: 13 dos 16 trisav\u00f4s do candidato s\u00e3o italianos da Toscana, do V\u00eaneto e da Cal\u00e1bria|url=http://www.insieme.com.br/pb/taddone-revela-genealogia-de-bolsonaro/|journal=Revista Insieme}}</ref> Bolsonaro's paternal grandfather's family comes from Veneto, more precisely the city of [[Anguillara Veneta]], in the [[province of Padua]]. His great-grandfather, Vittorio Bolzonaro (the surname was originally written with a Z), was born on 12 April 1878. Vittorio's parents immigrated to Brazil when he was ten, together with his little siblings, Giovanna and Tranquillo.<ref>{{cite news| title=In Veneto il paese del probabile presidente brasiliano Bolsonaro | url= https://stream24.ilsole24ore.com/video/mondo/in-veneto-paese-probabile-presidente-brasiliano-bolsonaro/AE9J8MWG | author= | date=26 October 2018 | website=[[Il Sole 24 ore]] | accessdate=27 October 2018 | language=Italian}}</ref><ref name=\"genealogia\"/> His German ancestry came from his father's maternal grandfather, Carl \"Carlos\" Hintze, born in [[Hamburg]] around 1876, who immigrated to Brazil in 1883.<ref name=\"genealogia\" /> His maternal grandparents were born in the Italian city of [[Lucca]], in [[Tuscany]], and went to live in Brazil in the 1890s.<ref name=\"genealogia\"/>\n\nBolsonaro spent most of his childhood moving around S\u00e3o Paulo with his family, living in the cities of [[Ribeira, S\u00e3o Paulo|Ribeira]], [[Jundia\u00ed]], and [[Sete Barras]], before settling in the town of [[Eldorado, S\u00e3o Paulo|Eldorado]], in the southern region of the state, in 1966, where he would grow up together with his five brothers.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bolsonaro |first=Fl\u00e1vio |date=2017 |title= Jair Messias Bolsonaro - Mito ou Verdade|url= |location= |publisher=Altadena Editora |page= |isbn=9788594307002}}</ref>\n\nHis first name is a tribute to [[Jair da Rosa Pinto]], football player for [[Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras|Palmeiras]] at the time of his birth and who celebrated his 34th birthday on the same day.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://veja.abril.com.br/placar/inspiracao-para-nome-de-bolsonaro-jair-brilhou-por-palmeiras-e-selecao/ | title=Inspira\u00e7\u00e3o para o nome de Bolsonaro, Jair brilhou por Palmeiras e sele\u00e7\u00e3o | author= | date=29 October 2018 | newspaper=Veja magazine| accessdate=2 March 2020 | language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/amp/esporte/2018/10/craque-do-palmeiras-da-decada-de-1950-inspirou-nome-de-jair-bolsonaro.shtml | title= Craque do Palmeiras da d\u00e9cada de 1950 inspirou nome de Jair Bolsonaro | author= | date=29 October 2018 | newspaper=Folha de S.Paulo| accessdate=2 March 2020 | language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n== Military career ==\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | total_width = 280\n\n| image1 = Bolsonaro e pais.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = Jair with his parents at the [[Agulhas Negras Military Academy]] in 1979\n\n| image2 = Bolsonaro 1986 (cropped).jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 = Bolsonaro in 1986<!--Please provide BETTER DESCRIPTION, so both captions will be of similar length-->\n}}\nIn his final years in high school, Bolsonaro was admitted to the [[Escola Preparat\u00f3ria de Cadetes do Ex\u00e9rcito]] (the prep school of the [[Brazilian Army]]), where he entered in 1973. In 1974, he went to the [[Academia Militar das Agulhas Negras]] (Brazil's main [[military academy]]), graduating in 1977, as an [[Artillery]] officer. He served in the 9th Field Artillery Group, in [[Nioaque]], [[Mato Grosso do Sul]]. Later he studied at the Army Physical Training School in [[Rio de Janeiro]] and served in the 21st Field Artillery Group and the 8th Paratrooper Field Artillery Group, from the [[Paratroopers Brigade (Brazil)|Paratrooper Brigade]], both in the same city. His superior officers described him as \"aggressive\" and having an \"excessive ambition to get financial and economical gain\".<ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2017/05/1884332-bolsonaro-era-agressivo-e-tinha-excessiva-ambicao-diz-ficha-militar.shtml#_=_|title=Bolsonaro era agressivo e tinha 'excessiva ambi\u00e7\u00e3o', diz ficha militar|website=1.folha.com.br|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> The assessment referred to Bolsonaro's attempt to mine gold in [[Bahia]] state; according to him, the activity was only a \"hobby and mental hygiene\". In 1987, he studied in the [[:pt:Escola de Aperfei\u00e7oamento de Oficiais|Officers Improvement School]], where he made the Artillery Advanced Course.\n\nBolsonaro's first rise to publicity came in 1986 when he gave an interview to the news magazine ''Veja''. He complained about low salaries in the military and claimed that the High Command was firing officers due to budgetary cuts and not because they were displaying 'deviations of conduct', as the command was telling the press.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arqanalagoa.ufscar.br/pdf/recortes/R03088.pdf|title=''O sal\u00e1rio est\u00e1 baixo''|website=Arqanalagoa.ufsacr.br|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> Despite being reprimanded by his superiors, Bolsonaro received praise from fellow officers and wives of military men, becoming a household name for a lot of hardliners and right-wingers who were growing disenchanted with Brazil's new civilian democratic government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://observatoriodaimprensa.com.br/jornal-de-debates/capitao-bolsonaro-a-historia-esquecida/|title=Capit\u00e3o Bolsonaro, a hist\u00f3ria esquecida \u2013 Observat\u00f3rio da Imprensa \u2013 Voc\u00ea nunca mais vai ler jornal do mesmo jeito|date=6 April 2011|publisher=|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1987, Bolsonaro faced a new accusation. The same ''Veja'' magazine reported that, with an Army colleague, he had plans to plant bombs in military units in [[Rio de Janeiro]]. After Bolsonaro called the allegation \"a fantasy\", the magazine published, in its subsequent edition, sketches in which the plan was detailed. The drawings had been allegedly produced by Bolsonaro himself. Official records unearthed by the newspaper ''[[O Estado de S.Paulo]]'' in 2018 detailed the case.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,o-julgamento-que-tirou-bolsonaro-do-anonimato,70002249929 |title=O julgamento que tirou Bolsonaro do anonimato - Pol\u00edtica |website=Estad\u00e3o}}</ref> After an investigation by an administrative military bureau named Justification Board, Bolsonaro was unanimously considered guilty. According to this board, Bolsonaro had a \"serious personality deviation and a professional deformation\", \"lack of moral courage to leave the Army\" and \"lied throughout the process\" when denying frequent contacts with the ''Veja'' magazine. The case was then analyzed by the Supreme Military Court. The [[General]] in charge of reporting the case voted for his acquittal, arguing that Bolsonaro had already been penalized for the initial article in ''Veja'', that there was no testimonial evidence of his plans to plant bombs and that there were \"deep contradictions in the four graphological exams\", two of which failed to conclude that Bolsonaro was indeed the author of the sketches. He ended up acquitted by the majority of the court (9{{nbsp}}x 4{{nbsp}}votes). In December 1988, just after this ruling, Bolsonaro left the Army to begin his political career. In total, he served in the military for fifteen years, reaching the rank of Captain.\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Councilor of Rio de Janeiro (1989\u20131991) ===\n[[File:Bolsonaro em mar\u00e7o de 1990 (Acervo Globo).jpg|thumb|upright|Bolsonaro as Rio de Janeiro city councilor in March 1990. In October of the same year, he was elected Federal Deputy for Rio.]]\nBolsonaro entered politics in 1988, getting elected as [[city councilor]] in Rio de Janeiro, representing the [[Christian Democratic Party (Brazil)|Christian Democratic Party]] (PDC). According to his biography written by his son Fl\u00e1vio, Bolsonaro \"was a candidate for councilor because it happened to be the only option he had at the moment to avoid persecution by some superiors. His entry into politics happened by chance, for his desire was to continue in his military career\".<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nHe spent only two years in the [[Municipal Chamber of Rio de Janeiro]]. He was described as a quiet, discreet and conservative councilor, and showed little participation.<ref name=\"vereador\">{{cite journal |last= |first= |date=26 November 2017 |title=Como vereador, projeto de transporte gratuito para tropas - Pol\u00edtica - Estad\u00e3o |url=https://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,como-vereador-projeto-de-transporte-gratuito-para-tropas,70002097328 |journal=Estad\u00e3o |accessdate= |language=pt}}</ref> His term as councilor was used mainly to give visibility to military causes, such as retirement benefits for former officers.<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book |url= |title=Jair Messias Bolsonaro - Mito ou Verdade |last=Bolsonaro |first=Fl\u00e1vio |publisher=Altadena Editora |year=2017 |location=Rio de Janeiro |isbn=9788594307002|ref=harv|language=pt-br|pages=77\u201379}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal Deputy for Rio de Janeiro (1991\u20132018) ===\nIn the 1990 elections, he was elected as a [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|federal deputy]] for the Christian Democratic Party. Bolsonaro served seven consecutive terms, from 1991 to 2018. He has been affiliated with several other Brazilian political parties over the years. In 2014, he was the congressman who gained the most votes in Rio de Janeiro, with 465,000 votes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://eleicoes.uol.com.br/2014/noticias/2014/10/05/bolsonaro-rj-e-eleito-deputado-federal-no-rj-com-o-maior-numero-de-votos.htm |title=Bolsonaro (PP) \u00e9 o deputado federal com maior n\u00famero de votos no RJ - Not\u00edcias - UOL Elei\u00e7\u00f5es 2014 |work=UOL Elei\u00e7\u00f5es 2014 |access-date=2018-10-29 |language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n\nIn his 27 years of service in the [[National Congress of Brazil|Brazilian National Congress]], he put forward one constitutional amendment and at least 171 bills, passing two of them into law.<ref>[https://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,bolsonaro-aprova-dois-projetos-em-26-anos-de-congresso,70001900653 \"Bolsonaro aprova dois projetos em 26 anos de Congresso\"] {{in lang|pt}}. Page accessed on 7 June 2018.</ref> Bolsonaro, who claims to be persecuted by the left-wing parties, said most congressmen do not vote according to their agenda, but \"by who the author of the bill is\".<ref>[https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2015/06/camara-aprova-pela-primeira-vez-emenda-de-jair-bolsonaro.html \"C\u00e2mara aprova pela primeira vez emenda de Jair Bolsonaro\"]. Page accessed on 1 August 2018.</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, Bolsonaro abandoned the [[Social Christian Party (Brazil)|Social Christian Party]] and switched to the [[Social Liberal Party (Brazil)|Social Liberal Party]] (PSL).<ref>{{cite news |title=Deputado Jair Bolsonaro deixa o PSC e se filia ao PSL|trans-title=Congressman Jair Bolsonaro leaves the PSC and joins the PSL |url=https://pleno.news/brasil/politica-nacional/deputado-jair-bolsonaro-deixa-o-psc-e-se-filia-ao-psl.html |accessdate=16 September 2018 |publisher=Pleno |date=5 January 2018 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> Following Bolsonaro's arrival, the PSL adopted [[Conservatism|conservative]] and [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] positions, and its social liberal group ''[[Livres (movement)|Livres]]'' announced their departure from the party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://politica.estadao.com.br/blogs/blog-do-fucs/com-chegada-de-bolsonaro-livres-anuncia-saida-do-psl/|title=Com chegada de Bolsonaro, Livres anuncia sa\u00edda do PSL|publisher=|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nexojornal.com.br/expresso/2018/10/09/Como-o-PSL-tomou-espa%C3%A7o-da-centro-direita-na-C%C3%A2mara|title=Como o PSL tomou espa\u00e7o da centro-direita na C\u00e2mara|website=Nexo Jornal|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Presidential campaign (2018) ===\n{{Main|Jair Bolsonaro presidential campaign}}\nOn 22 July 2018, Bolsonaro was officially nominated by the Social Liberal Party (PSL) as its presidential candidate for the [[2018 Brazilian general election|2018 election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=PSL oficializa candidatura de Jair Bolsonaro \u00e0 Presid\u00eancia, mas adia defini\u00e7\u00e3o de vice |url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/eleicoes/2018/noticia/2018/07/22/psl-confirma-candidatura-de-jair-bolsonaro-a-presidencia-da-republica.ghtml |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> Bolsonaro was also endorsed by the [[Brazilian Labour Renewal Party]]. His coalition name was \"Brazil above everything, God above everyone\" (''Brasil acima de tudo, Deus acima de todos'').<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/eleicoes/2018/brasil-acima-de-tudo-conheca-a-origem-do-slogan-de-bolsonaro-7r6utek3uk1axzyruk1fj9nas |title=Conhe\u00e7a a origem do slogan de Bolsonaro |work=Gazeta do Povo |access-date=2018-11-01 |language=pt-BR}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2017/11/09/jair-bolsonaro-hopes-to-be-brazils-donald-trump |title=Jair Bolsonaro hopes to be Brazil's Donald Trump |work=The Economist |access-date=2018-11-01 |language=en}}</ref> Though contested by two lawsuits, the [[Superior Electoral Court]] of Brazil deferred them and his candidacy was made official on 6{{nbsp}}August.<ref>{{cite news |title=TSE aprova por unanimidade candidatura de Bolsonaro \u00e0 Presid\u00eancia |url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/eleicoes/2018/noticia/2018/09/06/tse-aprova-por-unanimidade-candidatura-de-bolsonaro-a-presidencia.ghtml |work=G1 |accessdate=7 September 2018 |language=pt}}</ref> Bolsonaro announced in August that [[Ant\u00f4nio Hamilton Mour\u00e3o]], a retired army general, would be his running mate for the upcoming election.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/eleicoes/2018/noticia/2018/08/05/bolsonaro-anuncia-general-mourao-como-vice.ghtml |title=Bolsonaro anuncia general Hamilton Mour\u00e3o como vice |date=5 August 2013 |accessdate=21 August 2018 |website=G1}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Protesto pr\u00f3-Bolsonaro em Londres.jpg|thumb|left|Bolsonaro supporters in London, 7{{nbsp}}October 2018]]\nAccording to political pundits, early in the campaign, Bolsonaro moderated his tone, taking a less aggressive and confrontational style. Economically, he started to support the idea of less government intervention in the economy (in contrast to what he had stated in the past, when he defended [[Developmentalism|developmentalists]] policies). On the other hand, he maintained his tough stance on crime and his defense of \"traditional family values\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolsonaro modera discurso econ\u00f4mico em aceno ao mercado |url= https://istoe.com.br/bolsonaro-modera-discurso-economico-em-aceno-ao-mercado/|work= Isto \u00c9 magazine|accessdate=7 September 2018|language=pt}}</ref> Bolsonaro also said he planned to cut [[Taxation in Brazil|taxes]] across the board, particularly on inheritances and businesses, in order to generate growth and tackle unemployment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolsonaro quer menos fiscal em empresas e nenhum imposto sobre heran\u00e7a|url=https://www.valor.com.br/politica/5574761/bolsonaro-quer-menos-fiscal-em-empresas-e-nenhum-imposto-sobre-heranca|work=Valor Econ\u00f4mico|accessdate=7 September 2018|language=pt}}</ref> He also promised more [[austerity]] measures and cuts in government spending, but had difficulty naming the areas where he would make these cuts. He also mentioned he would work to diminish the size and bureaucracy of the federal government by enacting a wide variety of [[deregulation]] measures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/brasil/em-encontro-com-empresarios-bolsonaro-promete-gestao-austera-corte-de-impostos-22851805|title=Em encontro com empres\u00e1rios, Bolsonaro promete gest\u00e3o austera e e corte de impostos |date=4 July 2018|accessdate=8 September 2018|website=G1}}</ref> Bolsonaro's promises to [[Law and order (politics)|restore security]] amid [[Crime in Brazil|record high crime]] and to stamp out the country's rampant [[Corruption in Brazil|political corruption]] won him huge popular support.<ref>{{cite news |title=How Women Could Win It for Bolsonaro |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/10/26/how-women-could-win-it-for-bolsonaro/ |work=Foreign Policy |date=26 October 2018}}</ref> In October, Bolsonaro announced he would name [[Economic liberalism|liberal]] economist [[Paulo Guedes]] to serve as his finance minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/eleicoes,bolsonaro-anuncia-nomes-de-tres-ministros-em-eventual-governo,70002544037|title=Bolsonaro anuncia nomes de tr\u00eas ministros em eventual governo - Pol\u00edtica|website=Estad\u00e3o|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 August 2018, he attended the first presidential debate of the year, organized by the TV network [[Rede Bandeirantes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Band faz primeiro debate com candidatos ao Planalto nesta quinta |url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2018/08/band-faz-primeiro-debate-com-candidatos-ao-planalto-nesta-quinta.shtml|work=Folha.uol.com.br|accessdate=7 September 2018|language=pt}}</ref> A week later, there was another debate at [[RedeTV!]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Oito presidenci\u00e1veis discutem propostas de governo no segundo debate da campanha eleitoral de 2018|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/eleicoes/2018/noticia/2018/08/18/oito-presidenciaveis-discutem-propostas-de-governo-no-segundo-debate-da-campanha-eleitoral-de-2018.ghtml|work=G1|accessdate=7 September 2018|language=pt}}</ref> On 28 August, he gave an interview to [[Jornal Nacional]], Brazil's best rated prime time news program, at [[Rede Globo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jair Bolsonaro (PSL) \u00e9 entrevistado no Jornal Nacional|url=https://g1.globo.com/jornal-nacional/noticia/2018/08/28/jair-bolsonaro-psl-e-entrevistado-no-jornal-nacional.ghtml|work=G1|accessdate=7 September 2018|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nJair Bolsonaro was the first candidate for the presidency to raise over [[Brazilian real|R$]]1 million in donations from the public during the 2018 campaign. In the first 59 days, he amassed an average of R$17,000 per day in donations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolsonaro \u00e9 1\u00ba presidenci\u00e1vel a arrecadar mais de R$ 1 milh\u00e3o em vaquinha|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/politica/eleicoes/2018/noticias/2018/09/03/bolsonaro-arrecada-mais-de-r-1-milhao-veja-quanto-renderam-vaquinhas.htm|work=UOL Elei\u00e7\u00f5es|accessdate=7 September 2018|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Workers' Party]] candidate [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] was arrested in April 2018, Bolsonaro became the front-runner, according to all major opinion polls, for that year's presidential election.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/brazil/2018-07-12/will-brazils-next-president-be-far-right-nationalist|title=Will Brazil's Next President be a Far-Right Nationalist?|journal=Foreign Affairs|accessdate=30 September 2018|date=2018-07-12}}</ref><ref name=\"Disciple\">{{cite news | last1=Brooks | first1=Brad | title=A Disciple of Brazil's Dictatorship Moves Closer to the Presidency | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-election-bolsonaro-newsmaker/a-disciple-of-brazils-dictatorship-moves-closer-to-the-presidency-idUSKCN1MF1DP | date=5 October 2018 | newspaper=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> A ''[[Datafolha]]'' poll from September, for instance, showed Bolsonaro as the leading candidate in the first round with 28% of vote intentions; however, run-off scenarios showed Bolsonaro losing to opponents [[Geraldo Alckmin]], [[Fernando Haddad]] and [[Ciro Gomes]] and tying with [[Marina Silva]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/eleicoes,bolsonaro-mantem-lideranca-mas-perde-para-adversarios-no-2-turno-diz-pesquisa,70002524399|title=Bolsonaro mant\u00e9m lideran\u00e7a mas perde para advers\u00e1rios no 2\u00ba turno, diz pesquisa|work=Estado de S\u00e3o Paulo|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> Another poll from ''Datafolha'', conducted in the week leading up to election day, showed a considerable surge for Bolsonaro, who had 40% of vote intentions, or 36% when null or blank vote intentions were included. Fernando Haddad came in second with 25%, and Ciro Gomes in third with 15%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/eleicoes/2018/noticia/2018/10/06/datafolha-para-presidente-votos-validos-bolsonaro-40-haddad-25-ciro-15-alckmin-8.ghtml|title=Datafolha para presidente, votos v\u00e1lidos: Bolsonaro, 40%; Haddad, 25%; Ciro, 15%; Alckmin, 8%|work=G1|accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe first round of the election occurred on 7{{nbsp}}October 2018. Bolsonaro finished in first place with 46% of the popular vote (or 49.2 million people). Since he failed to win overall 50% of valid votes needed to win outright, he faced the second most voted, Fernando Haddad from the Workers' Party, in a runoff held on 28 October 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-45780176|title=Jair Bolsonaro: Far-right candidate wins first round of Brazil election|work=BBC|accessdate=8 October 2018|date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2019 Solenidade de Assinatura do Decreto que revoga o Hor\u00e1rio de Ver\u00e3o (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Bolsonaro is known for his [[finger-gun]] gesture, which he used during the presidential campaign.]]\nAfter the first round, when his victory looked certain, Bolsonaro gave a speech by videolink to thousands of supporters who gathered at Paulista Avenue, in S\u00e3o Paulo. In the speech, he threatened to arrest, purge or kill \"reds\" and \"petralhas\" (a derogatory term for Worker's Party's members), and promised that members of the social movements [[Landless Workers' Movement|MST]] and [[Homeless Workers' Movement|MTST]] would be treated as \"terrorists\". He said: \"This time, the clean-up will be even greater. This group [\"reds\"], if they want to stay, will have to abide by our laws{{nbsp}}... These red outlaws will be banned from our homeland. Either they go overseas, or they go to jail{{nbsp}}... Petralhada, you all go to the edge of the beach. It will be a cleaning never seen in the history of Brazil\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://br.reuters.com/article/topNews/idBRKCN1MW017-OBRTP|title=\"Esses marginais vermelhos ser\u00e3o banidos de nossa p\u00e1tria\", diz{{nbsp}}...|date=22 October 2018|website=Br.reuters.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/22/brazils-jair-bolsonaro-says-he-would-put-army-on-streets-to-fight|title=Brazil's Jair Bolsonaro threatens purge of leftwing 'outlaws'|first=Tom Phillips Latin America|last=correspondent|date=22 October 2018|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> The \"edge of the beach\", it was later confirmed by a Bolsonaro aide, was a reference to a [[Brazilian Navy|Navy]] base at [[Restinga da Marambaia]], in Rio de Janeiro State, where dissidents of the [[Brazilian military dictatorship]] were tortured and killed by the regime.<ref name=\"uol.com.br\">{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2018/12/bolsonaro-fez-referencia-a-area-de-desova-de-mortos-pela-ditadura.shtml|title=Bolsonaro fez refer\u00eancia a \u00e1rea de desova de mortos pela ditadura|date=29 December 2018|website=Folha de S.Paulo}}</ref> The speech was widely condemned by rivals, journalists and politicians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jornalggn.com.br/eleicoes/fascismo-ditadura-morte-da-democracia-as-reacoes-a-ameaca-de-bolsonaro-aos-adversarios-politicos-e-a-folha/|title=Fascismo e ditadura: as rea\u00e7\u00f5es \u00e0 amea\u00e7a de Bolsonaro aos advers\u00e1rios pol\u00edticos e \u00e0 Folha|first=C\u00edntia|last=Alves|date=22 October 2018|website=Jornalggn.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogdosakamoto.blogosfera.uol.com.br/2018/10/22/apos-justica-demonstrar-fraqueza-bolsonaro-avisa-que-banira-opositores/|title=Ap\u00f3s Justi\u00e7a demonstrar fraqueza, Bolsonaro avisa que banir\u00e1 opositores|website=blogdosakamoto.blogosfera.uol.com.br}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://epoca.globo.com/conrado-hubner-mendes/nunca-mais-nunca-menos-23195184|title=Nunca mais, nunca menos|first=Conrado H\u00fcbner|last=Mendes|date=29 October 2018|website=\u00c9poca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/ilustrissima/2019/01/bolsonaro-inaugura-o-presidencialismo-de-assombracao-diz-renato-lessa.shtml|title=Bolsonaro inaugura o presidencialismo de assombra\u00e7\u00e3o, diz Renato Lessa|date=5 January 2019|website=Folha de S.Paulo}}</ref>\n\nBolsonaro won the runoff election with 55.13% of the votes, and was elected the 38th president of Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/amphtml/world/the_americas/brazilians-vote-in-presidential-election-with-a-trump-fan-as-front-runner/2018/10/07/7d82d512-c65d-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html|title=Brazil's far-right candidate takes big lead in presidential election|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/28/jair-bolsonaro-wins-brazil-presidential-election|title=Jair Bolsonaro declared Brazil's next president|first=Tom Phillips Dom Phillips in Rio de|last=Janeiro|date=29 October 2018|accessdate=7 December 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/28/world/americas/jair-bolsonaro-brazil-election.html|title=Jair Bolsonaro Wins Brazil's Presidency, in a Shift to the Far Right|first1=Ernesto|last1=Londo\u00f1o|first2=Shasta|last2=Darlington|date=28 October 2018|publisher=|accessdate=7 December 2018|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> He took office on 1{{nbsp}}January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/world/jair-bolsonaro-sworn-in-as-president-of-brazil/video/f7fa46708a7a55391d7b9391b5aa0db8|title=Jair Bolsonaro sworn in as president of Brazil|date=2019-01-02|website=Herald Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign, academics repeatedly raised concerns on the consequences of Bolsonaro's rise for the Brazilian democracy. Writing for the news magazine ''[[Foreign Policy]]'', [[Federico Finchelstein]], a historian at the [[New School for Social Research]] who specializes in fascism, said: \"Bolsonaro's vocabulary recalls the rhetoric behind Nazi policies of persecution and victimization. But does sounding like a Nazi make him a Nazi? Insomuch as he believes in holding elections, he is not there yet. However, things could change quickly if he gains power.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/10/05/bolsonaros-model-its-goebbels-fascism-nazism-brazil-latin-america-populism-argentina-venezuela/|title=Jair Bolsonaro's Model Isn't Berlusconi. It's Goebbels.|first=Federico|last=Finchelstein|website=Foreignpolicy.com}}</ref> [[Jason Stanley]], a [[Yale]] philosopher who has published widely on Nazism, argued in an interview that Bolsonaro \"uses more tactics associated to fascism than [the] American president Donald Trump\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/internacional/en/world/2018/10/bolsonaro-uses-same-fascist-tactics-as-trump-says-yale-professor.shtml|title=Bolsonaro Uses Same Fascist Tactics As Trump, Says Yale Professor|date=4 October 2018|website=Folha de S.Paulo}}</ref> [[Harvard University|Harvard]]'s [[Steven Levitsky]] stated that Bolsonaro \"is clearly authoritarian\", but not a fascist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/brasil-45829323|title=Por que este professor de Harvard acredita que a democracia brasileira est\u00e1 em risco|first=Ricardo|last=Ferraz|date=19 October 2018|website=Bbc.com}}</ref> Similar concerns were raised by analysts in Portugal<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publico.pt/2018/10/06/mundo/opiniao/bolsonaro-um-fascista-e-um-fascista-1846282|title=Bolsonaro: um fascista \u00e9 um fascista|first=Jo\u00e3o Miguel|last=Tavares|website=P\u00daBLICO}}</ref> and Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nexojornal.com.br/colunistas/2018/N%C3%A3o-use-a-palavra-%E2%80%98fascismo%E2%80%99-em-v%C3%A3o|title=N\u00e3o use a palavra 'fascismo' em v\u00e3o|website=Nexo Jornal}}</ref> Others, such as Marxist historian [[Perry Anderson]], dismissed the \"fascist\" and \"populist\" labels altogether.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/v41/n03/perry-anderson/bolsonaros-brazil|title=Bolsonaro's Brazil|first=Perry|last=Anderson|date=7 February 2019|publisher=|pages=11\u201322|via=London Review of Books}}</ref>\n\nAnother highly controversial aspect of the campaign was the alleged use of illegal digital communication strategies by some of Bolsonaro's most important financial supporters. According to an investigation by ''[[Folha de S.Paulo]]'', one of Brazil's best selling newspapers, \"Bolsonaro has been getting an illegal helping hand from a group of Brazilian entrepreneurs who are bankrolling a campaign to bombard [[WhatsApp]] users with [[fake news]] about [Fernando] Haddad.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/18/brazil-jair-bolsonaro-whatsapp-fake-news-campaign|title=Bolsonaro business backers accused of illegal Whatsapp fake news campaign|first=Tom Phillips Latin America|last=correspondent|date=18 October 2018|publisher=|accessdate=9 March 2019|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> The suspicions led to a formal investigation by electoral authorities and the Federal Police; Bolsonaro and allies denied any wrongdoing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2018/10/19/politica/1539978047_019665.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105220232/https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2018/10/19/politica/1539978047_019665.html |archive-date=5 November 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Another controversial point was that Ta\u00edse Feij\u00f3 who is currently an adviser in Bolsonaro's government was among those paid to feed fake news to his supporters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/brazil-jair-bolsonaro-whatsapp_n_5d542b0de4b05fa9df088ccc|title=WhatsApp Is Radicalizing The Right In Bolsonaro's Brazil|last=Nemer|first=David|date=2019-08-16|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Assassination attempt during campaign ====\n[[File:Bolsonaro \u00e9 esfaqueado (2).jpg|thumb|The moment Bolsonaro was attacked at the [[Juiz de Fora]] rally]]\nBolsonaro was stabbed in the abdomen on 6{{nbsp}}September 2018 while campaigning and interacting with supporters in the city of [[Juiz de Fora]], [[Minas Gerais]].<ref name=\"Londono18\">{{cite news |last1=Londo\u00f1o |first1=Ernesto |title=Brazil Presidential Candidate Jair Bolsonaro Is Stabbed at Campaign Rally |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/06/world/americas/brazil-jair-bolsonaro.html |accessdate=6 September 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=6 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref> At first, his son [[Fl\u00e1vio Bolsonaro]] stated that his father's wounds were only superficial and he was recovering in the hospital,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Phillips |first1=Dom |title=Jair Bolsonaro: Brazil's far-right presidential hopeful stabbed at campaign rally |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/06/brazil-jair-bolsonaro-far-right-presidential-candidate-stabbed |accessdate=6 September 2018 |work=the Guardian |date=6 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref> but Fl\u00e1vio later stated that the wounds seemed worse than initially thought<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/right-wing-brazilian-presidential-candidate-jair-bolsonaro-stabbed-while-campaigning/2018/09/06/62381332-b20b-11e8-8b53-50116768e499_story.html|title=Brazilian presidential front-runner is stabbed while campaigning|last=|first=|date=6 September 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=}}</ref> and his father most likely would not be able to start campaigning personally before the end of the first round.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-45451473|title=Stabbed Brazil politician 'lost 40% blood'|date=8 September 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> He tweeted about his father's condition, explaining that the perforation reached parts of the liver, lung, and intestine. He also stated that Bolsonaro had lost a large amount of blood, arriving at the hospital with severe [[hypotension]] (his [[blood pressure]] was 10/3, equivalent to 100/30 mmHg), but that he had since stabilized.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/FlavioBolsonaro/status/1037808900660256773|title=Fl\u00e1vio Bolsonaro 177 Senador_RJ Verified account|last=Fl\u00e1vio|first=Bolsonaro|date=6 September 2018|website=Twitter|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=6 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Savarese |first1=Mauricio |last2=Prengaman |first2=Peter |title=Brazilian candidate Jair Bolsonaro stabbed during event |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/brazilian-candidate-jair-bolsonaro-stabbed-event-57652075 |accessdate=6 September 2018 |work=ABC News |date=6 September 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906232058/https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/brazilian-candidate-jair-bolsonaro-stabbed-event-57652075 |archive-date=6 September 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Londono18\" /> The attack was condemned by most of the other candidates in the presidential race, from both sides of the political spectrum, and by then current [[President of Brazil|Brazilian president]] [[Michel Temer]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolsonaro leva facada em MG: veja repercuss\u00e3o |url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/eleicoes/2018/noticia/2018/09/06/bolsonaro-leva-facada-veja-repercussao.ghtml |accessdate=6 September 2018 |work=G1.com |date=6 September 2018 |language=pt}}</ref> The day after the attack, Bolsonaro was transferred to the [[Albert Einstein Israelite Hospital]], in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], after a request from his family. According to the doctors, he was in an \"extremely stable\" condition.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jair Bolsonaro \u00e9 internado no Hospital Albert Einstein, em SP|url=https://g1.globo.com/sp/sao-paulo/noticia/2018/09/07/jair-bolsonaro-chega-a-sao-paulo-para-ser-internado-no-albert-einstein.ghtml|work=G1|accessdate=7 September 2018|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nPolice arrested and identified the attacker as Ad\u00e9lio Bispo de Oliveira, who, according to security agents, claimed he was on \"a mission from God\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Brazilian presidential candidate stabbed at campaign rally|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/brazilian-candidate-stabbed-gets-hospital-almost-dead-n907311|date=6 September 2018|work=NBC News|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> He had been a member of the [[Socialism and Liberty Party]] between 2007 and 2014. His social media posts included political criticisms against both Bolsonaro and Temer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Quem \u00e9 o autor do ataque a Bolsonaro|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2018/09/07/politica/1536275050_403883.html|work=El Pa\u00eds Brasil|accessdate=7 September 2018|language=pt}}</ref> However, an initial investigation by the Federal Police concluded that Ad\u00e9lio had no help from political organizations and acted alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/jornal-nacional/noticia/2018/09/28/pf-conclui-que-agressor-de-jair-bolsonaro-agiu-sozinho.ghtml|title=PF conclui que agressor de Jair Bolsonaro agiu sozinho|website=G1}}</ref> A medical report produced for a second investigation about the murder attempt concluded that Ad\u00e9lio is mentally disturbed, having a \"permanent paranoid delusional disorder\" which, according to the Brazilian law, prevents him from being considered legally liable for his actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/mg/minas-gerais/noticia/2019/03/07/laudo-aponta-que-agressor-de-bolsonaro-tem-doenca-mental.ghtml|title=Laudo aponta que agressor de Bolsonaro tem doen\u00e7a mental|website=G1}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 September, a month after the attack, Bolsonaro was released from the hospital and returned to his home in Rio de Janeiro. However, his condition prevented him from returning to the campaign trail for the remainder of the first round of the presidential election.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolsonaro recebe alta e deixa hospital em S\u00e3o Paulo|url=https://g1.globo.com/sp/sao-paulo/eleicoes/2018/noticia/2018/09/29/bolsonaro-recebe-alta-de-hospital-em-sao-paulo-diz-presidente-do-psl.ghtml|work=G1|accessdate=30 September 2018|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n==== Protests ====\n{{Main|Ele N\u00e3o movement}}\n[[File:EleNao (Porto Alegre, 2018-09-29) 63.jpg|thumb|Demonstration against Bolsonaro in [[Porto Alegre]], part of the [[Ele N\u00e3o movement]]]]\nIn the same weekend he left the hospital, thousands of people took the streets in dozens of cities in Brazil to protest against Bolsonaro and his political stances, chanting \"''{{lang|pt|Ele n\u00e3o}}''\" (\"Not him\").<ref name=\"globalnews\">{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4500818/jair-bolsonaro-brazil-election-protests/|title=Thousands protest leading far-right presidential candidate in Brazil|work=Global News|accessdate=30 September 2018|date=2018-09-29}}</ref> There were also rallies in support of the candidate in sixteen states.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/jornal-nacional/noticia/2018/09/29/manifestacoes-a-favor-de-bolsonaro-ocorrem-em-16-estados.ghtml|title=Manifesta\u00e7\u00f5es a favor de Bolsonaro ocorrem em 16 estados|work=G1|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Presidency (2019\u2013present) ===\n{{main|Presidency of Jair Bolsonaro}}\n[[File:Solenidades. Homenagens (44744824410).jpg|thumb|left|[[Michel Temer]] with Bolsonaro and his wife [[Michelle Bolsonaro|Michelle]] during the [[Brazilian presidential inauguration|inauguration]] on 1{{nbsp}}January 2019]]\nBolsonaro was sworn in as President of the Republic on 1{{nbsp}}January 2019, succeeding [[Michel Temer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/will-bolsonaro-win-brazil-usher-right-wing-ripple-effects-latin-n926816|title=Will Bolsonaro's victory in Brazil usher right-wing ripple effects in Latin America?|website=NBC News|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> Bolsonaro began his [[Bolsonaro administration cabinet members|cabinet formation]] before winning the presidency, having chosen economist [[Paulo Guedes]] as his Economy minister and astronaut [[Marcos Pontes]] as his Science and Technology minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2018/10/31/bolsonaro-anuncia-astronauta-marcos-pontes-como-ministro-da-ciencia-e-tecnologia.ghtml|title=Bolsonaro anuncia astronauta Marcos Pontes como ministro da Ci\u00eancia e Tecnologia|website=G1|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> Bolsonaro initially said his cabinet would be composed of 15 members; this figure later rose to 22 when he announced his final minister, [[Ricardo Salles]], in December. His predecessor, [[Michel Temer]], had a cabinet of 29 members.<ref name=P360Cabinet>{{cite web|url=https://www.poder360.com.br/governo/saiba-quem-sao-os-22-ministros-da-esplanada-de-bolsonaro/|title=Saiba quem s\u00e3o os 22 ministros da Esplanada de Bolsonaro|author=|date=10 December 2018|website=Poder360|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nBolsonaro's [[Cabinet of Brazil|cabinet]] is composed of 16 ministers, two cabinet-level positions, and four presidency secretaries including Chief of Staff [[Onyx Lorenzoni]].<ref name=P360Cabinet /> Bolsonaro's ministries include [[Operation Car Wash]] judge [[S\u00e9rgio Moro]] as Justice minister and congresswoman [[Tereza Cristina]] as Agriculture minister.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-46063656|title=Brazil top judge becomes justice minister|date=1 November 2018|publisher=|accessdate=7 December 2018|website=Bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,bolsonaro-escolhe-deputada-tereza-cristina-para-chefiar-ministerio-da-agricultura,70002593049|title=Bolsonaro escolhe deputada Tereza Cristina para chefiar Minist\u00e9rio da Agricultura - Pol\u00edtica|website=Estad\u00e3o|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nBolsonaro has stripped the indigenous affairs agency [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional do \u00cdndio|FUNAI]] of the responsibility to identify and demarcate [[Indigenous territory (Brazil)|indigenous lands]]. He argued that those territories have very tiny isolated populations, who would be controlled by NPOs, and proposed to integrate them into the larger Brazilian society. Critics feared that such integration would lead the Brazilian natives to suffer [[cultural assimilation]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Brazil's new president makes it harder to define indigenous lands |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4808295/jair-bolsonaro-funai-indigenous-farm-brazil/ |work=Global News |date=January 2, 2019}}</ref> Argentine President [[Mauricio Macri]] was the first foreign leader to be received by Bolsonaro on a state visit to [[Bras\u00edlia]] since he assumed the Brazilian presidency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-16/all-smiles-in-brasilia-as-macri-and-bolsonaro-reset-relationship|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Bolsonaro with Argentine President Mauricio Macri at the Casa Rosada.jpg|right|thumb|Bolsonaro with Argentine President [[Mauricio Macri]], June 2019]]\n\nThe [[second inauguration of Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] in Venezuela took place nine days after [[Brazilian presidential inauguration#Inauguration of Jair Bolsonaro|Bolsonaro's inauguration]]. The disputed results of the [[2018 Venezuelan presidential election]] led to the [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis]], as the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] rejected the results, considered Maduro an illegitimate ruler since his first term of office ended, and appointed [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] as acting president. Bolsonaro did not attend Maduro's inauguration and recognized Guaid\u00f3 as the legitimate ruler of Venezuela, alongside [[Mauricio Macri]] from Argentina and [[Donald Trump]] from the US, among others.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-argentina/brazil-argentina-step-up-pressure-on-venezuelas-maduro-idUSKCN1PA23T|title= Brazil, Argentina step up pressure on Venezuela's Maduro|author= Anthony Boadle|date= January 16, 2019|publisher= Reuters|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> He said that \"We will continue doing everything possible to re-establish order, democracy and freedom there\".<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-venezuela/brazils-bolsonaro-pledges-action-to-restore-democracy-in-venezuela-idUSKCN1PC00N |title= Brazil's Bolsonaro pledges action to 'restore democracy' in Venezuela|author= |date= January 17, 2019|publisher= Reuters|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> After allegations of campaign-finance fraud, Bolsonaro fired [[Gustavo Bebianno]], a top adviser and general secretary for the president. His party was accused of diverting public campaign funds to candidates who did not run for office.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazils-bolsonaro-fires-top-adviser-amid-accusations-of-campaign-finance-fraud-11550534863|title= Brazil's Bolsonaro Fires Key Adviser Amid Accusations of Campaign-Finance Fraud|author1= Paulo Trevisani|author2= Jeffrey T. Lewis|date= February 18, 2019|publisher= Wall Street Journal|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSince his election, his popularity is steadily declining. A ''Datafolha'' survey, published on 21 May 2019, showed that 34% of respondents described Bolsonaro's administration as \"great or good\"; 26% as \"regular\", 36% as \"bad or awful\", while 4% did not respond. This is the first time more Brazilians reject the politics of Bolsonaro than affirming it.<ref>[https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2019/05/21/politica/1558459667_020362.html Desaprova\u00e7\u00e3o do Governo Bolsonaro supera aprova\u00e7\u00e3o pela primeira vez, mostra pesquisa Atlas Pol\u00edtico]</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n[[File:Jair Bolsonaro na c\u00e2mara sobre a comiss\u00e3o da verdade.jpg|thumb|Bolsonaro in 2010]]\nBolsonaro's political views have been described as [[Brazilian nationalism|nationalist]] and [[Right-wing populism|populist]] in nature, and he himself as an advocate of [[Far-right politics|far-right]] policies.<ref>{{cite news|first=Anthony|last=Boadle|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-politics-bolsonaro-interview/far-right-presidential-hopeful-aims-to-be-brazils-trump-idUSKCN1C2384|title=Far-right presidential hopeful aims to be Brazil's Trump|agency=[[Reuters]]|location=London, England|date=27 September 2017|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"opendemocracy\">{{cite web|first=Pedro Henrique|last=Leal|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/democraciaabierta/pedro-henrique-leal/bolsonaro-and-brazilian-far-right|title=Bolsonaro and the Brazilian far right|website=opendemocracy.net|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> His supporters, however, claim that his views are more aligned with traditional right-wing [[conservatism]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Katy|last=Watson|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-43414315|title=Brazil's rising tide of young conservatives seeks change|website=[[BBC News]]|publisher=BBC|location=London, England|date=2 April 2018|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> His electorate is mainly formed by adults above the age of 34, the working [[Middle class|middle]] to upper class (mainly in the southeast region of the country), conservatives in general, college graduates, some centrists and the [[Christian right]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/brasil/renda-estudo-regiao-separam-eleitores-de-lula-bolsonaro-21286515|title=Renda, estudo e regi\u00e3o separam eleitores de Lula e Bolsonaro|date=3 May 2017|website=O Globo}}</ref> According to some polls, Bolsonaro's main support comes from the [[Southeast Region, Brazil|southeast]], [[Central-West Region, Brazil|central-west]] and [[South Region, Brazil|south]] regions of Brazil. His voters are usually male and [[White Brazilians|white]], with a noticeable gender gap, with Bolsonaro polling poorly among female voters (mustering only 18% support with this demographic).<ref name=\"globalnews\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2017/12/1945680-nichos-realcam-contrastes-de-eleitores-de-lula-e-bolsonaro.shtml|title=Nichos real\u00e7am contrastes de eleitores de Lula e Bolsonaro|publisher=Folha de S\u00e3o Paulo|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.r7.com/eleicoes-2018/ibope-mostra-queda-de-8-pontos-de-bolsonaro-na-regiao-sul-24092018|title=Ibope mostra queda de 8 pontos de Bolsonaro na regi\u00e3o Sul|publisher=R7|accessdate=30 September 2018|date=2018-09-25}}</ref> Just before the 2018 election, however, it was reported that female support for him had risen to 27%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/10/brazil-bolsonaro-election-far-right-lula-election/572203/|title=A Brazilian Far-Right Populist and the Women Who Like Him|publisher=The Atlantic|accessdate=4 October 2018|date=2018-10-04}}</ref>\n\nBolsonaro is viewed as a [[Anti-abortion movements|pro-life]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-45982501|title=Jair Bolsonaro beyond the sound bites: What are his policies?|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 October 2019|date=28 October 2018}}</ref> [[anti-establishment]] and [[Overview of gun laws by nation#Brazil|pro-gun]] politician, voicing opposition to most forms of [[Gun laws in Brazil|gun control]] legislation, arguing that law-abiding citizens have the right to self-defense, especially those living in rural areas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/apr/19/jair-bolsonaro-brazil-presidential-candidate-trump-parallels|title=Trump of the tropics: the 'dangerous' candidate leading Brazil's presidential race|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=27 October 2018|date=2018-04-19|last1=Phillips|first1=Tom}}</ref> According to ''The Washington Post'', \"Homicides hit a [[Crime in Brazil|record high]] of 63,880 last year [...] Bolsonaro's solution is zero tolerance. He has called for police to use more lethal force and wants to relax gun laws so that average citizens can defend themselves.\"<ref name=\"environment\">{{cite news |title=Who is Jair Bolsonaro, the man likely to be Brazil's next president? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2018/10/28/critics-are-afraid-jair-bolsonaro-heres-where-he-stands-issues/ |work=The Washington Post |date=28 October 2018}}</ref> Bolsonaro often rejects accusations made against him of [[misogyny]] and [[homophobia]], and says he is not \"far-right\", but simply right-wing.<ref name=\"estadaomarco\">{{cite news|first=Constan\u00e7a|last=Rezende|url=https://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,bolsonaro-quer-campo-de-refugiados-em-roraima,70002226010|title=Bolsonaro quer campo de refugiados em Roraima|newspaper=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]]|publisher=Grupo Estado|location=S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil|date=14 March 2018|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Brazil protest 2016 March.jpg|thumb|left|Bolsonaro was one of the key political figures in support of the [[impeachment of Dilma Rousseff]] and the [[2015\u201316 protests in Brazil|2015\u201316 protests against corruption]], galvanizing a lot of support for his cause among the populace.]]\nJair Bolsonaro is known for his strong opposition to [[Left-wing politics|left-wing policies]]. Most notably, he has been a vocal opponent of [[Same-sex marriage in Brazil|same-sex marriage]],<ref name=\"noticias.terra.com.br\"/> environmental regulations,<ref name=\"Atkins 2018\">{{cite web | last=Atkins | first=Ed | title=Jair Bolsonaro's Brazil Is a Disaster for the Amazon and Global Climate Change | website=Motherboard | date=2018-10-29 | url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/43ejw3/jair-bolsonaros-brazil-is-a-disaster-for-the-amazon-and-global-climate-change | access-date=2018-10-30}}</ref> abortion,<ref name=\"osul.com.br\"/> [[affirmative action]] (particularly racial quotas),<ref name=\"Pol\u00edtica\"/> immigration<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jornalopcao.com.br/ultimas-noticias/bolsonaro-ve-imigrantes-como-ameaca-e-chama-refugiados-de-a-escoria-do-mundo-46043/|title=Bolsonaro v\u00ea imigrantes como \"amea\u00e7a\" e chama refugiados de \"a esc\u00f3ria do mundo\" - Jornal Op\u00e7\u00e3o|date=18 September 2015|publisher=|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> (particularly from Haiti, Africa and the Middle East, which he once called \"the scum of humanity\"),<ref name=\"opendemocracy\" /> [[drug liberalization]],<ref name=\"epoca2\"/> land reforms,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olhardireto.com.br/noticias/exibir.asp?noticia=em-mato-grosso-bolsonaro-defende-radicalizacao-dos-produtores-contra-mst&id=410525|title=Em Mato Grosso, Bolsonaro defende radicaliza\u00e7\u00e3o dos produtores contra MST|publisher=|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> and secularism at the federal level,<ref name=\"epoca2\"/> among other things.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americasquarterly.org/content/jair-bolsonaro-pro-torture-anti-gay-and-brazils-future-president|title=Jair Bolsonaro: Pro-Torture, Anti-Gay and Brazil's Future President?|website=Americasquarterly.org|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> He has also made statements in defense of the [[Brazilian military regime]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebc.com.br/noticias/politica/2013/02/jair-bolsonaro-defende-golpe-militar-de-1964-em-recepcao-a-yoani-sanchez|title=Jair Bolsonaro defende golpe militar de 1964 em recep\u00e7\u00e3o a Yoani S\u00e1nchez|date=20 February 2013|publisher=|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> (a dictatorship known for constant human rights violations).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/14/brazil-jair-bolsonaro-energy-drink-bolsomito|title=Brazil's far-right presidential contender gets soft drink named after him|first=Dom|last=Phillips|date=14 January 2018|newspaper=the Guardian|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> He argues that torture is a \"legitimate practice\" and says that he would try to pass new legislation regarding the introduction of life imprisonment to the Brazilian penal code.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com.br/istoegente/28/reportagens/entrev_jair.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531142150/http://www.terra.com.br/istoegente/28/reportagens/entrev_jair.htm|archivedate=2013-05-31|title=Terra \u2013 ISTO GENTE \u2013 Entrevista: Jair Bolsonaro|date=31 May 2013|publisher=|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> Bolsonaro supports the privatization of state-owned companies and advocates free market policies,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2017/10/1925458-bolsonaro-diz-que-e-liberal-e-adota-discurso-que-agrada-investidores.shtml|title=Bolsonaro diz que \u00e9 liberal e adota discurso que agrada investidores|website=1.folha.uol.com.br}}</ref> although critics have stated that his policy-making record does not in fact show him to be a supporter of [[economic liberalism]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://jornalggn.com.br/eleicoes/em-7-mandatos-bolsonaro-nao-foi-um-deputado-liberal-nem-totalmente-anti-pt/|title=Em 7 mandatos, Bolsonaro n\u00e3o foi um deputado liberal nem totalmente anti-PT|first=C\u00edntia|last=Alves|date=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2017 interview with journalist Claudio Dantas Sequeira from ''O Antagonista'', Bolsonaro said that his views are directly aligned with the centrist to right-wing United States citizens' views on gun ownership, abortion, gender politics, and trade, despite the \"left-leaning media frenzy\" against him. He reiterated that he intends to reverse some disarmament laws, improve public security, and also improve trade ties with the United States, which he said were broken during [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva|Lula da Silva]]'s and [[Dilma Rousseff]]'s administrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=etEDQOZJJK0|title=ENTREVISTA &#124; Bolsonaro revela a O Antagonista seus planos para a Presid\u00eancia|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Press conference EU-Mercosul on June 26, 2019 (VII).jpg|thumb|Bolsonaro supported the [[European Union\u2013Mercosur Free Trade Agreement]], which would form one of the world's largest free trade areas.]]\n\nBolsonaro has, during his long political career, expressed views regarded as being far-right.<ref>{{cite news|title=With Rousseff on the ropes, Brazil's far right sees an opening|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/05/brazil-far-right-dilma-rousseff-impeachment |newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=18 June 2017|date=2016-05-05|last1=Watts|first1=Jonathan}}</ref> He has made statements that some people considered insulting, homophobic,<ref name=\"dw-homophobia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/unlikely-and-unlikable-jair-bolsonaro-could-lead-brazil/a-45083300|title=Unlikely and unlikable, Jair Bolsonaro could lead Brazil|website=DW.com}}</ref> violence-inciting,<ref name=\"globo-violence-inciting\">{{cite web|url=http://oglobo.globo.com/cultura/ellen-page-confronta-jair-bolsonaro-em-cena-de-documentario-18855202|title=Ellen Page confronta Jair Bolsonaro em cena de document\u00e1rio|author=Globo|website=Globo.com|date=2016-03-11}}</ref><ref name=\"usnews\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/opinion/world-report/articles/2017-10-20/could-jair-bolsonaro-become-brazils-next-president|title=Brazil's Donald Trump?|author=Mark Weisbrot|website=US News}}</ref><ref name=\"washingtonpost\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2017/11/28/a-trump-like-politician-in-brazil-could-snag-the-support-of-a-powerful-religious-group-evangelicals/|title=Acts of Faith. A Trump-like politician in Brazil could snag the support of a powerful religious group: evangelicals|website=The Washington Post}}</ref> misogynistic, sexist,<ref name=\"gardian-sexist\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/18/brazilian-congressman-rape-remark-compensation|title=Brazilian congressman ordered to pay compensation over rape remark|author=TheGuardian|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2015-09-18}}</ref><ref name=\"usnews\" /><ref name=\"washingtonpost\" /> racist<ref name=\"Gavin Fernando\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/wtf/is-this-the-worlds-most-repulsive-politician/news-story/926a4a59cf6132f770dfdbd46f610e97|title=Is this the world's most repulsive politician?|author=Gavin Fernando|website=News.com.au}}</ref><ref name=\"usnews\" /><ref name=\"washingtonpost\" /> or anti-refugee.<ref name=\"anti-refugee\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/08/world/americas/conservatives-star-rises-in-brazil-as-polarizing-views-tap-into-discontent.html|title=Conservative's Star Rises in Brazil as Polarizing Views Tap Into Discontent|author=Simon Romero|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2016-05-07}}</ref> Other controversial political stances expressed by Bolsonaro have been the defense of the [[Capital punishment|death penalty]] (which is currently banned under the [[Constitution of Brazil]] of 1988) and of radical interventionism in Brazil by the military, along with an imposition of a [[Brazilian military government]].<ref name=\"epoca2\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/20/world/americas/brazil-lula-bolsonaro-election.html|title=Leftist Lion and Far-Right Provocateur Vie for Brazil Presidency|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2018-01-20|last1=Londo\u00f1o|first1=Ernesto|last2=Darlington|first2=Shasta}}</ref>\n\nJournalist [[Glenn Greenwald]] called Bolsonaro \"the most misogynistic, hateful elected official in the democratic world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://firstlook.org/theintercept/2014/12/11/misogynistic-hateful-elected-official-democacratic-world-brazils-jair-bolsonaro/|title=The Most Misogynistic, Hateful Elected Official in the Democratic World: Brazil's Jair Bolsonaro \u2013 The Intercept|website=The Intercept|date=2014-12-11}}</ref> [[News.com.au]] wondered whether Bolsonaro was \"the world's most repulsive politician\".<ref name=\"Gavin Fernando\" /> British news magazine ''[[The Economist]]'' referred to him as a \"radical\", \"religious nationalist\", a \"right-wing demagogue\", and \"apologist of dictators\".<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/news/americas/21731190-can-right-wing-demagogue-win-next-years-election-jair-bolsonaro-hopes-be-brazils-donald|title=Jair Bolsonaro hopes to be Brazil's Donald Trump|journal=The Economist|accessdate=7 September 2018|date=2017-11-09}}</ref> [[Federico Finchelstein]], scholar on fascism and populism, has considered Bolsonaro, as he would link violence to austerity and neoliberal economic ideas, to be the most similar leader to [[Augusto Pinochet]] to come out from the young South American democracies.<ref>{{Cite journal|author-link=Federico Finchelstein|first=Federico|last=Finchelstein|journal=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|url=https://www.clarin.com/opinion/brasil-todas-opciones-malas_0_CyhTjjk9e.html|date=14 October 2018|title=Brasil: todas las opciones son malas}}</ref>\n\nBolsonaro is an open admirer of U.S. President [[Donald Trump]]. During Bolsonaro's campaign, some observers saw similarities between the Brazilian president-elect and the U.S. president's ideals, hardline attacks and a reputation for incendiary rhetoric, as well as social media presence. Because of this, Bolsonaro has been called the Brazilian equivalent of Trump or the \"Trump of the Tropics\".<ref name=\"Foreign Staff\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/29/brazils-president-elect-jair-bolsonaro-really-trump-tropics/|author=Foreign Staff|date=2018-10-29|title=Why Brazil's president-elect Jair Bolsonaro really is the 'Trump of the Tropics'|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n=== Views on the Brazilian military dictatorship ===\n[[File:Jair e Eduardo Bolsonaro no congresso com bandeira do Brasil.jpg|right|thumb|Bolsonaro and his son [[Eduardo Bolsonaro|Eduardo]] hold up a Brazilian flag during a ceremony to mark the 50th anniversary of the [[1964 Brazilian coup d'\u00e9tat|1964 military coup d'\u00e9tat]], 1{{nbsp}}April 2014.]]\n\nThroughout his political career, Bolsonaro has made several admiring comments about the U.S.\u2013supported [[Brazilian military regime|Brazilian military dictatorship]] which ruled the country from 1964 to 1985. He said in 1993, eight years after the return of democracy, that the military regime had \"led to a more sustainable and prosperous Brazil\".<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Bolsonaro has publicly referred to the military dictatorship as a \"glorious\" period in Brazil's history,<ref name=\"R7.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://noticias.r7.com/brasil/bolsonaro-chama-ditadura-militar-brasileira-de-intervencao-democratica-31032015|title=Bolsonaro chama ditadura militar brasileira de \"interven\u00e7\u00e3o democr\u00e1tica\"|date=2015-03-31|work=R7.com|access-date=2018-09-13|language=pt-BR}}</ref> and that under the military dictatorship, Brazil enjoyed \"20 years of order and progress\".<ref name=\"R7.com\"/> In December 2008, Bolsonaro said that \"the error of the dictatorship was that it tortured, but did not kill\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jovempanfm.uol.com.br/panico/defensor-da-ditadura-jair-bolsonaro-reforca-frase-polemica-o-erro-foi-torturar-e-nao-matar.html|title=Defensor da Ditadura, Jair Bolsonaro refor\u00e7a frase pol\u00eamica: \"o erro foi torturar e n\u00e3o matar\" - P\u00e2nico - Jovem Pan FM S\u00e3o Paulo 100.9|website=Jovem Pan FM|language=pt-BR|access-date=2018-09-13|date=2016-07-08}}</ref>\n\nBolsonaro has also repeatedly made admiring comments about a number of other Latin American dictatorships. He praised Peruvian president [[Alberto Fujimori]] as a role model for his use of military intervention via [[1992 Peruvian constitutional crisis|self-coup]] against the judiciary and legislature.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> In a 1998 interview with ''Veja'' magazine, Bolsonaro praised the [[Military dictatorship of Chile (1973\u201390)|Chilean dictatorship]] of [[Augusto Pinochet]], and said the Pinochet regime, which killed over 3,000 Chilean citizens, \"should have killed more people\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://congressoemfoco.uol.com.br/especial/noticias/as-frases-polemicas-de-jair-bolsonaro/|title=As frases pol\u00eamicas de Jair Bolsonaro|date=2017-08-05|work=Congresso em Foco|access-date=2018-09-13|language=pt-BR}}</ref> In 1999, Bolsonaro said that [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] represented \"hope for Latin America\", comments that became a matter of controversy during the 2018 campaign, when Bolsonaro presented himself as a harsh critic of ''[[Chavismo]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,entrevista-de-bolsonaro-ao-estado-com-elogios-a-chavez-mobiliza-militancia,70002117151|title=Entrevista de Bolsonaro ao 'Estado' com elogios a Ch\u00e1vez mobiliza milit\u00e2ncia - Pol\u00edtica|website=Estad\u00e3o}}</ref> In 2019, already in power, Bolsonaro commended Paraguay autocrat [[Alfredo Stroessner]] as a \"visionary\" and \"statesman\", drawing immediate criticism, particularly due to multiple allegations of [[pedophilia]] against Stroessner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2019/02/26/internacional/1551213499_127441.html|title=Bolsonaro elogia ditador paraguaio Alfredo Stroessner em p\u00fablico|first=Santi|last=Carneri|date=27 February 2019|website=EL PA\u00cdS}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://epoca.globo.com/7-fatos-sobre-ditador-e-pedofilo-reiterado-elogiado-por-bolsonaro-23486277|title=7 fatos sobre o ditador \u2014 e ped\u00f3filo reiterado \u2014 elogiado por Bolsonaro|date=27 February 2019|website=\u00c9poca}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking before his vote in favor of [[Impeachment process against Dilma Rousseff|President Dilma Rousseff's impeachment]] amid the [[Operation Car Wash|massive corruption scandal]], Bolsonaro paid homage to Colonel [[Carlos Alberto Brilhante Ustra|Brilhante Ustra]], an agent of [[Brazilian military government|Brazil's military dictatorship]], and announced on the floor of the Chamber of Deputies that he was dedicating his pro-impeachment vote to Ustra's memory. Ustra had headed the [[DOI-CODI]] torture unit where Rousseff was allegedly tortured during the military dictatorship. Left-wing deputy [[Jean Wyllys]] spat at him after his statement during the same session. The congressman claimed to have suffered homophobic offenses from Jair Bolsonaro and his allies.<ref>{{cite web |title=A lightning rod for attacks by Brazil's right-wing |url=https://www.latimes.com/world/brazil/la-fg-brazil-congressman-20151128-story.html |publisher=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/18/dilma-rousseff-congress-impeach-brazilian-president|title=Dilma Rousseff: Brazilian congress votes to impeach president|last=Watts|first=Jonathan|date=18 April 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=18 April 2016|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn a TV interview with ''C\u00e2mera Aberta'' in the 1990s, Bolsonaro said that if he ever became President, he would use this as an opportunity to shut down the National Congress and instigate a military coup himself. {{as of|2018}}, he appeared to have changed his mind, and said that if someone becomes the head of the country, it would be through voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/internacional/en/brazil/2018/06/1970871-congressman-bolsonaro-defended-new-military-coup-in-the-1990s.shtml|title=Folha de S.Paulo \u2013 Internacional \u2013 En \u2013 Brazil \u2013 Congressman Bolsonaro Defended New Military Coup in the 1990s \u2013 04/06/2018|website=1.folha.uol.com.br|access-date=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Bolsonaro stated that the [[1964 Brazilian coup d'\u00e9tat|1964 coup d'\u00e9tat]] that overthrew President [[Jo\u00e3o Goulart]]<ref name=1964coup>{{cite web |author=Kingstone, Steve |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3588339.stm|title=Brazil remembers 1964 coup d'etat|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=May 8, 2007 | date=April 1, 2004}}</ref> was not a [[Coup d'\u00e9tat|coup]], and that March 31, the day the coup was installed, should be \"properly commemorated\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2019/03/25/bolsonaro-determinou-que-defesa-faca-as-comemoracoes-devidas-do-golpe-de-64-diz-porta-voz.ghtml|title=Bolsonaro determinou que Defesa fa\u00e7a as 'comemora\u00e7\u00f5es devidas' do golpe de 64, diz porta-voz|website=G1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Santa Rita |first1=Bruno |last2=Souza |first2=Renato |last3=Kafruni |first3=Simone |title=Bolsonaro recomendou 'devidas comemora\u00e7\u00f5es' do golpe de 1964, diz Porta-Voz |url=https://www.correiobraziliense.com.br/app/noticia/politica/2019/03/25/interna_politica,745271/bolsonaro-recomendou-devidas-comemoracoes-do-golpe-de-1964-diz-port.shtml |website=Correio Braziliense |language=pt-BR |date=25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.terra.com.br/noticias/brasil/politica/bolsonaro-nao-considera-que-houve-golpe-em-1964-e-determina-comemoracoes-devidas-diz-porta-voz,a833162dc1987b126cd259b9717d944d6sjaukq7.html|title=Bolsonaro determina \"comemora\u00e7\u00f5es devidas\" do 31 de mar\u00e7o|website=Terra}}</ref>\n\n=== Foreign policy ===\n{{See also|List of international presidential trips made by Jair Bolsonaro}}\n[[File:19-03-2019 Encontro com o Senhor Donald Trump, Presidente dos Estados Unidos da Am\u00e9rica.jpg|right|thumb|Bolsonaro with U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] at the White House, Washington, D.C., 19 March 2019]]\nDuring the 2018 presidential campaign, Bolsonaro said he would make considerable changes to Brazil's foreign relations, saying that the \"''[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Brazil)|Itamaraty]]'' needs to be in service of the values that were always associated with the Brazilian people\". He also said that the country should stop \"praising dictators\" and attacking democracies, such as the [[United States]], [[Israel]] and [[Italy]].<ref name=\"foreignpolicy\">{{Cite news|first=Ana Cristina|last=Campos|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2018-10/veja-propostas-de-bolsonaro-e-haddad-para-politica-externa|title=Veja as propostas de Bolsonaro e Haddad para a pol\u00edtica externa|work=Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=26 October 2018|access-date=26 October 2018}}</ref> In early 2018, he affirmed that his \"trip to the five democratic countries the United States, Israel, [[Japan]], [[South Korea]], and [[Taiwan]] showed who we will be and we would like to join good people\". Bolsonaro has shown distrust towards [[China]] throughout the presidential campaign claiming they \"[want to] buy Brazil\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://manchikoni.com/presidential-candidates-present-a-drastic-turn-in-foreign-policy-jair-bolsonaro-psl-promises-to-break-brazils-traditional-diplomatic-positions-while-fernando-haddad/|title=Presidential candidates present a drastic turn in foreign policy Jair Bolsonaro (PSL) promises to break Brazil's traditional diplomatic positions while Fernando Haddad|work=|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mKVnvgrkcfQ|title=Os compromissos de Bolsonaro em Taiwan.|work=Jair Bolsonaro|date=2018-03-04|access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z4c36Kw6388|title=Conversa com Brasileiros em Taiwan.|work=Jair Bolsonaro|date=2018-03-05|access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.ltn.com.tw/news/world/paper/1242214|title=\u5df4\u897f\u5ddd\u666e\u6279\u4e2d\u63a0\u596a\u8005 \u5317\u4eac\u6025\u4e86|work=[[Liberty Times]]|date=2018-10-26|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.epochtimes.com/b5/18/10/29/n10815828.htm|title=\u5df4\u897f\u65b0\u7e3d\u7d71\u89aa\u53f0\u53cd\u5171 \u4eca\u5e74\u66fe\u7387\u5718\u8a2a\u53f0\u7063|work=[[Epoch Times]]|date=2018-10-29|access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref> although Brazil recorded a US$20 billion trade surplus with China in 2018, and China is only the 13th largest source of foreign direct investment into Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b5371a10-044a-11e9-bf0f-53b8511afd73|title=Bolsonaro will regret baiting the Chinese tiger|last=|first=|date=|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref> Bolsonaro said he wishes to continue to have business with the Chinese but he also said that Brazil should \"make better [economic] deals\" with other countries, with no \"ideological agenda\" behind it.<ref name=\"estadaomarco\" /> His stance towards China has also been interpreted by some as an attempt to curry favor from the [[Donald Trump|Trump]] administration to garner concessions from the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b5371a10-044a-11e9-bf0f-53b8511afd73|title=Bolsonaro will regret baiting the Chinese dragon|last=|first=|date=|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref> However, Bolsonaro has mostly changed his position on China after he took office, saying that the two countries were \u201cborn to walk together\u201d during his visit to Beijing in October 2019.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/12/06/bolsonaro-losing-bet-trump-brazil-tariffs/|title=Bolsonaro Placed a Losing Bet on Trump|last=Stuenkel|first=Oliver|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3034658/common-ground-investment-still-no-hint-brazil-signing-chinas|title=Still no hint of Brazil signing up for China\u2019s Belt and Road Initiative|date=2019-10-25|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> He has also said that Brazil will stay out of the ongoing [[China\u2013United States trade war|China-U.S. trade war]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nBolsonaro said that his first international trip as president will be to [[Brazil\u2013Israel relations|Israel]].<ref name=\"palestine\">{{cite news |title=Israel hails election of Brazil's controversial Bolsonaro, who plans visit soon |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-hails-election-of-brazils-controversial-bolsonaro-who-plans-visit/ |work=The Times of Israel |date=29 October 2018}}</ref> Bolsonaro also said that the [[State of Palestine]] \"is not a country, so there should be no embassy here\", adding that \"you don't negotiate with terrorists.\"<ref name=\"palestine\" /> The announcement was warmly received by the [[Prime Minister]] of Israel, [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], who welcomed Bolsonaro to Israel in March 2019 during the final weeks of a re-election campaign,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://jg-tc.com/news/world/netanyahu-warmly-welcomes-brazil-s-bolsonaro-in-israel/article_2b286bf8-4d6e-5f02-9a6d-4e83a9cf4e34.html |title=Netanyahu embraces Brazil's far-right Bolsonaro in Israel |work=Associated Presa |date=31 March 2019|accessdate=6 April 2018|first=Ilan|last=Ben Zion}}</ref> but was met with condemnation from the [[Arab League]], which warned Bolsonaro it could damage diplomatic ties.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/arab-league-warns-brazil-that-jerusalem-embassy-move-could-harm-ties/ |title=Arab League warns Brazil that Jerusalem embassy move could harm ties |work=Times of Israel |date=11 December 2018|accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref> \"I love Israel,\" Bolsonaro said in Hebrew at a welcoming ceremony, with Netanyahu at his side, at Tel Aviv's Ben-Gurion airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/i-love-israel-brazils-bolsonaro-lands-in-tel-aviv/a-48134150|title='I love Israel' \u2014 Brazil's Bolsonaro lands in Tel Aviv {{!}} DW {{!}} 31.03.2019|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bolsonaro Xi Jinping China 2019.jpg|left|thumb|Bolsonaro with Chinese President [[Xi Jinping]] in October 2019]]\nBolsonaro has also praised U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] and [[Foreign policy of the Donald Trump administration|his foreign policy]].,<ref name=\"foreignpolicy\" /> with Bolsonaro being named \u2018the tropical Trump\u2019.<ref>https://www.ft.com/content/874c8a46-4873-11e9-bbc9-6917dce3dc62</ref> Bolsonaro's son [[Eduardo Bolsonaro|Eduardo]] has indicated that Brazil should distance itself from [[Iran]], sever ties with [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]]'s government in [[Venezuela]] and relocate [[List of diplomatic missions in Israel|Brazil's embassy in Israel]] to [[Jerusalem]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Brazil Should Shun Venezuela and Embrace Israel, Bolsonaro's Son Says |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-10-10/brazil-to-shun-venezuela-and-embrace-israel-bolsonaro-son-says |work=Bloomberg |date=10 October 2018}}</ref> Bolsonaro is widely considered to be the most [[Foreign relations of the United States|pro-American]] candidate in Brazil since the 1980s. PSL members have said that if elected, he will dramatically improve [[Brazil\u2013United States relations|relations between the United States and Brazil]].<ref name=\":3\" /> During an October 2017 campaign rally in [[Miami]], he saluted the [[Flag of the United States|American flag]] and led chants of \"USA! USA!\" to a large crowd.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americasquarterly.org/content/what-expect-jair-bolsonaro|title=What to Expect from Jair Bolsonaro|last=Winter|first=Brian|date=October 9, 2018|website=[[Americas Quarterly]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=October 11, 2018}}</ref> U.S. National Security Advisor [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]] praised Bolsonaro as a 'like-minded' partner and said his victory was a \"positive sign\" for Latin America.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jair Bolsonaro: Brazil's far-right president-elect wants to move Israel embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jair-bolsonaro-brazil-embassy-israel-tel-aviv-jerusalem-middle-east-palestine-a8614066.html |work=The Independent |date=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the regional level, he praised the Argentine President [[Mauricio Macri]] for ending the 12-years rule of [[N\u00e9stor Kirchner|N\u00e9stor]] and [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]], which he saw as similar to Lula and Rousseff. Although he does not have plans of leaving the [[Mercosur]], he criticized that it gave priority to ideological issues instead of economic ones.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alberto|last=Almendariz|url= https://www.lanacion.com.ar/2180830-bolsonaro-un-saludo-macri-termino-dilma-kirchner|title=Bolsonaro: \"Un abrazo a Macri, que termin\u00f3 con la 'Dilma Kirchner'\"|trans-title= Bolsonaro: \"A hug for Macri, who ended the 'Dilma-Kirchner'\"|language= Spanish|date= 11 October 2018|newspaper= La Naci\u00f3n|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref> A staunch anti-communist, Bolsonaro has condemned [[Cuba]]'s former leader [[Fidel Castro]] and the current regime in that island.<ref name=\"churchill\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Brazil's Bolsonaro names Trump fan top diplomat as Cuba relations sour |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-politics/brazils-bolsonaro-names-trump-fan-top-diplomat-as-cuba-relations-sour-idUSKCN1NJ31M |work=Reuters |date=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nBolsonaro praised British Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]], saying that he had learned from Churchill: \"Patriotism, love for your fatherland, respect for your flag \u2013 something that has been lost over the last few years here in Brazil{{nbsp}}... and governing through example, especially at that difficult moment of the Second World War.\"<ref name=\"churchill\">{{cite news |title=Jair Bolsonaro denies he is a fascist and paints himself as a Brazilian Churchill |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/30/jair-bolsonaro-denies-he-is-a-fascist-brazilian-churchill |work=The Guardian |date=30 October 2018}}</ref> Bolsonaro said he's open to the possibility of hosting a [[United States military deployments|U.S. military base]] in Brazil to counter [[Russia]]n influence in the region.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brazil military uneasy with Bolsonaro's openness to U.S. base: source |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-usa-base/brazil-military-uneasy-with-bolsonaros-openness-to-u-s-base-source-idUSKCN1OZ0IW |publisher=Reuters |date=January 5, 2019}}</ref> With the intention of the U.S. President Donald Trump to make Brazil a [[NATO]] member in March 2019, Bolsonaro said: \"the discussions with the United States will begin in the coming months\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump says strongly considering NATO membership for Brazil |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-brazil-nato/trump-says-looking-at-nato-membership-for-brazil-idUSKCN1R024O|publisher=Reuters |date=19 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump says looking at NATO membership for Brazil|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/03/19/trump-says-looking-at-nato-membership-for-brazil|publisher=Euronews|date=19 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Diplomacia em primeiro lugar, at\u00e9 as \u00faltimas consequ\u00eancias', diz Bolsonaro sobre Venezuela|url=https://g1.globo.com/mundo/noticia/2019/03/19/diplomacia-em-primeiro-lugar-ate-as-ultimas-consequencias-diz-bolsonaro-sobre-venezuela.ghtml|publisher=G1|date=19 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Em almo\u00e7o fechado, Trump diz querer Brasil como membro pleno da Otan|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/mundo/2019/03/em-almoco-fechado-trump-diz-querer-brasil-como-membro-pleno-da-otan.shtml|publisher=Folha de S.Paulo|date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bolsonaro with Modi November 2019 (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|Bolsonaro with Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] in Bras\u00edlia, November 2019]]\nWith formal support from the United States for Brazil's entry on [[OECD]] on May 2019, Bolsonaro said that \"currently, all 36 members of the organization support the entry of the country, fruit of confidence in the new Brazil being built, more free, open and fair\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Official Twitter of President Jair Bolsonaro|url=https://twitter.com/jairbolsonaro/status/1131634002824245248|publisher=@jairbolsonaro|language=pt|date=23 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Official Twitter of United States Embassy in Brazil|url=https://twitter.com/EmbaixadaEUA/status/1131526230073851909|publisher=@EmbaixadaEUA|language=pt|date=23 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=USA Officially Supports Brazil's Candidature to The OECD|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/internacional/en/business/2019/05/usa-officially-supports-brazils-candidature-to-the-oecd.shtml|publisher=Folha de S.Paulo|date=24 May 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, on a state visit to China, Bolsonaro announced the end of the need for visas for Chinese and Indian entry into Brazil. The Brazilian government had already removed the need for visas for people from the United States, Canada, Japan, and Australia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brazil says it will no longer require visas from Chinese, Indian citizens|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-visas/brazil-says-it-will-no-longer-require-visas-from-chinese-indian-citizens-idUSKBN1X32AX|publisher=Reuters|date=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 January 2020, the high-level Iranian General, [[Qasem Soleimani]], was [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|assassinated by the United States]], which considerably heightened the [[2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis|existing tensions]] between the two countries. Bolsonaro said he supports any \"initiative against terrorism\", also reaffirmed his support for U.S. President Donald Trump in the action.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clarin.com/mundo/jair-bolsonaro-dijo-general-irani-qasem-soleimani-participo-atentado-amia_0_CEIIciav.html |website=Clarin |title=Jair Bolsonaro dijo que el general iran\u00ed Qasem Soleimani particip\u00f3 en el atentado a la AMIA |date=4 January 2020 |language=es |trans-title=\"Jair Bolsonaro said Iranian General Qasem Soleimani participated in the AMIA attack }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://noticias.r7.com/jr-na-tv/videos/bolsonaro-diz-que-apoia-acao-americana-e-que-brasil-condena-o-terrorismo-03012020 |website=R7 |title=Bolsonaro diz que apoia a\u00e7\u00e3o americana e que Brasil condena o terrorismo |date=3 January 2020 |language=pt-br |trans-title=Bolsonaro says he supports U.S. action and Brazil condemns terrorism }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January 2020, on his first state visit to India, Bolsonaro said that Brazil will continue to demand a [[Reform of the United Nations Security Council|permanent seat]] on the [[United Nations Security Council|UN Security Council]], and that will remain a priority on his government. Together with Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]], he said that \"Brazil and India are two great countries, among the ten largest economies in the world, that together have 1.5 billion inhabitants, are democratic countries. We believe that it will be good for the world if Brazil and India join this group\".<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00cdndia e Brasil confirmam interesse em ampliar Conselho de Seguran\u00e7a da ONU\n|url=https://www.correiobraziliense.com.br/app/noticia/politica/2020/01/25/interna_politica,823263/india-e-brasil-confirmam-interesse-em-ampliar-conselho-de-seguranca-da.shtml|website=Correio Brasiliense|date=25 January 2019}}</ref> As the head of the state, he became the chief guest at the [[Delhi Republic Day parade]] on 26 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abplive.com/news/india/republic-day-2020-live-updates-india-71st-r-day-brazilian-prez-jair-bolsonaro-chief-guest-rajpath-1148777|title=Republic Day 2020 Live Updates: PM Modi, President Kovind, Chief Guest President of Brazil Jair Bolsonaro Arrive At Rajpath; R-day Parade To Begin|last=Bureau|first=ABP News|date=2020-01-26|website=news.abplive.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March 2020, Bolsonaro was hosted by the U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] at [[Mar-a-Lago]] for a working dinner, where the two leaders discussed the U.S.-led effort to oust Venezuelan President [[Nicolas Maduro]], a future trade deal and peace for the Middle East, also Trump reaffirmed his interest in upgrading the American military alliance with Brazil, suggesting give to the country a full [[NATO]] membership, as part of an effort to fortify the Western Hemisphere against Russian and Chinese influence.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-08/trump-and-bolsonaro-to-discuss-venezuela-over-mar-a-lago-dinner |author1=Adghirni, Sami |author2=Harney, John|author3=Parker, Mario| title=Trump and Bolsonaro Discuss Venezuela Over Mar-a-Lago Dinner |publisher=Bloomberg |date=March 7, 2020 |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/defense-national-security/that-would-really-be-historic-trump-wants-nato-to-tighten-ties-with-brazils-jair-bolsonaro |author1=Gehrke, Joel| title=That would really be historic: Trump wants NATO to tighten ties with Brazil\u2019s Jair Bolsonaro |publisher=Washington Examiner |date=March 7, 2020 |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nBrazil has the world's [[Amazon rainforest|largest tropical rainforest]] in the [[Amazon basin]]. According to ''The Washington Post'', \"Bolsonaro is a powerful supporter of [[Agriculture in Brazil|agribusiness]] [...] and is likely to favor profits over preservation. [...] Bolsonaro has chafed at foreign pressure to safeguard [[Amazon rainforest|the Amazon rainforest]], and he served notice to international nonprofit groups such as the [[World Wildlife Fund]] that he will not tolerate their agendas in Brazil. He has also come out strongly against [[Indigenous territory (Brazil)|lands]] reserved for [[Indigenous peoples in Brazil|indigenous tribes]]. Bolsonaro advisers additionally say that he plans to expand [[Nuclear activities in Brazil|nuclear]] and hydroelectric power into the Amazon.\"<ref name=\"environment\"/>\n\n[[File:Bolsonaro with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at the Wailing Wall.jpg|left|thumb|Bolsonaro with Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] at the [[Western Wall]]]]\nBolsonaro rejects the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]. He repeatedly threatened to withdraw from the [[Paris Agreement]] during his campaign.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolsonaro diz que Brasil deixar\u00e1 Acordo de Paris se n\u00e3o forem aceitas mudan\u00e7as|url=https://br.reuters.com/article/topNews/idBRKBN1OB2ZY-OBRTP|language=pt|agency=Reuters|date=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2019/01/brazil-s-new-president-has-scientists-worried-here-s-why|title=Brazil's new president has scientists worried. Here's why|last=Escobar|first=Herton|date=2019-01-22|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> Even before taking office, he backed out of Brazil's offer to host the [[United Nations Climate Change conference#2019: COP 25/CMP 15/CMA 2|2019 UN Climate Change Conference]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-climate-change-accord-brazil-idUSKCN1NX27B|title=Brazil's Bolsonaro nixes plans to host U.N. climate event|date=2018-11-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-01-25|language=en}}</ref> [[Ernesto Ara\u00fajo]], the new Minister of Foreign Affairs appointed by Bolsonaro, has called global warming a [[Global warming conspiracy theory|plot]] by \"cultural Marxists\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/nov/15/brazil-foreign-minister-ernesto-araujo-climate-change-marxist-plot|title=Brazil's new foreign minister believes climate change is a Marxist plot|last=editor|first=Jonathan Watts Global environment|date=2018-11-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-01-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and has eliminated the Climate Change Division of the ministry.<ref name=\":0\" /> Two departments of the [[Ministry of the Environment (Brazil)|Ministry of the Environment]] dealing with climate change and mitigation and one dealing with deforestation have also been eliminated.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn April 2019, the [[American Museum of Natural History]] canceled an event honoring Bolsonaro after facing heavy public criticism, including from New York Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]]. The museum's directorate justified its decision in a statement, \"With mutual respect for the work and goals of our organizations, we jointly agreed that the Museum is not the optimal location for the Brazilian-Am. Chamber of Commerce gala dinner. This traditional event will go forward at another location on the original date and time.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Museum cancels event honouring Brazil's Jair Bolsonaro |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-47946955 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |agency=BBC |date=16 April 2019}}</ref> Bolsonaro has supported plans to open the Reserva Nacional do Cobre e Associados (Renca) [[Amazon rainforest|Amazonian]] reserve in Brazil's northern states of [[Par\u00e1]] and [[Amap\u00e1]] to commercial [[mining]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolsonaro says Brazil rainforest reserve may be opened to mining |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-amazon-mining/brazils-bolsonaro-says-rainforest-reserve-should-be-opened-to-mining-idUSKCN1RO29H |agency=Reuters |date=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:28 06 2019 Reuni\u00e3o Paralela dos L\u00edderes do G20, sobre Economia Digital (48142864762).jpg|right|thumb|Bolsonaro, French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] and Saudi Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] at the 2019 G20 Osaka summit]]\n[[Deforestation of the Amazon rainforest|Destruction of the Amazon rainforest]] increased by 88% for the month of June 2019, during Bolsonaro's first year as president, as compared with the previous year, according to [[National Institute for Space Research]] (INPE). Bolsonaro has rejected the agency's data as false. The IPSE director was fired after he rebutted Bolsonaro's criticism of IPSE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/natureza/noticia/2019/07/03/desmatamento-na-amazonia-em-junho-e-88percent-maior-do-que-no-mesmo-periodo-de-2018.ghtml|title=Desmatamento na Amaz\u00f4nia em junho \u00e9 88% maior do que no mesmo per\u00edodo de 2018|website=G1|language=pt-br|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-climatechange-protests/london-climate-change-protesters-daub-brazilian-embassy-blood-red-idUKKCN1V30LA|title=London climate change protesters daub Brazilian embassy blood red|website=Reuters|language=en|access-date=15 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Amazon deforestation: Brazil's Bolsonaro dismisses data as 'lies' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-49052360 |website=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |date=July 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=de Campos |first1=Jo\u00e3o Pedroso |title=Ap\u00f3s rebater Bolsonaro, diretor do Inpe deixar\u00e1 o cargo |url=https://veja.abril.com.br/politica/apos-rebater-bolsonaro-diretor-do-inpe-deixara-o-cargo/ |website=[[Veja (magazine)|Veja]] |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |language=Portuguese |date=August 2, 2019}}</ref> The Bolsonaro administration has decreased government efforts which combat illegal logging, ranching and mining in the Amazon. Government enforcement actions such as fines, warnings and the confiscation or destruction of illegal equipment in protected areas have decreased by 20% in the first half of 2018 compared to the first half of 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Casado |first1=Let\u00edcia |last2=Londo\u00f1o |first2=Ernesto |title=Under Brazil's Far-Right Leader, Amazon Protections Slashed and Forests Fall |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/world/americas/brazil-deforestation-amazon-bolsonaro.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |date=July 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] said she was concerned about [[Deforestation in Brazil|deforestation]] in the Amazon rainforest and would seek \"straight talk with Brazil's President Jair Bolsonaro on the upcoming [[2019 G20 Osaka summit|G20 summit]] in Osaka\". She also said that the situation \"does not affect the imminent free trade agreement between [[Mercosur]] and the [[European Union|EU]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Merkel descreve situa\u00e7\u00e3o sob Bolsonaro como dram\u00e1tica|url=https://www.dw.com/pt-br/merkel-descreve-situa%C3%A7%C3%A3o-sob-bolsonaro-como-dram%C3%A1tica/a-49367311|language=pt|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=26 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Merkel wants 'straight talk' with Bolsonaro over deforestation|url=http://www.spacedaily.com/afp/190626140722.4340bpio.html|publisher=Space Daily|date=26 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Merkel quer ter \"conversa clara\" com Bolsonaro sobre desmatamento no G20|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2019/06/26/politica/1561562740_367321.html|language=pt|publisher=El Pa\u00eds|date=26 May 2019}}</ref> After French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] conditioned France's support for a trade accord between the [[European Union]] and [[Mercosul]] to Brazil remaining in the [[Paris Agreement]], Bolsonaro said that Brazil \"will not leave the Paris Agreement\" in their meeting at the G20 Osaka, also inviting Macron to visit Brazil's Amazon region.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolsonaro sinaliza a Macron que fica no Acordo de Paris, e discute com Trump medidas contra Maduro|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2019/06/28/politica/1561724232_672469.html|language=pt|publisher=El Pa\u00eds|date=28 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bolsonaro sinaliza a Macron que Brasil vai continuar no Acordo do Clima de Paris|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2019/06/28/bolsonaro-convida-macron-para-visitar-a-amazonia.ghtml|language=pt|publisher=G1|date=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2019 Foto de Fam\u00edlia - 49064894752.jpg|left|thumb|Bolsonaro with Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] in 2019]]\nDuring a conversation with journalists in July 2019, Bolsonaro lashed out at European leaders, saying that the Amazon belongs to Brazil and European countries can mind their own business because they have already \"destroyed their environment\". He also said: \"We preserve more [rainforest] than anyone. No country in the world has the moral right to talk about Amazon.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/19/jair-bolsonaro-brazil-amazon-rainforest-deforestation|title=Bolsonaro declares 'the Amazon is ours' and calls deforestation data 'lies'|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=16 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 Brazil wildfires]], Bolsonaro in August 2019 accused (without providing any evidence) that non-governmental organizations had started the forest fires, due to a reduction of government funding to the NGOs. Environmental and climate experts described Bolsonaro's accusation as a \"smokescreen\" to hide his own government's rolling back of protections for the Amazon. They instead attributed the fires to farmers clearing land.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sim\u00f5es |first1=Eduardo |last2=Boadle |first2=Anthony |last3=Mano |first3=Ana |last4=Stargardter |first4=Gabriel |last5=Brown |first5=Tom |last6=O'Brien |first6=Rosalba |title=Igniting global outrage, Brazil's Bolsonaro baselessly blames NGOs for Amazon fires |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-politics-idUSKCN1VB1BY |website=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |date=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 August 2019, Bolsonaro accused Macron of having \"a misplaced colonialist mentality in the 21st century\" in reference to criticism by the French president, where he called on G7 leaders to discuss the [[2019 Brazil wildfires|Amazon crisis]]. He also said \"regret that the French president seeks to instrumentalize an internal issue of Brazil and other Amazonian countries for personal political gains.\"{{clarify|date=August 2019}} He added that \"the Brazilian government remains open to dialogue, based on objective data and mutual respect.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolsonaro diz que Macron busca instrumentalizar uma quest\u00e3o interna e critica tom sensacionalista sobre a Amaz\u00f4nia |url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2019/08/22/bolsonaro-diz-que-macron-busca-instrumentalizar-uma-questao-interna-e-critica-tom-sensacionalista-sobre-a-amazonia.ghtml|publisher=G1 |language=pt |date=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Macron Calls on G7 Countries to Discuss Amazon Forest in Summit |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-08-22/macron-calls-on-g7-countries-to-discuss-amazon-forest-in-summit|publisher=Bloomberg |date=22 August 2019}}</ref> Macron stated he will refuse to ratify the [[European Union\u2013Mercosur Free Trade Agreement]] unless Brazil commits to protecting the environment.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ireland, France set to block EU-Mercosur trade deal over Amazon |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/ajimpact/ireland-block-eu-mercosur-trade-deal-amazon-fires-190823095908509.html |work=Al-Jazeera |date=23 August 2019}}</ref> Bolsonaro's Facebook comments mocking Brigitte Macron's looks escalated the diplomatic clash, which was dubbed \"the worst diplomatic crisis between France and Brazil in 40 years\". Macron pointed out that the French overseas territory of [[French Guiana]] on the northern coast of South America is France's biggest land border.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/26/macron-rebukes-bolsonaro-over-extraordinarily-rude-comments-about-wife |title=Macron rebukes Bolsonaro for 'extraordinarily rude' comments about wife |date=2019-08-26 |website=The Guardian |access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Christianity and secularism ===\n[[File:Jair Bolsonaro discursa na 74\u00aa Sess\u00e3o da Assembleia Geral da ONU (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|Bolsonaro speaking to the United Nations General Assembly in September 2019]]\nBolsonaro is a member of the [[Catholic Church in Brazil|Catholic Church]] (while his wife and one of his sons are [[Evangelical Christian]]s).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/internacional/en/brazil/2018/10/bolsonaro-a-catholic-expanded-his-base-among-evangelicals.shtml|title=Bolsonaro, a Catholic, Expanded His Base Among Evangelicals|date=2018-10-30|work=Folha de S.Paulo|access-date=2018-11-01|language=pt-BR}}</ref> However, according to ''[[The New Yorker]]'' reporter Jon Lee Anderson \"he had himself baptized as an evangelical [Protestant] early in his campaign, by being ceremonially dunked in the Jordan River.\"<ref>Jon Lee Anderson, \"Southern Strategy,\" ''The New Yorker'', April 1, 2019.</ref> He is reported to have attended a [[Baptist]] church for 10 years.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Chayenne|last1=Polim\u00e9dio |title=The Rise of the Brazilian Evangelicals |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/01/the-evangelical-takeover-of-brazilian-politics/551423/ |magazine=[[The Atlantic]] |publisher=[[Emerson Collective]]|location=Washington DC|date=24 January 2018 |accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref> In a 2017 speech, Bolsonaro stated, \"God above everything. There is no such thing as a [[secular state]]. The state is Christian, and any minority that is against this has to change, if they can.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Johny |first1=Stanly |title=Who is Jair Bolsonaro? |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/who-is-jair-bolsonaro/article25413969.ece |accessdate=7 December 2018 |work=The Hindu |publisher=The Hindu |date=3 November 2018 |language=en-IN}}</ref> He later evolved his position to maintaining the country a secular state during the first round of the Brazilian presidential elections: \"We are going to make a government for everyone, regardless of religion. Even for atheists. We have almost 5% of atheists in Brazil, and they have the same needs that others have.\"<ref name=\"noticias.uol.com.br\">{{cite web |url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/politica/eleicoes/2018/noticias/2018/10/06/em-ultima-fala-antes-de-votacao-bolsonaro-faz-aceno-para-ateus-e-gays.htm |title=Em \u00faltima fala antes de vota\u00e7\u00e3o, Bolsonaro faz aceno para ateus e gays |publisher=[[Universo Online|UOL]] |date=6 October 2018 |access-date=10 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Views on women ===\nIn an interview with ''Zero Hora'' in 2015, Bolsonaro argued that men and women should not receive the same salaries, because women get pregnant, adding that he believes federal law mandating paid [[maternity leave]] harms work productivity.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Vanessa|last=Lima|url=https://revistacrescer.globo.com/Familia/Maes-e-Trabalho/noticia/2015/02/jair-bolsonaro-diz-que-mulher-deve-ganhar-salario-menor-porque-engravida.html|title=Jair Bolsonaro diz que mulher deve ganhar sal\u00e1rio menor porque engravida|work=revistacrescer.globo.com|access-date=2 June 2018|language=pt-br}}</ref> Bolsonaro has denied saying that women should receive less than men; he claims it was statistical data by [[IBGE]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2018/08/bolsonaro-diz-que-cabe-a-justica-diferenca-salarial-entre-homens-e-mulheres.shtml|title=Bolsonaro diz que cabe \u00e0 justi\u00e7a acabar com a diferen\u00e7a salarial entre homens e mulheres|date=2018-08-28|work=Folha de S.Paulo|access-date=2018-10-22|language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n\nIn a public speech in April 2017, Bolsonaro said he had five children, that the first four were male and that for the fifth he produced a daughter out of \"a moment of weakness\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://exame.abril.com.br/brasil/piada-de-bolsonaro-sobre-sua-filha-gera-revolta-nas-redes-sociais/|title=Piada de Bolsonaro sobre sua filha gera revolta nas redes sociais |website=exame.abril.com.br|language=pt-BR|access-date=2 June 2018|date=2017-04-06 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:1044950-df img 2182.jpg|thumb|Bolsonaro arguing with Federal Deputy [[Maria do Ros\u00e1rio]] in the [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Chamber of Deputies]], 14 September 2016]]\nBolsonaro provoked controversy for a series of remarks made to and about Federal Deputy and former Human Rights Minister [[Maria do Ros\u00e1rio]]. During a Congressional debate, Bolsonaro said that minors should be treated as adults if they commit heinous crimes such as murder or rape, to which Maria do Ros\u00e1rio responded by calling him a \"rapist\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://veja.abril.com.br/blog/reinaldo/geral/e-chegada-a-hora-de-dar-um-basta-as-bocalidades-de-bolsonaro-hoje-o-mais-importante-aliado-da-esquerda-bocal-ambos-se-alimentam-e-se-merecem/|title=\u00c9 chegada a hora de dar um \"Basta!\" \u00e0s bo\u00e7alidades de Bolsonaro, hoje o mais importante aliado da esquerda bo\u00e7al: ambos se alimentam e se merecem!|website=Reinaldo Azevedo \u2013 VEJA.com.br}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2014/12/1559815-para-rebater-deputada-bolsonaro-diz-que-nao-a-estupraria.shtml|title=Para rebater deputada, Bolsonaro diz que n\u00e3o a 'estupraria'|website=M\u00e1rcio Falc\u00e3o e Gabriela Guerreiro \u2013 Folha de S\u00e3o Paulo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.terra.com.br/noticias/brasil/politica/bolsonaro-sobre-ataque-a-deputada-me-acusou-de-estuprador,36ba9a143643a410VgnVCM5000009ccceb0aRCRD.html|title=Bolsonaro sobre ataque a deputada: \"me acusou de estuprador\" |website=Andr\u00e9 Naddeo \u2013 Terra}}</ref> Bolsonaro then stated that Congresswoman Ros\u00e1rio was \"not worth raping; she is very ugly\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/18/brazilian-congressman-rape-remark-compensation|title=Brazilian congressman ordered to pay compensation over rape remark|last=Paulo|first=AP in S\u00e3o|date=2015-09-18|newspaper=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref> The remarks drew considerable condemnation throughout Brazil. In the aftermath of these remarks, Bolsonaro was tried and convicted in a Federal court in September 2015 on counts of [[hedonic damages]] against Ros\u00e1rio.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/colunas/monicabergamo/2015/09/1682452-bolsonaro-e-condenado-por-dizer-que-maria-do-rosario-nao-merece-estupro.shtml|title=M\u00f4nica Bergamo: Bolsonaro \u00e9 condenado por dizer que Maria do Ros\u00e1rio 'n\u00e3o merece' estupro|work=Folha de S.Paulo|access-date=2 June 2018|language=pt-BR}}</ref> In June 2016, the Federal Supreme Court responded to a complaint filed by the [[Attorney General of Brazil|Attorney General]] and decided to open two criminal actions against Bolsonaro. The Supreme Court ruled that he had potentially [[Incitement|incited]] rape and [[defamation|defamed]] the honor of his fellow Deputy. He faced a penalty of up to six months of jail and a fine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/2016/06/bolsonaro-vira-reu-por-falar-que-maria-do-rosario-nao-merece-ser-estuprada.html|title=Bolsonaro vira r\u00e9u por falar que Maria do Ros\u00e1rio n\u00e3o merece ser estuprada|date=21 June 2016|work=Pol\u00edtica|access-date=2 June 2018|language=pt-BR}}</ref> Ultimately in August 2017, an appellate court upheld a lower court's verdict which found Bolsonaro guilty and sentenced him to pay a fine to Ros\u00e1rio of R$10,000 (roughly equivalent to US$2,500).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2017/08/1910097-stj-determina-que-bolsonaro-indenize-maria-do-rosario-por-danos-morais.shtml|title=STJ determina que Bolsonaro indenize Maria do Ros\u00e1rio por danos morais|work=Folha de S.Paulo|access-date=2 June 2018}}</ref> This lawsuit was dismissed by the Supreme Federal Court as Bolsonaro was inaugurated as president in 2019 and acquired [[Legal immunity|immunity from prosecution]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/brasil-46012367|title=Ap\u00f3s posse presidencial, processos contra Bolsonaro no STF ser\u00e3o suspensos|last=Gragnani|first=Juliana|date=2018-10-30|work=BBC News Brasil|access-date=2018-11-15|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Views on homosexuality ===\n[[File:Parada gay 2011 - bonecos dilma e bolsonaro.jpg|thumb|left|[[Gay Pride]] parade in S\u00e3o Paulo, June 2011]]\n\nIn a June 2011 interview with ''[[Playboy]]'', Bolsonaro said that \"I would be incapable of loving a gay son\", and added that he would prefer any gay son of his \"to die in an accident\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://noticias.terra.com.br/brasil/bolsonaro-quotprefiro-filho-morto-em-acidente-a-um-homossexualquot,cf89cc00a90ea310VgnCLD200000bbcceb0aRCRD.html|title=Bolsonaro: \"prefiro filho morto em acidente a um homossexual\"|work=Terra|access-date=2 June 2018|language=pt-BR}}</ref> In the same interview, Bolsonaro said that if a gay couple moved in next door to him, it would lower the market value of his house. In a July 2011 interview with the magazine ''\u00c9poca,'' Bolsonaro said that he would \"fight to prevent the distribution of the 'gay kit'\" [a set of guidelines proposed by [[UNESCO]] to promote the rights of the LGBT community in primary schools] because \"their intention is to promote homosexuality, which is an affront to the family structure, and if that makes me prejudiced, then I'm prejudiced and very proud of it\".<ref name=\"epoca2\"/> In the 2013 BBC documentary ''Out There'', by British actor [[Stephen Fry]], Bolsonaro said that \"no father is ever proud of having a gay son,\" and that \"we Brazilians do not like homosexuals.\"<ref>{{cite AV media|last=novoiluminismo|title=Entrevista \u2013 Jair Bolsonaro e Ang\u00e9lica Ivo [ORIGINAL]|date=17 October 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9TiqyO5JQZs|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2011 interview with ''Jornal de Not\u00edcias'', Bolsonaro linked homosexuality to [[pedophilia]], claiming that \"many of the children who are adopted by gay couples will be abused by these couples\". He further argued that Brazil does not need legislation specifically targeting homophobia, because \"most homosexuals are murdered by their respective pimps at hours when good citizens are already asleep\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Pedro Henrique|last=Fonseca|url=https://www.jn.pt/brasil/interior/deputado-bolsonaro-diz-que-governo-transforma-gays-numa-classe-privilegiada-1879387.html|title=Deputado Bolsonaro diz que Governo transforma gays numa classe privilegiada|website=Jornal de Not\u00edcias|date=21 June 2011|access-date=7 September 2018}}</ref> In a May 2002 interview with the ''[[Folha de S.Paulo]]'', Bolsonaro told the newspaper, \"If I see two men kissing in the street, I will beat them.\" He then publicly defended beating gay children by saying: \"If your child starts to become like that, a little gay, you take a whip and you change their behavior.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/fsp/cotidian/ff2611201025.htm|title=Folha de S.Paulo \u2013 C\u00e2mara: Palmada muda filho \"gayzinho\", declara deputado federal \u2013 26/11/2010|website=1.folha.uol.com.br|access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Beija\u00e7o contra Bolsonaro e Marco Feliciano 2.jpg|thumb|Bolsonaro and his son, Eduardo, together with fellow congressman [[Marco Feliciano]], watching as a couple of protesters for LGBT rights kiss on the floor of the Committee on Culture of the Chamber of Deputies, May 2016]]\nIn a video interview for ''[[Vice Media|Vice]]'' with openly [[lesbian]] actress [[Ellen Page]], Page asked Bolsonaro if he thinks she should have been beaten as a child, in response to his public statements that gay children should be beaten. In response, Bolsonaro said to Page, \"You are very nice. If I were a cadet in the military academy and saw you on the street, I would whistle at you. All right? You are very pretty.\"<ref name=\"advocate.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.advocate.com/world/2016/3/12/watch-ellen-page-confronts-brazils-biggest-homophobe-gaycation|title=WATCH: Ellen Page Confronts Brazil's Biggest Homophobe on 'Gaycation'|date=12 March 2016|access-date=10 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> Bolsonaro added, \"Over time, due to liberal habits, drugs, with women also working, the number of homosexuals has really increased.\"<ref name=\"advocate.com\" />\n\nOn 9 November 2017, the Court of Justice for the State of Rio de Janeiro sentenced Bolsonaro to pay a fine of R$150,000 for [[hate speech]] because of televised comments he made in 2011 to the [[Custe o Que Custar|''CQC'' TV program]], when Bolsonaro stated that \"there is no risk\" of his family producing a homosexual child because his children had a \"good education\". Judge Luciana Teixeira said that the deputy had abused his right of free expression to commit a wrongful act. \"You cannot deliberately attack and humiliate, ignoring the principles of equality, just because you invoke freedom of expression,\" said the judge.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2017/11/1934062-bolsonaro-e-condenado-a-pagar-r-150-mil-por-declaracoes-contra-gays.shtml|title=Bolsonaro \u00e9 condenado a pagar R$ 150 mil por declara\u00e7\u00f5es contra gays|work=Folha de S.Paulo|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\nHowever, on 11 January 2016, when he began to present himself as a pre-candidate to the [[Presidency of Brazil]], Bolsonaro began to moderate his discourse on gay people by publishing a video on his official YouTube channel:\n\n<blockquote>I have nothing to do with anyone's behavior. If the man and the woman later decide to live with their partner, to form a couple, to live with a same-sex person, go and be happy. But we cannot admit that, by our omission in the Parliament, children become homosexuals in the future, or have such homosexual behavior in the future, by the influence of school. That is inadmissible.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mbiNDU3ztyw |publisher = Jair Bolsonaro |type = canal oficial |title= Homofobia?}}</ref> \n</blockquote>\n\nSince then, Bolsonaro claims he has nothing against gays and that he fights only the \"gay kit\" in schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2018/07/bolsonaro-se-diz-vitima-de-noticias-falsas-mas-recorre-a-fakes-sobre-seu-proprio-passado.shtml |title=Bolsonaro se diz v\u00edtima de not\u00edcias falsas, mas recorre a 'fakes' sobre seu pr\u00f3prio passado |publisher=Folha de S. Paulo |date=31 July 2018 |access-date=10 August 2018}}</ref> On 4{{nbsp}}October 2018, for example, Bolsonaro said:\n\n<blockquote>Each person, after a certain age, owner of their acts, will take care of their life. For six-year-old children, it cannot be. A father does not want to come home and see his son playing with a doll by the influence of school. Homosexuals will be happy if I become president.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ultimosegundo.ig.com.br/politica/2018-10-04/bolsonaro-sobre-homossexuais-serao-felizes.html|title=\"Homossexuais ser\u00e3o felizes se eu for presidente\", diz Bolsonaro em entrevista|publisher=[[Internet Group|iG]] |date=4 October 2018 |access-date=10 October 2018}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThat same month, shortly before the first round of the Brazilian presidential elections, he said: \"We are going to make a government for everybody. For gays, and some gays are fathers, who are mothers. It is a work for everyone\".<ref name=\"noticias.uol.com.br\"/> After being elected president, when asked by [[William Bonner (newscaster)|William Bonner]] in the ''[[Jornal Nacional]]'' about what he would say to those who are more prejudiced and aggressive against gays, Bolsonaro replied: \"The aggression against a fellow man has to be punished in the way of law. And if [such aggression is committed] for a reason like this, you have to have your sentence increased.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://g1.globo.com/jornal-nacional/noticia/2018/10/29/presidente-eleito-jair-bolsonaro-e-entrevistado-no-jornal-nacional.ghtml |title=Presidente eleito, Jair Bolsonaro \u00e9 entrevistado no Jornal Nacional |publisher=[[Jornal Nacional]] |date=29 October 2018 |accessdate=6 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Views on political violence ===\n[[File:Plen\u00e1rio do Senado (24998818073).jpg|thumb|upright|Bolsonaro visits the [[Brazilian Senate|Federal Senate]], March 2016.]]\n\nOn multiple occasions, Bolsonaro has publicly endorsed physical violence as a legitimate and necessary form of political action. In 1999, when he was 44 years old and a representative in the Brazilian Congress, Bolsonaro said during a TV interview that the only way of \"changing\" Brazil was by \"killing thirty thousand people, beginning with [[Fernando Henrique Cardoso]]\" (then President of Brazil).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/politica/republica/o-dia-que-bolsonaro-quis-matar-fhc-sonegar-impostos-e-declarar-guerra-civil-8mtm0u0so6pk88kqnqo0n1l69|title=Bolsonaro sincero quis matar FHC e sonegar impostos|website=Gazeta do Povo}}</ref> During the 2018 campaign, he stated during a rally in [[Acre (state)|Acre]] that the local \"petralhas\" (a derogatory term for members of the Workers' Party) would be \"shot\"; according to his aides, the statement was a \"joke\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/brasil/campanha-confirma-video-em-que-bolsonaro-fala-em-fuzilar-petralhada-do-acre-foi-brincadeira-23033857|title=Campanha confirma v\u00eddeo em que Bolsonaro fala em 'fuzilar petralhada do Acre': 'Foi brincadeira'|date=3 September 2018|website=O Globo}}</ref> One week before the second round, Bolsonaro said during a speech that in his administration \"petralhas\" and \"reds\" (i.e. leftists) would be arrested, purged or taken to the \"corner of the beach\", a term that was later revealed to mean a Navy base where dissidents of the [[Brazilian military dictatorship]] were murdered.<ref name=\"uol.com.br\"/>\n\nIn 1999, talking about [[Chico Lopes]], a former president of the Brazilian Central Bank who invoked his right to remain silent during a Congress hearing, Bolsonaro declared himself in favour of torture in this sort of situation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://piaui.folha.uol.com.br/lupa/2018/07/31/bolsonaro-roda-viva/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228185717/https://piaui.folha.uol.com.br/lupa/2018/07/31/bolsonaro-roda-viva/ |archive-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Asked about this phrase years later, Bolsonaro said: \"Ask the father of a kidnapped child what he would like him to do to discover [where the kid is]. You have to take brutal measures, which some consider torture\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2018/10/veja-11-frases-polemicas-de-bolsonaro.shtml|title=Veja 11 frases pol\u00eamicas de Bolsonaro|date=6 October 2018|website=Folha de S.Paulo}}</ref>\n\n=== Birth control for the poor ===\nBolsonaro provoked considerable controversy for public remarks made in July 2008, where he proposed to provide poor people with birth control methods, who he suggested might be too uneducated to understand family planning education. Bolsonaro said:\n\n<blockquote>I wish Brazil had a family planning program. It's not even worthy to talk about education when most of these [poor] people are not prepared to receive education, therefore they won't educate themselves. Only rigid birth control can save us from chaos. An educated man and woman will hardly desire an extra child with the sole purpose of engaging in a social welfare assistance program [as it is nowadays]. We need to adopt a rigid birth control policy. We can't make demagogic speeches any longer, proposing bills and means of government to support these poor people [who] are increasingly proliferating throughout the country. [...] People who aren't prepared to have children, shouldn't have them. This is what I stand for and I'm not worried about getting votes in the future. It's past time to discuss a policy to contain this demographic explosion, otherwise, we'll keep voting in this [[Chamber of Deputies|Chamber]] only matters such as [[Bolsa Fam\u00edlia]], loans for the poor, gas vouchers, etc. Methods [of birth control] have to be provided for those who, unfortunately, are ignorant and have no means to control their offspring. Because we [as upper-middle class] can control ours. Poor people don't control [theirs].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opovo.com.br/noticias/politica/2018/06/bolsonaro-defendeu-esterilizacao-como-forma-de-combater-miseria-e-crim.html|title=Bolsonaro defendeu esteriliza\u00e7\u00e3o de pobres como forma de combater mis\u00e9ria e criminalidade|last=Online|first=O POVO|website=Opovo.com.br|language=pt-br|access-date=15 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/brazil-jair-bolsonaro-stabbing-video-president-candidate-juiz-de-fora-minas-gerais-a8526726.html|title='Brazil's Donald Trump' critically injured in presidential campaign rally stabbing|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-09-16|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/world/2018-06-14-forced-sterilisation-of-brazilian-woman-sparks-uproar/|title='Forced' sterilisation of Brazilian woman sparks uproar|access-date=2018-09-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2018/06/bolsonaro-defendeu-esterilizacao-de-pobres-para-combater-miseria-e-crime.shtml|title=Bolsonaro defendeu esteriliza\u00e7\u00e3o de pobres para combater mis\u00e9ria e crime|date=2018-06-11|work=Folha de S.Paulo|access-date=2018-10-18|language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nAs a Congressman, Bolsonaro put forward three bills trying to remove \"virtually all\" legal restrictions to surgical sterilisation via the public health system, including the reduction of \"the minimum age of sterilization to 21 years\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2018/06/bolsonaro-defendeu-esterilizacao-de-pobres-para-combater-miseria-e-crime.shtml|title=Bolsonaro defendeu esteriliza\u00e7\u00e3o de pobres para combater mis\u00e9ria e crime|date=11 June 2018|website=Folha de S.Paulo}}</ref> None of the bills were voted.\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Bolsonaro e filhos.jpg|thumb|Bolsonaro and two of his sons, Eduardo and Fl\u00e1vio, in the late 1980s]]\nBolsonaro is married to his third wife and has five children. His first wife was Rog\u00e9ria Nantes Braga (with whom he has three sons: [[Fl\u00e1vio Bolsonaro|Fl\u00e1vio]], [[Carlos Bolsonaro|Carlos]] and [[Eduardo Bolsonaro|Eduardo]]). His second marriage was with Ana Cristina Valle (with whom he has one son, Renan). In 2007, he married his third and current wife [[Michelle Bolsonaro|Michelle de Paula Firmo Reinaldo]] (with whom he has a daughter, Laura).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/eleicoes/2018/noticia/2018/10/28/a-mulher-dos-bastidores-saiba-quem-e-michelle-bolsonaro-a-nova-primeira-dama.ghtml|title=A mulher dos bastidores: saiba quem \u00e9 Michelle Bolsonaro, a nova primeira-dama|publisher=G1|language=pt|date=28 October 2018|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com.br/istoegente/65/reportagem/rep_bolsonaro.htm|title=ISTO\u00c9 Gente Online|website=Terra.com.br}}</ref> While working in Congress, Bolsonaro hired Michelle as a secretary and over the next two years she received unusual promotions and her salary more than tripled. He was forced to fire her after the [[Supreme Federal Court]] ruled that [[nepotism]] is illegal in the public administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://universa.uol.com.br/especiais/michelle-bolsonaro/index.htm#tematico-1|title=A bela da fera|website=universa.uol.com.br|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/brasil/bolsonaro-empregou-ex-mulher-parentes-dela-no-legislativo-22143135|title=Bolsonaro empregou ex-mulher e parentes dela no Legislativo|website=O Globo|accessdate=18 October 2018|date=2017-12-03}}</ref> {{as of|2018}}, Bolsonaro and his wife lived in [[Barra da Tijuca]], [[Rio de Janeiro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/politica/ultimas-noticias/2018/12/29/bolsonaro-posa-com-vizinhos-no-rio-antes-de-se-mudar-para-brasilia.htm|title=Bolsonaro posa com vizinhos no Rio antes de se mudar para Bras\u00edlia|website=noticias.uol.com.br|language=pt-br|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref>\n\n== Honours and awards ==\n\n=== National honours ===\n* [[File:BRA Order of the Southern Cross - Grand Cross BAR.png|50x50px]] Grand Master and Grand Collar of the [[Order of the Southern Cross|National Order of the Southern Cross]] (1 January 2019)<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolsonaro concede Ordem Nacional do Cruzeiro do Sul a Netanyahu |url=https://veja.abril.com.br/mundo/bolsonaro-concede-ordem-nacional-do-cruzeiro-do-sul-a-netanyahu|website=Veja |date=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:BRA Ordem de Rio Branco Gra-Cruz BAR.svg|50x50px]] Grand Master and Grand Cross of the [[Order of Rio Branco]] (1 January 2019)<ref>{{cite news |title=Itamaraty foge de padr\u00e3o ao condecorar Eduardo e Fl\u00e1vio Bolsonaro |url=https://www.em.com.br/app/noticia/politica/2019/05/03/interna_politica,1050870/itamaraty-foge-de-padrao-ao-condecorar-eduardo-e-flavio-bolsonaro.shtml|website=Estado de Minas |date=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:Order of Merit for Defence - Grand Cross (Brazil) - ribbon bar.png|50x50px]] Grand Master and Grand Cross of the [[Order of Defence Merit (Brazil)|Order of Defence Merit]] (8 January 2019)<ref>{{cite web |title=Presidente recebe Ordem do M\u00e9rito da Defesa |url=https://www.defesa.gov.br/noticias/51335-ministro-da-defesa-recebe-a-ordem-do-merito-naval-no-grau-gra-cruz |work=Minist\u00e9rio da Defesa |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:BRA Ordem do Merito Militar Gra-cruz.png|50x50px]] Grand Master and Grand Cross of the [[Order of Military Merit (Brazil)|Order of Military Merit]] (16 June 2019)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.defesa.gov.br/noticias/55035-discursos-condecoracoes-e-apresentacoes-marcam-o-dia-do-exercito-em-brasilia |title=Discursos, condecora\u00e7\u00f5es e apresenta\u00e7\u00f5es marcam o Dia do Ex\u00e9rcito em Bras\u00edlia |publisher=defesa.gov.br |date=17 April 2019 |accessdate=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:Brazil Order of Naval Merit.jpg|50x50px]] Grand Master and Grand Cross of the [[Order of Naval Merit (Brazil)|Order of Naval Merit]] (8 January 2019)<ref name=\"Medalhas\" />\n* [[File:BRA Ordem do M\u00e9rito Aeron\u00e1utico Gr\u00e3-Cruz.png|50x50px]] Grand Master and Grand Cross of the [[Order of Aeronautical Merit (Brazil)|Order of Aeronautical Merit]] (3 January 2019)<ref name=\"Medalhas\">{{cite web|title=Ap\u00f3s Aeron\u00e1utica e Ex\u00e9rcito, Bolsonaro \u00e9 homenageado pela Marinha|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/politica/ultimas-noticias/2019/01/08/apos-aeronautica-e-exercito-bolsonaro-e-homenageado-pela-marinha.htm|work=noticias.uol.com.br|accessdate=2019-06-27|language=pt-br}}</ref>\n*[[File:Ordem do M\u00e9rito Judici\u00e1rio do Trabalho - Gr\u00e3-Cruz (Brasil).png|50x50px]] Grand Collar of the [[Order of Labor Judicial Merit]] (13 August 2019)<ref>{{cite web|title=TST entrega comenda da Ordem do M\u00e9rito Judici\u00e1rio do Trabalho 2019 - Not\u00edcias - TST|url=http://www.tst.jus.br/web/guest/noticias/-/asset_publisher/89Dk/content/tst-entrega-comenda-da-ordem-do-merito-judiciario-do-trabalho-2019?inheritRedirect=false&redirect=http://www.tst.jus.br/web/guest/noticias?p_p_id=101_INSTANCE_89Dk&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=column-2&p_p_col_count=2|work=www.tst.jus.br|accessdate=2019-08-19}}</ref>\n* [[File:Ordem do m\u00e9rito judiciario militar.png|50x50px]] Grand Cross of the [[Order of Military Judicial Merit]] (28 March 2019)<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolsonaro recebe, em Bras\u00edlia, homenagem da Justi\u00e7a Militar|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2019-03/bolsonaro-recebe-em-brasilia-homenagem-da-justica-militar|website=EBC |date=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:Medalha do m\u00e9rito Mau\u00e1.png|50x50px]] The [[Mau\u00e1 Medal of Merit]] (15 August 2019)<ref name=\"Reda\u00e7\u00e3o\">{{cite web|title=\"Existe abuso, mas n\u00e3o pode cercear o trabalho das institui\u00e7\u00f5es\", diz Bolsonaro|url=https://odocumento.com.br/existe-abuso-mas-nao-pode-cercear-o-trabalho-das-instituicoes-diz-bolsonaro/|work=O Documento|date=2019-08-15|accessdate=2019-08-19|language=pt-BR|first=Da|last=Reda\u00e7\u00e3o}}</ref>\n* [[File:Medalha do Pacificador.png|50x50px]] The [[Peacemaker Medal]] (5 December 2018)<ref name=\"Reda\u00e7\u00e3o\"/>\n\n=== Awards ===\n* One of the world's 100 most influential people by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine (17 April 2019)<ref name=\"time\">{{cite web|url=http://time.com/collection/100-most-influential-people-2019/|publisher=time.com|title=Most influential people 2019|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"timeg1\">{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/mundo/noticia/2019/04/17/bolsonaro-aparece-na-lista-dos-100-mais-influentes-da-revista-time-em-2019.ghtml|publisher=g1.globo.com|title=Bolsonaro aparece na lista dos '100 mais influentes' da revista 'Time' em 2019|accessdate=26 April 2019|language=portuguese}}</ref>\n* Person of the Year of Brazilian-American Chamber of Commerce (14 May 2019)<ref>{{cite news |title=2019 Person of the Year Awards |url=https://brazilcham.com/event/2019-person-of-the-year-awards-gala-dinner |website=Brazilcham |date=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n\n=== Presidential ===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Election\n!colspan=4|First round\n!colspan=4|Second round\n|-\n!Votes\n!%\n!Position\n!Result\n!Votes\n!%\n!Position\n!Result\n|-\n! [[2018 Brazilian general election|2018]]\n| 49,276,990\n| 46.0\n| #1\n| '''Run-off'''\n| 57,797,847\n| 55.1\n| #1\n| '''Elected'''\n|}\n\n=== Chamber of Deputies ===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Election\n|-\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!Position in Rio de Janeiro State\n!Result\n|-\n! [[1990 Brazilian legislative election|1990]]\n| [[Christian Democratic Party (Brazil)|PDC]]\n| \n| \n| \n| Elected<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/brasil-42231485 | title=Como o discurso de Bolsonaro mudou ao longo de 27 anos na C\u00e2mara?| newspaper=BBC News Brasil| date=2017-12-07| last1=Shalders - @Shaldim| first1=Andr\u00e9}}</ref>\n|-\n![[1994 Brazilian general election|1994]]\n|[[Reform Progressive Party|PPR]]\n| 111,927\n| 2.5\n| #3\n| Elected<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tse.jus.br/eleicoes/eleicoes-anteriores/eleicoes-1994/resultados-das-eleicoes-1994/rio-de-janeiro/resultados-das-eleicoes-1994-rio-de-janeiro-deputado-federal|tit